{"title_page": "Nama people", "text_new": "{{More footnotes|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use South African English|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group=Nama <br> <small>Namaqua</small>\n|image=Nama man greeting us (3693359757).jpg\n|image_caption = A Nama man of [[Namibia]].\n|population=\n|popplace= {{flag|Namibia}}<br>{{flag|Botswana}}<br>{{flag|South Africa}}\n|region1={{flag|Namibia}}\n|pop1=130,349\n|langs= [[Nama language|Nama]], [[Afrikaans language|Afrikaans]], [[English language|English]]\n|rels=[[Christianity]], [[African Traditional Religion]], [[Islam]]\n|related= [[Khoekhoe people]]\n}}\n{{Contains Khoekhoe text}}\n\n'''Nama''' (in older sources also called '''Namaqua''') are an African [[ethnic group]] of South Africa, Namibia and [[Botswana]]. They traditionally speak the [[Khoekhoe language|Nama language]] of the [[Khoe languages|Khoe-Kwadi]] language family, although many Nama also speak [[Afrikaans]]. The Nama People (or Nama-Khoe people) are the largest group of the [[Khoikhoi]] people, most of whom have largely disappeared as a group, except for the Namas. Many of the Nama clans live in Central Namibia and the other smaller groups live in [[Namaqualand]], which today straddles the Namibian border with South Africa.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 105-DSWA0093, Deutsch-S\u00fcdwestafrika, Namafamilie.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Nama group in front of a hut]]\n[[File:Kaptain hendrik wittboi mit seinem stabe.jpg|thumbnail|left|250px|Chief ''[[Hendrik Witbooi (Namaqua chief)|Hendrik Witbooi]]'' (centre) and his companions]]\nFor thousands of years, the [[Khoisan]] peoples of South Africa and southern Namibia maintained a [[nomad]]ic life, the [[Khoikhoi]] as pastoralists and the [[San people]] as hunter-gatherers. The Nama are a Khoikhoi group. The Nama originally lived around the [[Orange River]] in southern Namibia and northern South Africa. The early colonialists referred to them as [[Khoikhoi|Hottentots]]. Their alternative historical name, \"Namaqua\", stems from the addition of the [[Khoekhoe language]] suffix ''\"-qua/khwa\"'', meaning \"people\" (found in the names of other Southern African nations like the [[Griqua people|Griqua]]), to the language name.\n\nFrom 1904 to 1908, the German Empire, which had colonised present-day [[Namibia]], waged a war against the Nama and the [[Herero people|Herero]] (a group of Bantu pastoralists), leading to the [[Herero and Namaqua genocide]] and a large loss of life for both the Nama and Herero populations.<ref>{{cite web\n|title=The Herero genocide: German unity, settlers, soldiers, and ideas\n|url=https://openaccess.leidenuniv.nl/bitstream/handle/1887/4844/ASC-1293873-017.pdf?sequence=1 |accessdate=17 January 2014}} \"When the war finally ended in 1908 no less than 80% of the Herero had lost their lives. The majority of the Herero who remained in Namibia, primarily women and children, survived in [[concentration camp]]s as forced labourers employed on state, military and civilian projects (Pool 1979; Nuhn 1989; Bley 1971:142\u2013169; Drechsler 1966:132-167; Gewald 1999:141-230).</ref> This was motivated by the German desire to establish a prosperous colony which required displacing the indigenous people from their agricultural land.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}} Large herds of cattle were confiscated and Nama and Herero people were driven into the desert and in some cases interned in concentration camps on the coast,{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}} for example at [[Shark Island Concentration Camp|Shark Island]].  Additionally, the Nama and Herero were forced into slave labour to build railways and to dig for diamonds during the [[diamond rush]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nIn the 1920s diamonds were discovered at the mouth of the [[Orange River]], and prospectors began moving there, establishing towns at Alexander Bay and [[Port Nolloth]]. This accelerated the appropriation of traditional lands that had begun early in the colonial period.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}} Under [[apartheid]], remaining pastoralists were encouraged to abandon their traditional lifestyle in favour of village life.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nIn 1991, a part of [[Namaqualand]] (home of the Nama and one of the last true wilderness areas of South Africa) was named the [[Richtersveld National Park]]. In December 2002, ancestral lands, including the park, were returned to community ownership and the governments of South Africa and Namibia began creating a trans-frontier park from the west coast of southern Africa to the desert interior, absorbing the Richtersveld National Park.  Today, the Richtersveld National Park is one of the few places where the original Nama traditions survive. There, the Nama move with the seasons and speak their language. The traditional Nama dwelling \u2013 the |haru oms, or portable rush-mat covered domed hut \u2013 protects against the blistering sun, and is easy to move when grazing becomes scarce.\n\nAt the dawn of the 19th century, [[Oorlam people]] encroached into Namaqualand and [[Damaraland]]. They likewise descended from [[indigenous peoples|indigenous]] Khoikhoi but were a group with mixed ancestry including Europeans and slaves from [[Madagascar]], India, and [[Indonesia]].<ref name=\"Slavery\">{{cite web\n |title       = Slavery in the Cape\n |publisher   = Institute for the Study of Slavery and its Legacy \u2013 South Africa\n |url         = http://slaveryinstitute.wordpress.com/slavery-in-the-cape/\n |accessdate  = 8 July 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20100610194604/http://slaveryinstitute.wordpress.com/slavery-in-the-cape/\n |archivedate = 10 June 2010\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> After two centuries of assimilation into the Nama culture, many Oorlams today regard [[Khoekhoe language|Khoikhoigowab]] (Damara/Nama) as their mother tongue, though others speak [[Afrikaans]]. The distinction between Namas and Oorlams has gradually disappeared over time to an extent where they are today regarded as one ethnic group, despite their different ancestries.<ref name=\"Malan\">{{cite book\n|last=Malan\n|first=Johan S\n|title=Die V\u00f6lker Namibias\n|trans-title=The Tribes of Namibia\n|year=1998\n|publisher=Klaus Hess\n|location=Windhoek, G\u00f6ttingen\n|language=German\n|pages=120\u2013125}}</ref>\n\n==Nama clans==\n* \u01c0Khowesen (Direct descendants of Captain [[Hendrik Witbooi (Namaqua chief)|Hendrik Witbooi]]) who was killed in the battle with Germans in 1905 29 October. The |Khowesin, recite in modern-day [[Gibeon, Namibia|Gibeon]] under the leadership of [[Ismael Hendrik Witbooi]] the 9th Gaob (meaning captain) of the |Khowesen [[Gibeon, Namibia|Gibeon]], situated 72&nbsp;km south of [[Mariental, Namibia|Mariental]] and 176&nbsp;km north of [[Keetmanshoop]] just off the B1, was originally known by the name [[Khaxa-ts\u00fbs]]. It received its name from [[Kido Witbooi]] first Kaptein of the \u01c0Khowesin.\n* Khai\u01c1khaun ([[Red Nation, Namibia|Red Nation]]) at [[Hoachanas]], the main group and the oldest Nama clan in Namibia<ref name=KDNama>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.republikein.com.na/politiek-en-nasionale/the-historical-role-of-the-nama-nation.45136.php\n|title=The historical role of the Nama nation\n|last=Dierks\n|first=Klaus\n|authorlink=Klaus Dierks\n|date=3 December 2004\n|newspaper=[[Die Republikein]]\n|accessdate=8 July 2011}}</ref>\n* \u01c3Gami\u01c2nun ([[Bondelswarts]]) at [[Warmbad, Namibia|Warmbad]]\n* \u01c2Aonin (Southern [[Topnaar]]s) at [[Rooibank]]\n* \u01c3Gomen (Northern Topnaars) at [[Sesfontein]]\n* \u01c3Kharakhoen ([[Fransman Nama]]) at [[Gochas]]. After being defeated by [[German Empire|Imperial Germany]]{{'s}} ''[[Schutztruppe]]'' in the Battle of Swartfontein on 15 January 1905, this Nama group split into two. Part of the \u01c3Kharakhoen fled to [[Lokgwabe]], Botswana, and stayed there permanently,<ref>{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.namibiansun.com/content/national-news/bridging-hundred-year-old-separation\n |title       = Bridging a hundred year-old separation\n |last        = Goeieman\n |first       = Fred\n |date        = 30 November 2011\n |work        = [[Namibian Sun]]\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20131029195955/http://www.namibiansun.com/content/national-news/bridging-hundred-year-old-separation\n |archivedate = 29 October 2013\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> the part that remained on South West African soil relocated their tribal centre to [[Amper-Bo]]. In 2016 [[David Hanse]] was inaugurated as chief of the clan.<ref>{{Cite news | title=\u01c3Khara-Khoen Nama sub-clan installs leader | last=Cloete | first=Luqman | newspaper=[[The Namibian]] | date=2 February 2016 | url=http://www.namibian.com.na/index.php?page=read&id=36666}}</ref>\n* \u01c1Hawoben ([[Veldschoendragers]]) at [[Ko\u00ebs]]\n* !Aman   at  [[Bethanie]] which was led by Cornelius Frederick\n* \u01c1Ogain ([[Groot Doden]]) at [[Schlip]]\n* \u01c1Khau\u01c0goan ([[Swartbooi Nama]]) at [[Rehoboth, Namibia|Rehoboth]], later at [[Salem, Namibia|Salem]], [[Ameib]], and [[Franzfontein]]\n* The Kharo\u01c3oan ([[Keetmanshoop Nama]]) under the leadership of [[Hendrik Tseib]]<ref name=\"Keetmanshoop\">{{cite news\n|title=Aus \"\u01c2Nu\u01c2goaes\" wird Keetmanshoop\n|trans-title=\"\u01c2Nu\u01c2goaes\" becomes Keetmanshoop\n|language=German\n|last=von Schmettau\n|first=Konny\n|date=28 February 2013\n|work=[[Allgemeine Zeitung (Namibia)|Allgemeine Zeitung]]\n|publisher=Tourismus Namibia monthly supplement\n|page=10}}</ref> split from the Red Nation in February 1850 and settled at [[Keetmanshoop]].<ref name=KDNama/>\n\n==Culture==\n[[File:Nama huts.JPG|thumb|300px|Nama huts.]]\nIn general the Nama practice a policy of communal land ownership. Music, poetry and story telling are very important in Nama culture and many stories have been passed down orally through the generations.\n\nThe Nama have a culture that is rich in the musical and literary abilities of its people. Traditional music, folk tales, proverbs, and praise poetry have been handed down for generations and form the base for much of their culture. They are known for crafts which include leatherwork, skin [[kaross]]es and mats, musical instruments (such as reed flutes), jewellery, clay pots, and tortoiseshell powder containers.\n\nMany of the Nama people in South Namibia have lost their lands during German colonialism. New Namibian minister of land reform, Uutoni Nujoma has been accused of preferring other Namibians from other regions over native Namas.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newera.com.na/2016/12/14/swartbooi-resigned-not-fired-kapofi/|title=Swartbooi resigned, not fired|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=|via=}}</ref>\n\n===Dress===\nThe traditional dress of Nama women consists of long, formal dresses that resemble Victorian traditional fashion. The long, flowing dresses were developed from the style of the missionaries in the 1800s, and this traditional clothing is today an integral part of the Nama nation's culture.\n\n===Religion===\nThey have largely abandoned their traditional religion through the sustained efforts of Christian (and now Muslim) proselytisers. The majority of the Nama people in [[Namibia]] today are therefore Christian while [[Islam in Namibia|Nama Muslim]]s make up a large percentage of the Namibia's Muslims.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.islamonline.net/?p=18129|title=Islam in Namibia, making an impact|publisher=Islamonline.net}}</ref>\n\n===Wedding ritual===\n[[File:White flag in yard.jpg|thumb|A house in Windhoek's Hochland Park suburb. The white flag indicates marriage arrangements are in place.]]\n\nNamas have a complicated wedding ritual. First the man has to discuss his intentions with his family. If they agree they will advise him of the customs to ask the bride's family and then accompany him to the place she lives. The yard at the bride's living place is prepared prior to the future husband's family's arrival, animal hides are laid out in the corners for the different groups to sit down and discuss.<ref name=wedding>{{cite news\n|title=Love, traditionally \u2013 a \u01c0Hai\u01c0Khaua wedding\n|last=Sasman\n|first=Catherine\n|newspaper=[[New Era (Namibia)|New Era]]\n|date=3 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe groom's family ask for the gate to be opened. If this is granted, the groom is interrogated about details of the bride, including the circumstances of their first meeting and how to identify her body marks to make sure both know each other well. If the bride is pregnant or already has children from her future husband or someone else, the bride is subjected to the \"door cleansing\" ceremony (slaughtering and consuming a snow-white goat). After several days the wedding ritual continues in reverse; the bride's family visits the clan of the groom. If all is to the satisfaction of the two clans, an engagement day is announced.<ref name=wedding/>\n\nAt the engagement, the groom's family brings live animals to the woman's family home. The animals are slaughtered, hung on three sticks, and each part is offered to the bride's family. Other items like bags of sugar or flour are only offered in quantities of two or four to indicate that there will always be abundance of food. This process is also celebrated in reverse at the man's family home. White flags are mounted on both families' houses which may not be taken off but wither or are blown off by the wind one day.<ref name=wedding/>\n\nThe wedding preparations can take up to one year. The family of the groom makes a gift to the bride's mother, traditionally a cow and a calf, for she has raised the bride at her breast. A bargaining process accompanies the gift that can take weeks in itself. On wedding day, both families provide animals and other food and bring it to the bride's home. The wedding itself takes place in a church. Festivities afterward go on for several days. The first night after the wedding the couple spends separately. On the next morning, they set off for their own home.<ref name=wedding/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Democratic Action for Namas]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Literature==\n*Hoernl\u00e9\u201a A. W. (1925) \"The Social Organisation of the Nama Hottentots\", ''American Anthropologist'', New Series, Vol.27 No.1 pp.&nbsp;1\u201324 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/661495 JSTOR]\n*Hoernl\u00e9\u201a A. W. (1918) \"Certain Rites of Transition and the Conception of !Nau among the Hottentots\", in Oric Bates (1918) ''Harvard African Studies II; Varia Africana II'', pp.&nbsp;65\u201382, Cambridge, Massachusetts. (Review by: Robert H. Lowie (Apr. - Jun., 1919) ''American Anthropologist'',  New Series, Vol. 21, No. 2, pp.&nbsp;208\u2013210 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/660280 JSTOR])\n* Schultze, Leonhard (1907) [https://books.google.com/books?id=oSIPAAAAYAAJ ''Aus Namaland und Kalahari''], Gustav Fischer Verlag, Jena {{oclc|470637064}} {{in lang|de}}\n* Leonhard Schultze et al. (1970) ''In Namaland and the Kalahari'', Human Relations Area Files, New Haven, Conn.  {{oclc|37146594}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.sanparks.org/parks/richtersveld/ South African National Parks website]\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Botswana}}\n{{Ethnic groups in Namibia}}\n{{Ethnic groups in South Africa}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Nama people| ]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Namibia]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Botswana]]\n[[Category:African nomads]]\n", "text_old": "{{More footnotes|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use South African English|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group=Nama <br> <small>Namaqua</small>\n|image=Nama man greeting us (3693359757).jpg\n|image_caption = A Nama man of [[Namibia]].\n|population=\n|popplace= {{flag|Namibia}}<br>{{flag|Botswana}}<br>{{flag|South Africa}}\n|region1={{flag|Namibia}}\n|pop1=130,349\n|langs= [[Nama language|Nama]], [[Afrikaans language|Afrikaans]], [[English language|English]]\n|rels=[[Christianity]], [[African Traditional Religion]], [[Islam]]\n|related= [[Khoekhoe people]]\n}}\n{{Contains Khoekhoe text}}\n\n'''Nama''' (in older sources also called '''Namaqua''') are an African [[ethnic group]] of South Africa, Namibia and [[Botswana]]. They traditionally speak the [[Khoekhoe language|Nama language]] of the [[Khoe languages|Khoe-Kwadi]] language family, although many Nama also speak [[Afrikaans]]. The Nama People (or Nama-Khoe people) are the largest group of the [[Khoikhoi]] people, most of whom have largely disappeared as a group, except for the Namas. Many of the Nama clans live in Central Namibia and the other smaller groups live in [[Namaqualand]], which today straddles the Namibian border with South Africa.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 105-DSWA0093, Deutsch-S\u00fcdwestafrika, Namafamilie.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Nama group in front of a hut]]\n[[File:Kaptain hendrik wittboi mit seinem stabe.jpg|thumbnail|left|250px|Chief ''[[Hendrik Witbooi (Namaqua chief)|Hendrik Witbooi]]'' (centre) and his companions]]\nFor thousands of years, the [[Khoisan]] peoples of South Africa and southern Namibia maintained a [[nomad]]ic life, the [[Khoikhoi]] as pastoralists and the [[San people]] as hunter-gatherers. The Nama are a Khoikhoi group. The Nama originally lived around the [[Orange River]] in southern Namibia and northern South Africa. The early colonialists referred to them as [[Khoikhoi|Hottentots]]. Their alternative historical name, \"Namaqua\", stems from the addition of the [[Khoekhoe language]] suffix ''\"-qua/khwa\"'', meaning \"people\" (found in the names of other Southern African nations like the [[Griqua people|Griqua]]), to the language name.\n\nFrom 1904 to 1908, the German Empire, which had colonised present-day [[Namibia]], waged a war against the Nama and the [[Herero people|Herero]] (a group of Bantu pastoralists), leading to the [[Herero and Namaqua genocide]] and a large loss of life for both the Nama and Herero populations.<ref>{{cite web\n|title=The Herero genocide: German unity, settlers, soldiers, and ideas\n|url=https://openaccess.leidenuniv.nl/bitstream/handle/1887/4844/ASC-1293873-017.pdf?sequence=1 |accessdate=17 January 2014}} \"When the war finally ended in 1908 no less than 80% of the Herero had lost their lives. The majority of the Herero who remained in Namibia, primarily women and children, survived in [[concentration camp]]s as forced labourers employed on state, military and civilian projects (Pool 1979; Nuhn 1989; Bley 1971:142\u2013169; Drechsler 1966:132-167; Gewald 1999:141-230).</ref> This was motivated by the German desire to establish a prosperous colony which required displacing the indigenous people from their agricultural land.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}} Large herds of cattle were confiscated and Nama and Herero people were driven into the desert and in some cases interned in concentration camps on the coast,{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}} for example at [[Shark Island Concentration Camp|Shark Island]].  Additionally, the Nama and Herero were forced into slave labour to build railways and to dig for diamonds during the [[diamond rush]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nIn the 1920s diamonds were discovered at the mouth of the [[Orange River]], and prospectors began moving there, establishing towns at Alexander Bay and [[Port Nolloth]]. This accelerated the appropriation of traditional lands that had begun early in the colonial period.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}} Under [[apartheid]], remaining pastoralists were encouraged to abandon their traditional lifestyle in favour of village life.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nIn 1991, a part of [[Namaqualand]] (home of the Nama and one of the last true wilderness areas of South Africa) was named the [[Richtersveld National Park]]. In December 2002, ancestral lands, including the park, were returned to community ownership and the governments of South Africa and Namibia began creating a trans-frontier park from the west coast of southern Africa to the desert interior, absorbing the Richtersveld National Park.  Today, the Richtersveld National Park is one of the few places where the original Nama traditions survive. There, the Nama move with the seasons and speak their language. The traditional Nama dwelling \u2013 the |haru oms, or portable rush-mat covered domed hut \u2013 protects against the blistering sun, and is easy to move when grazing becomes scarce.\n\nAt the dawn of the 19th century, [[Oorlam people]] encroached into Namaqualand and [[Damaraland]]. They likewise descended from [[indigenous peoples|indigenous]] Khoikhoi but were a group with mixed ancestry including Europeans and slaves from [[Madagascar]], India, and [[Indonesia]].<ref name=\"Slavery\">{{cite web\n |title       = Slavery in the Cape\n |publisher   = Institute for the Study of Slavery and its Legacy \u2013 South Africa\n |url         = http://slaveryinstitute.wordpress.com/slavery-in-the-cape/\n |accessdate  = 8 July 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20100610194604/http://slaveryinstitute.wordpress.com/slavery-in-the-cape/\n |archivedate = 10 June 2010\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> After two centuries of assimilation into the Nama culture, many Oorlams today regard [[Khoekhoe language|Khoikhoigowab]] (Damara/Nama) as their mother tongue, though others speak [[Afrikaans]]. The distinction between Namas and Oorlams has gradually disappeared over time to an extent where they are today regarded as one ethnic group, despite their different ancestries.<ref name=\"Malan\">{{cite book\n|last=Malan\n|first=Johan S\n|title=Die V\u00f6lker Namibias\n|trans-title=The Tribes of Namibia\n|year=1998\n|publisher=Klaus Hess\n|location=Windhoek, G\u00f6ttingen\n|language=German\n|pages=120\u2013125}}</ref>\n\n==Nama clans==\n* \u01c0Khowesen (Direct descendants of Captain [[Hendrik Witbooi (Namaqua chief)|Hendrik Witbooi]]) who was killed in the battle with Germans in 1905 29 October. The |Khowesin, recite in modern day [[Gibeon, Namibia|Gibeon]] under the leadership of [[Ismael Hendrik Witbooi]] the 9th Gaob (meaning captain) of the |Khowesen [[Gibeon, Namibia|Gibeon]], situated 72&nbsp;km south of [[Mariental, Namibia|Mariental]] and 176&nbsp;km north of [[Keetmanshoop]] just off the B1, was originally known by the name [[Khaxa-ts\u00fbs]]. It received its name from [[Kido Witbooi]] first Kaptein of the \u01c0Khowesin.\n* Khai\u01c1khaun ([[Red Nation, Namibia|Red Nation]]) at [[Hoachanas]], the main group and the oldest Nama clan in Namibia<ref name=KDNama>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.republikein.com.na/politiek-en-nasionale/the-historical-role-of-the-nama-nation.45136.php\n|title=The historical role of the Nama nation\n|last=Dierks\n|first=Klaus\n|authorlink=Klaus Dierks\n|date=3 December 2004\n|newspaper=[[Die Republikein]]\n|accessdate=8 July 2011}}</ref>\n* \u01c3Gami\u01c2nun ([[Bondelswarts]]) at [[Warmbad, Namibia|Warmbad]]\n* \u01c2Aonin (Southern [[Topnaar]]s) at [[Rooibank]]\n* \u01c3Gomen (Northern Topnaars) at [[Sesfontein]]\n* \u01c3Kharakhoen ([[Fransman Nama]]) at [[Gochas]]. After being defeated by [[German Empire|Imperial Germany]]{{'s}} ''[[Schutztruppe]]'' in the Battle of Swartfontein on 15 January 1905, this Nama group split into two. Part of the \u01c3Kharakhoen fled to [[Lokgwabe]], Botswana, and stayed there permanently,<ref>{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.namibiansun.com/content/national-news/bridging-hundred-year-old-separation\n |title       = Bridging a hundred year-old separation\n |last        = Goeieman\n |first       = Fred\n |date        = 30 November 2011\n |work        = [[Namibian Sun]]\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20131029195955/http://www.namibiansun.com/content/national-news/bridging-hundred-year-old-separation\n |archivedate = 29 October 2013\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> the part that remained on South West African soil relocated their tribal centre to [[Amper-Bo]]. In 2016 [[David Hanse]] was inaugurated as chief of the clan.<ref>{{Cite news | title=\u01c3Khara-Khoen Nama sub-clan installs leader | last=Cloete | first=Luqman | newspaper=[[The Namibian]] | date=2 February 2016 | url=http://www.namibian.com.na/index.php?page=read&id=36666}}</ref>\n* \u01c1Hawoben ([[Veldschoendragers]]) at [[Ko\u00ebs]]\n* !Aman   at  [[Bethanie]] which was led by Cornelius Frederick\n* \u01c1Ogain ([[Groot Doden]]) at [[Schlip]]\n* \u01c1Khau\u01c0goan ([[Swartbooi Nama]]) at [[Rehoboth, Namibia|Rehoboth]], later at [[Salem, Namibia|Salem]], [[Ameib]], and [[Franzfontein]]\n* The Kharo\u01c3oan ([[Keetmanshoop Nama]]) under the leadership of [[Hendrik Tseib]]<ref name=\"Keetmanshoop\">{{cite news\n|title=Aus \"\u01c2Nu\u01c2goaes\" wird Keetmanshoop\n|trans-title=\"\u01c2Nu\u01c2goaes\" becomes Keetmanshoop\n|language=German\n|last=von Schmettau\n|first=Konny\n|date=28 February 2013\n|work=[[Allgemeine Zeitung (Namibia)|Allgemeine Zeitung]]\n|publisher=Tourismus Namibia monthly supplement\n|page=10}}</ref> split from the Red Nation in February 1850 and settled at [[Keetmanshoop]].<ref name=KDNama/>\n\n==Culture==\n[[File:Nama huts.JPG|thumb|300px|Nama huts.]]\nIn general the Nama practice a policy of communal land ownership. Music, poetry and story telling are very important in Nama culture and many stories have been passed down orally through the generations.\n\nThe Nama have a culture that is rich in the musical and literary abilities of its people. Traditional music, folk tales, proverbs, and praise poetry have been handed down for generations and form the base for much of their culture. They are known for crafts which include leatherwork, skin [[kaross]]es and mats, musical instruments (such as reed flutes), jewellery, clay pots, and tortoiseshell powder containers.\n\nMany of the Nama people in South Namibia have lost their lands during German colonialism. New Namibian minister of land reform, Uutoni Nujoma has been accused of preferring other Namibians from other regions over native Namas.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newera.com.na/2016/12/14/swartbooi-resigned-not-fired-kapofi/|title=Swartbooi resigned, not fired|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=|via=}}</ref>\n\n===Dress===\nThe traditional dress of Nama women consists of long, formal dresses that resemble Victorian traditional fashion. The long, flowing dresses were developed from the style of the missionaries in the 1800s, and this traditional clothing is today an integral part of the Nama nation's culture.\n\n===Religion===\nThey have largely abandoned their traditional religion through the sustained efforts of Christian (and now Muslim) proselytisers. The majority of the Nama people in [[Namibia]] today are therefore Christian while [[Islam in Namibia|Nama Muslim]]s make up a large percentage of the Namibia's Muslims.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.islamonline.net/?p=18129|title=Islam in Namibia, making an impact|publisher=Islamonline.net}}</ref>\n\n===Wedding ritual===\n[[File:White flag in yard.jpg|thumb|A house in Windhoek's Hochland Park suburb. The white flag indicates marriage arrangements are in place.]]\n\nNamas have a complicated wedding ritual. First the man has to discuss his intentions with his family. If they agree they will advise him of the customs to ask the bride's family and then accompany him to the place she lives. The yard at the bride's living place is prepared prior to the future husband's family's arrival, animal hides are laid out in the corners for the different groups to sit down and discuss.<ref name=wedding>{{cite news\n|title=Love, traditionally \u2013 a \u01c0Hai\u01c0Khaua wedding\n|last=Sasman\n|first=Catherine\n|newspaper=[[New Era (Namibia)|New Era]]\n|date=3 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe groom's family ask for the gate to be opened. If this is granted, the groom is interrogated about details of the bride, including the circumstances of their first meeting and how to identify her body marks to make sure both know each other well. If the bride is pregnant or already has children from her future husband or someone else, the bride is subjected to the \"door cleansing\" ceremony (slaughtering and consuming a snow-white goat). After several days the wedding ritual continues in reverse; the bride's family visits the clan of the groom. If all is to the satisfaction of the two clans, an engagement day is announced.<ref name=wedding/>\n\nAt the engagement, the groom's family brings live animals to the woman's family home. The animals are slaughtered, hung on three sticks, and each part is offered to the bride's family. Other items like bags of sugar or flour are only offered in quantities of two or four to indicate that there will always be abundance of food. This process is also celebrated in reverse at the man's family home. White flags are mounted on both families' houses which may not be taken off but wither or are blown off by the wind one day.<ref name=wedding/>\n\nThe wedding preparations can take up to one year. The family of the groom makes a gift to the bride's mother, traditionally a cow and a calf, for she has raised the bride at her breast. A bargaining process accompanies the gift that can take weeks in itself. On wedding day, both families provide animals and other food and bring it to the bride's home. The wedding itself takes place in a church. Festivities afterward go on for several days. The first night after the wedding the couple spends separately. On the next morning, they set off for their own home.<ref name=wedding/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Democratic Action for Namas]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Literature==\n*Hoernl\u00e9\u201a A. W. (1925) \"The Social Organisation of the Nama Hottentots\", ''American Anthropologist'', New Series, Vol.27 No.1 pp.&nbsp;1\u201324 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/661495 JSTOR]\n*Hoernl\u00e9\u201a A. W. (1918) \"Certain Rites of Transition and the Conception of !Nau among the Hottentots\", in Oric Bates (1918) ''Harvard African Studies II; Varia Africana II'', pp.&nbsp;65\u201382, Cambridge, Massachusetts. (Review by: Robert H. Lowie (Apr. - Jun., 1919) ''American Anthropologist'',  New Series, Vol. 21, No. 2, pp.&nbsp;208\u2013210 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/660280 JSTOR])\n* Schultze, Leonhard (1907) [https://books.google.com/books?id=oSIPAAAAYAAJ ''Aus Namaland und Kalahari''], Gustav Fischer Verlag, Jena {{oclc|470637064}} {{in lang|de}}\n* Leonhard Schultze et al. (1970) ''In Namaland and the Kalahari'', Human Relations Area Files, New Haven, Conn.  {{oclc|37146594}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.sanparks.org/parks/richtersveld/ South African National Parks website]\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Botswana}}\n{{Ethnic groups in Namibia}}\n{{Ethnic groups in South Africa}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Nama people| ]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Namibia]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Botswana]]\n[[Category:African nomads]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNama clans:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: modern day \u2192 modern-day", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nama_people"}
{"title_page": "Rosa Manch\u00f3n", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Rosa M. Manch\u00f3n\n| image = File:Rosa Manchon.jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1957|07|06|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Murcia]], [[Spain]]\n| residence = [[Murcia]], [[Spain]]\n| fields = {{plainlist |\n*[[Second language acquisition]]\n* [[Second language writing]]\n  }}\n| workplaces = {{plainlist |\n* [[University of Murcia]]\n  }}\n| alma_mater = \n| doctoral_advisor = \n| thesis_title = \n| thesis_url = \n| thesis_year = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for = {{plainlist |\n*Second language writing\n  }}\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| awards = \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| religion = \n| website = {{URL|https://www.um.es/web/filologia-inglesa/contenido/pdi|Manch\u00f3n on the website of the University of Murcia}}\n}}\n\n'''Rosa Mar\u00eda Manch\u00f3n Ruiz''' (born 1957) is a [[Spanish people|Spanish]] [[linguist]]. She is currently a professor of [[applied linguistics]] at the [[University of Murcia]], [[Spain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.um.es/web/filologia-inglesa/contenido/pdi|title=Manch\u00f3n - University of Murcia|date=7 September 2018|publisher=Universidad de Murcia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n2009027290/|title=Manch\u00f3n on Worldcat|date=23 November 2018|publisher=[[WorldCat]]}}</ref> Her research focuses on [[second language acquisition]] and [[second language writing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://slw4sla.weebly.com/rosa-m-manchoacuten.html|title=Second Language Writing for SLA|date=7 September 2018|publisher=SLW4SLA}}</ref> She was the editor of the ''[[Journal of Second Language Writing]]'' between 2008 and 2014.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://www.journals.elsevier.com/journal-of-second-language-writing|title=Journal of Second Language Writing|date=7 September 2018|publisher=Journals Elsevier}}</ref> \nAlong with [[Alister Cumming|Cumming]], [[Ken Hyland|Hyland]], [[Judit Kormos|Kormos]], [[Paul Kei Matsuda|Matsuda]], [[Lourdes Ortega|Ortega]], [[Charlene Polio|Polio]], [[Neomy Storch]] and [[Marjolijn Verspoor|Verspoor]], Manch\u00f3n is considered an important theoretician in second language writing research.{{By whom|date=October 2018}}\n\n== Career ==\nManch\u00f3n started teaching at the University of Murcia in 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ciencia.gob.es/portal/site/MICINN/menuitem.8ce192e94ba842bea3bc811001432ea0/?vgnextoid=88228c7a4b240510VgnVCM1000001d04140aRCRD|title=Manch\u00f3n - Curriculum vitae|date=2018|publisher=University of Murcia}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2011 and 2014, she was a member of the Executive Board of the [[International Association of Applied Linguistics]]. From 2008 and 2014, she was the co-editor of the ''Journal of Second Language Writing.''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aila.info/about/organization/international_committee-2/|title=AILA - Committees|date=2018|publisher=Aila|access-date=2018-09-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907144737/https://aila.info/about/organization/international_committee-2/|archive-date=2018-09-07|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sslw.asu.edu/2015/keynote.html|title=Symposium on Second Language Writing|date=2015|publisher=Sslw.asu.edu}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March 2010, she was interviewed along with [[Ilona Leki]] on the goals and the future of the ''Journal of Second Language Writing''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9ngLHqdtmNE|title=Interview with Ilona Leki and Rosa Manchon, Editors of the Journal of Second Language Writing|date=2010|publisher=Elsevier Journals}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 July 2012, she presented at the Campus Mare Nostrum of the [[University of Murcia]]: Curso de verano entitled ''Escribir ciencia en ingl\u00e9s''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g0WOw-5zO1I|title=Curso UNIMAR-CMN. Conferencia Rosa Manch\u00f3n|date=2012|publisher=Campus Mare Nostrum}}</ref>\n\nShe is an [[associate editor]] of [[The Modern Language Journal]], a [[Peer review|peer-reviewed]] [[academic journal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/page/journal/15404781/homepage/editorialboard.html|title=The Modern Language Journal - Editorial Board|date=6 October 2018|publisher=[[Wiley.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==Research==\nManch\u00f3n has published extensively in prestigious journals such as [[Journal of Second Language Writing]],<ref>{{cite journal|title=Manch\u00f3n R. M. (2017). The potential impact of multimodal composition on language learning. Journal of Second Language Writing, 38, 94-95.|journal=Journal of Second Language Writing|volume=38|pages=94\u201395|date=2017|doi=10.1016/j.jslw.2017.10.008|last1=Manch\u00f3n|first1=Rosa M.}}</ref> [[The Modern Language Journal]],<ref>{{cite journal|title=Roca de Larios J., Manch\u00f3n R. M., & Murphy L. (2006). Generating Text in Native and Foreign Language Writing: A Temporal Analysis of Problem Solving Formulation Processes. The Modern Language Journal, 90(1), 110-114.|journal=The Modern Language Journal|volume=90|pages=100\u2013114|date=2006|doi=10.1111/j.1540-4781.2006.00387.x|last1 = De Larios|first1 = Julio Roca|last2=Manch\u00f3n|first2=Rosa M.|last3=Murphy|first3=LIZ}}</ref> [[Language Learning (journal)|Language Learning]],<ref>{{cite journal|title=Vasylets O., Gilabert R., & Manch\u00f3n R. M. (2017). The Effects of Mode and Task Complexity on Second Language Production. Language Learning, 67(2), 394-430.|journal=Language Learning|volume=67|issue=2|pages=394\u2013430|date=2017|doi=10.1111/lang.12228|last1 = Vasylets|first1 = Olena|last2=Gilabert|first2=Roger|last3=Manch\u00f3n|first3=Rosa M.}}</ref> Annual Review of Applied Linguistics,<ref>{{cite journal|title=Gilabert R., Manch\u00f3n R. M., & Vasylets O. (2016). Mode in Theoretical and Empirical TBLT Research: Advancing Research Agendas. Annual Review of Applied Linguistics, 36, 117-135.|journal=Annual Review of Applied Linguistics|volume=36|pages=117\u2013135|date=2016|doi=10.1017/S0267190515000112|last1=Gilabert|first1=Roger|last2=Manch\u00f3n|first2=Rosa|last3=Vasylets|first3=Olena}}</ref> International Review of Applied Linguistics in Language Teaching.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Manch\u00f3n R. M., & Cenoz J. (2008). Doing second language acquisition research: An introduction. International Review of Applied Linguistics in Language Teaching, 46(3)|journal=Iral - International Review of Applied Linguistics in Language Teaching|volume=46|issue=3|date=2008|doi=10.1515/IRAL.2008.007|last1=Manch\u00f3n|first1=Rosa|last2=Cenoz|first2=Jasone}}</ref>\n\nManch\u00f3n is noted for her theoretical contributions to the study of [[second language writing]]. She distinguished the writing-to-learn (WL) and the learning-to-write (LW) dimensions.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://benjamins.com/catalog/lllt.31|title=Learning-to-Write and Writing-to-Learn in an Additional Language|date=2011|publisher=[[John Benjamins Publishing]]|isbn=9789027284839}}</ref> Her research interests have focused on the cognitive dimension of the acquisition and use of second languages, with special emphasis on the psycholinguistic dimension of textual production.\n\nShe has edited several books on second language writing: ''Writing in Foreign Language Contexts: Learning, Teaching and Research'', ''Learning-to-Write and Writing-to-Learn in an Additional Language'', and ''L2 Writing Development: Multiple Perspectives''.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n===Books===\n*''Writing in foreign language contexts: Learning, teaching, and research.'' (2009)<ref name=\"Writing in foreign language contexts: Learning, teaching, and research.\">{{cite book|last=Manch\u00f3n|first=Rosa|editor2-first=Paul Kei|editor2-last=Matsuda|editor1-first=Rosa M|editor1-last=Manch\u00f3n|title=Writing in foreign language contexts: Learning, teaching, and research|year=2009|publisher=[[De Gruyter]]|isbn=978-1-61451-133-5|pages=648|url=https://www.degruyter.com/view/product/182263|doi=10.1515/9781614511335}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=Studies in Second Language Acquisition|volume=33|issue=3|pages=467\u2013469|date=2011|jstor = 44486016|last1=Kim|first1=Soo Hyon|title=WRITING IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE CONTEXTS: LEARNING, TEACHING, AND RESEARCH. Rosa M. Manch\u00f3n (Ed.). Clevedon, UK: Multilingual Matters, 2009. Pp. Vii + 297|doi=10.1017/S0272263111000088}}</ref>\n*''Learning-to-write and writing-to-learn in an additional language.'' (2011)<ref name=\"Learning-to-write and writing-to-learn in an additional language.\">{{cite book|last=Manch\u00f3n|first=Rosa |title=Learning-to-write and writing-to-learn in an additional language|volume=31 |year=2011|publisher=[[John Benjamins Publishing Company]]|isbn=9789027213037|pages=263|doi=10.1075/lllt.31 |series=Language Learning & Language Teaching }}</ref>\n*''L2 Writing Development: Multiple Perspectives.'' (2012)<ref name=\"L2 Writing Development: Multiple Perspectives.\">{{cite book|last=Manch\u00f3n|first=Rosa |editor1-first=Rosa |editor1-last=Manch\u00f3n |title=L2 Writing Development: Multiple Perspectives|year=2012|publisher=[[De Gruyter]]|isbn=978-1-934078-30-3|pages=252|url=https://www.degruyter.com/view/product/44165|doi=10.1515/9781934078303 }}</ref>\n*''Task-Based Language Learning \u2013 Insights from and for L2 Writing.'' (2014)<ref name=\"Task-Based Language Learning \u2013 Insights from and for L2 Writing.\">{{cite book|last=Manch\u00f3n|first=Rosa |title=Task-Based Language Learning \u2013 Insights from and for L2 Writing|volume=7 |year=2014|publisher=[[John Benjamins Publishing Company]]|isbn=9789027207296|pages=312|doi=10.1075/tblt.7 |series=Task-Based Language Teaching }}</ref>\n*''Handbook of Second and Foreign Language Writing.'' (2016)<ref name=\"Handbook of Second and Foreign Language Writing.\">{{cite book|last=Manch\u00f3n|first=Rosa |editor2-first=Paul Kei |editor2-last=Matsuda |editor1-first=Rosa M |editor1-last=Manch\u00f3n |title=Handbook of Second and Foreign Language Writing|year=2016|publisher=[[De Gruyter]]|isbn=978-1-61451-133-5|pages=648|url=https://www.degruyter.com/view/product/182263|doi=10.1515/9781614511335 }}</ref>\n\n===Articles===\n*\"The use of restructuring strategies in EFL writing: A study of Spanish learners of English as a foreign language.\" (2008)<ref>{{cite journal|title=Roca de Larios J., Murphy L., & Manch\u00f3n R. M. (2008). The use of restructuring strategies in EFL writing: A study of Spanish learners of English as a foreign language. Journal of Second Language Writing, 17(1), 13-44.|journal=Journal of Second Language Writing|volume=8|pages=13\u201344|date=2008|doi=10.1016/S1060-3743(99)80111-8|last1 = De Larios|first1 = Julio Roca|last2=Murphy|first2=Liz|last3=Manchon|first3=Rosa}}</ref>\n*\"The foreign language writer's strategic behaviour in the allocation of time to writing processes.\" (2008)<ref>{{cite journal|title=Roca de Larios J., Manch\u00f3n R. M., Murphy L., & Mar\u00edn J. (2008). The foreign language writer's strategic behaviour in the allocation of time to writing processes. Journal of Second Language Writing, 17(1), 30-47.|journal=Journal of Second Language Writing|volume=17|pages=30\u201347|date=2008|doi=10.1016/j.jslw.2007.08.005|last1 = Roca De Larios|first1 = Julio|last2=Manch\u00f3n|first2=Rosa|last3=Murphy|first3=Liz|last4=Mar\u00edn|first4=Javier}}</ref>\n*\"Generating text in native and foreign language writing: A temporal analysis of problemsolving formulation processes.\" (2006)\n*\"An approximation to the study of backtracking in L2 writing.\" (2000)\n*\"On the temporal nature of planning in L1 and L2 composing.\" (2007)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|https://www.um.es/web/filologia-inglesa/contenido/pdi}}\n{{Second language writing}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Manch\u00f3n, Rosa}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Applied linguists]]\n[[Category:Second language writing]]\n[[Category:Linguists from Spain]]\n[[Category:University of Murcia|Manch\u00f3n, Rosa]]\n[[Category:Women linguists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Rosa M. Manch\u00f3n\n| image = File:Rosa Manchon.jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1957|07|06|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Murcia]], [[Spain]]\n| residence = [[Murcia]], [[Spain]]\n| fields = {{plainlist |\n*[[Second language acquisition]]\n* [[Second language writing]]\n  }}\n| workplaces = {{plainlist |\n* [[University of Murcia]]\n  }}\n| alma_mater = \n| doctoral_advisor = \n| thesis_title = \n| thesis_url = \n| thesis_year = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for = {{plainlist |\n*Second language writing\n  }}\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| awards = \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| religion = \n| website = {{URL|https://www.um.es/web/filologia-inglesa/contenido/pdi|Manch\u00f3n on the website of the University of Murcia}}\n}}\n\n'''Rosa Mar\u00eda Manch\u00f3n Ruiz''' (born 1957) is a [[Spanish people|Spanish]] [[linguist]]. She is currently a professor of [[applied linguistics]] at the [[University of Murcia]], [[Spain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.um.es/web/filologia-inglesa/contenido/pdi|title=Manch\u00f3n - University of Murcia|date=7 September 2018|publisher=Universidad de Murcia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n2009027290/|title=Manch\u00f3n on Worldcat|date=23 November 2018|publisher=[[WorldCat]]}}</ref> Her research focuses on [[second language acquisition]] and [[second language writing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://slw4sla.weebly.com/rosa-m-manchoacuten.html|title=Second Language Writing for SLA|date=7 September 2018|publisher=SLW4SLA}}</ref> She was the editor of the ''[[Journal of Second Language Writing]]'' between 2008 and 2014.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://www.journals.elsevier.com/journal-of-second-language-writing|title=Journal of Second Language Writing|date=7 September 2018|publisher=Journals Elsevier}}</ref> \nAlong with [[Alister Cumming|Cumming]], [[Ken Hyland|Hyland]], [[Judit Kormos|Kormos]], [[Paul Kei Matsuda|Matsuda]], [[Lourdes Ortega|Ortega]], [[Charlene Polio|Polio]], [[Neomy Storch]] and [[Marjolijn Verspoor|Verspoor]], Manch\u00f3n is considered an important theoretician in second language writing research.{{By whom|date=October 2018}}\n\n== Career ==\nManch\u00f3n started teaching at the University of Murcia in 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ciencia.gob.es/portal/site/MICINN/menuitem.8ce192e94ba842bea3bc811001432ea0/?vgnextoid=88228c7a4b240510VgnVCM1000001d04140aRCRD|title=Manch\u00f3n - Curriculum vitae|date=2018|publisher=University of Murcia}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2011 and 2014, she was a member of the Executive Board of the [[International Association of Applied Linguistics]]. From 2008 and 2014, she was the co-editor of the ''Journal of Second Language Writing.''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aila.info/about/organization/international_committee-2/|title=AILA - Committees|date=2018|publisher=Aila|access-date=2018-09-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907144737/https://aila.info/about/organization/international_committee-2/|archive-date=2018-09-07|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sslw.asu.edu/2015/keynote.html|title=Symposium on Second Language Writing|date=2015|publisher=Sslw.asu.edu}}</ref> \n\nOn 24 March 2010, she was interviewed along with [[Ilona Leki]] on the goals and the future of the ''Journal of Second Language Writing''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9ngLHqdtmNE|title=Interview with Ilona Leki and Rosa Manchon, Editors of the Journal of Second Language Writing|date=2010|publisher=Elsevier Journals}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 July 2012, she presented at the Campus Mare Nostrum of the [[University of Murcia]]: Curso de verano entitled ''Escribir ciencia en ingl\u00e9s''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g0WOw-5zO1I|title=Curso UNIMAR-CMN. Conferencia Rosa Manch\u00f3n|date=2012|publisher=Campus Mare Nostrum}}</ref>\n\nShe is an [[associate editor]] of [[The Modern Language Journal]], a [[Peer review|peer-reviewed]] [[academic journal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/page/journal/15404781/homepage/editorialboard.html|title=The Modern Language Journal - Editorial Board|date=6 October 2018|publisher=[[Wiley.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==Research==\nManch\u00f3n has published extensively in prestigious journals such as [[Journal of Second Language Writing]]<ref>{{cite journal|title=Manch\u00f3n R. M. (2017). The potential impact of multimodal composition on language learning. Journal of Second Language Writing, 38, 94-95.|journal=Journal of Second Language Writing|volume=38|pages=94\u201395|date=2017|doi=10.1016/j.jslw.2017.10.008|last1=Manch\u00f3n|first1=Rosa M.}}</ref>, [[The Modern Language Journal]]<ref>{{cite journal|title=Roca de Larios J., Manch\u00f3n R. M., & Murphy L. (2006). Generating Text in Native and Foreign Language Writing: A Temporal Analysis of Problem Solving Formulation Processes. The Modern Language Journal, 90(1), 110-114.|journal=The Modern Language Journal|volume=90|pages=100\u2013114|date=2006|doi=10.1111/j.1540-4781.2006.00387.x|last1 = De Larios|first1 = Julio Roca|last2=Manch\u00f3n|first2=Rosa M.|last3=Murphy|first3=LIZ}}</ref>, [[Language Learning (journal)|Language Learning]]<ref>{{cite journal|title=Vasylets O., Gilabert R., & Manch\u00f3n R. M. (2017). The Effects of Mode and Task Complexity on Second Language Production. Language Learning, 67(2), 394-430.|journal=Language Learning|volume=67|issue=2|pages=394\u2013430|date=2017|doi=10.1111/lang.12228|last1 = Vasylets|first1 = Olena|last2=Gilabert|first2=Roger|last3=Manch\u00f3n|first3=Rosa M.}}</ref>, Annual Review of Applied Linguistics<ref>{{cite journal|title=Gilabert R., Manch\u00f3n R. M., & Vasylets O. (2016). Mode in Theoretical and Empirical TBLT Research: Advancing Research Agendas. Annual Review of Applied Linguistics, 36, 117-135.|journal=Annual Review of Applied Linguistics|volume=36|pages=117\u2013135|date=2016|doi=10.1017/S0267190515000112|last1=Gilabert|first1=Roger|last2=Manch\u00f3n|first2=Rosa|last3=Vasylets|first3=Olena}}</ref>, International Review of Applied Linguistics in Language Teaching.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Manch\u00f3n R. M., & Cenoz J. (2008). Doing second language acquisition research: An introduction. International Review of Applied Linguistics in Language Teaching, 46(3)|journal=Iral - International Review of Applied Linguistics in Language Teaching|volume=46|issue=3|date=2008|doi=10.1515/IRAL.2008.007|last1=Manch\u00f3n|first1=Rosa|last2=Cenoz|first2=Jasone}}</ref>\n\nManch\u00f3n is noted for her theoretical contributions to the study of [[second language writing]]. She distinguished the writing-to-learn (WL) and the learning-to-write (LW) dimensions.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://benjamins.com/catalog/lllt.31|title=Learning-to-Write and Writing-to-Learn in an Additional Language|date=2011|publisher=[[John Benjamins Publishing]]|isbn=9789027284839}}</ref> Her research interests have focused on the cognitive dimension of the acquisition and use of second languages, with special emphasis on the psycholinguistic dimension of textual production.\n\nShe has edited several books on second language writing: ''Writing in Foreign Language Contexts: Learning, Teaching and Research'', ''Learning-to-Write and Writing-to-Learn in an Additional Language'', and ''L2 Writing Development: Multiple Perspectives''.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n===Books===\n*''Writing in foreign language contexts: Learning, teaching, and research.'' (2009)<ref name=\"Writing in foreign language contexts: Learning, teaching, and research.\">{{cite book|last=Manch\u00f3n|first=Rosa|editor2-first=Paul Kei|editor2-last=Matsuda|editor1-first=Rosa M|editor1-last=Manch\u00f3n|title=Writing in foreign language contexts: Learning, teaching, and research|year=2009|publisher=[[De Gruyter]]|isbn=978-1-61451-133-5|pages=648|url=https://www.degruyter.com/view/product/182263|doi=10.1515/9781614511335}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=Studies in Second Language Acquisition|volume=33|issue=3|pages=467\u2013469|date=2011|jstor = 44486016|last1=Kim|first1=Soo Hyon|title=WRITING IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE CONTEXTS: LEARNING, TEACHING, AND RESEARCH. Rosa M. Manch\u00f3n (Ed.). Clevedon, UK: Multilingual Matters, 2009. Pp. Vii + 297|doi=10.1017/S0272263111000088}}</ref>\n*''Learning-to-write and writing-to-learn in an additional language.'' (2011)<ref name=\"Learning-to-write and writing-to-learn in an additional language.\">{{cite book|last=Manch\u00f3n|first=Rosa |title=Learning-to-write and writing-to-learn in an additional language|volume=31 |year=2011|publisher=[[John Benjamins Publishing Company]]|isbn=9789027213037|pages=263|doi=10.1075/lllt.31 |series=Language Learning & Language Teaching }}</ref>\n*''L2 Writing Development: Multiple Perspectives.'' (2012)<ref name=\"L2 Writing Development: Multiple Perspectives.\">{{cite book|last=Manch\u00f3n|first=Rosa |editor1-first=Rosa |editor1-last=Manch\u00f3n |title=L2 Writing Development: Multiple Perspectives|year=2012|publisher=[[De Gruyter]]|isbn=978-1-934078-30-3|pages=252|url=https://www.degruyter.com/view/product/44165|doi=10.1515/9781934078303 }}</ref>\n*''Task-Based Language Learning \u2013 Insights from and for L2 Writing.'' (2014)<ref name=\"Task-Based Language Learning \u2013 Insights from and for L2 Writing.\">{{cite book|last=Manch\u00f3n|first=Rosa |title=Task-Based Language Learning \u2013 Insights from and for L2 Writing|volume=7 |year=2014|publisher=[[John Benjamins Publishing Company]]|isbn=9789027207296|pages=312|doi=10.1075/tblt.7 |series=Task-Based Language Teaching }}</ref>\n*''Handbook of Second and Foreign Language Writing.'' (2016)<ref name=\"Handbook of Second and Foreign Language Writing.\">{{cite book|last=Manch\u00f3n|first=Rosa |editor2-first=Paul Kei |editor2-last=Matsuda |editor1-first=Rosa M |editor1-last=Manch\u00f3n |title=Handbook of Second and Foreign Language Writing|year=2016|publisher=[[De Gruyter]]|isbn=978-1-61451-133-5|pages=648|url=https://www.degruyter.com/view/product/182263|doi=10.1515/9781614511335 }}</ref>\n\n===Articles===\n*\"The use of restructuring strategies in EFL writing: A study of Spanish learners of English as a foreign language.\" (2008)<ref>{{cite journal|title=Roca de Larios J., Murphy L., & Manch\u00f3n R. M. (2008). The use of restructuring strategies in EFL writing: A study of Spanish learners of English as a foreign language. Journal of Second Language Writing, 17(1), 13-44.|journal=Journal of Second Language Writing|volume=8|pages=13\u201344|date=2008|doi=10.1016/S1060-3743(99)80111-8|last1 = De Larios|first1 = Julio Roca|last2=Murphy|first2=Liz|last3=Manchon|first3=Rosa}}</ref>\n*\"The foreign language writer's strategic behaviour in the allocation of time to writing processes.\" (2008)<ref>{{cite journal|title=Roca de Larios J., Manch\u00f3n R. M., Murphy L., & Mar\u00edn J. (2008). The foreign language writer's strategic behaviour in the allocation of time to writing processes. Journal of Second Language Writing, 17(1), 30-47.|journal=Journal of Second Language Writing|volume=17|pages=30\u201347|date=2008|doi=10.1016/j.jslw.2007.08.005|last1 = Roca De Larios|first1 = Julio|last2=Manch\u00f3n|first2=Rosa|last3=Murphy|first3=Liz|last4=Mar\u00edn|first4=Javier}}</ref>\n*\"Generating text in native and foreign language writing: A temporal analysis of problemsolving formulation processes.\" (2006)\n*\"An approximation to the study of backtracking in L2 writing.\" (2000)\n*\"On the temporal nature of planning in L1 and L2 composing.\" (2007)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|https://www.um.es/web/filologia-inglesa/contenido/pdi}}\n{{Second language writing}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Manch\u00f3n, Rosa}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Applied linguists]]\n[[Category:Second language writing]]\n[[Category:Linguists from Spain]]\n[[Category:University of Murcia|Manch\u00f3n, Rosa]]\n[[Category:Women linguists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rosa_Manch%C3%B3n"}
{"title_page": "Ronnie Wilbur", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=September 2018}}\n{| class=\"infobox biography vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold\" |<span class=\"fn\">Ronnie Bring Wilbur</span>\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\" |<div>Wilbur in 2015</div>\n|}\n'''Ronnie Bring Wilbur''' is an American theoretical and experimental linguist and a professor of [[linguistics]] in the Department of Linguistics, School of Interdisciplinary Studies, College of Liberal Arts, at [[Purdue University]] in [[West Lafayette]], [[Indiana]]. She also has a joint appointment in the Department of Speech, Language, and Hearing Sciences in the College of Health and Human sciences. Her main focus is [[sign language|sign language linguistics]]. Some of Wilbur's major contributions to the subfield include the discovery that sign languages have [[syllable]]s similar to spoken languages and that blinks can be used grammatically to mark clause boundaries.<ref>'''Syllables''':     \nWilbur, R. B. (1982). A multi-tiered theory of syllable structure for American Sign Language. Paper presented at the Annual meeting, Linguistic Society of America, San Diego, CA.; Wilbur, R. B. (2011). Sign syllables. In van Oostendorp, Marc, Colin J. Ewen, Elizabeth Hume and Keren Rice (eds). The Blackwell Companion to Phonology, 1309-1334. Blackwell Publishing. Blackwell Reference Online. '''Blinks''':      Wilbur, R. B. 1994. Eyeblinks and ASL phrase structure. Sign Language Studies 84: 221 240.</ref> Wilbur is the director of the Sign Language Linguistics Laboratory at Purdue.<ref>https://www.purdue.edu/hhs/slhs/directory/faculty/wilbur_ronnie.html</ref> Research on the cross-linguistic typology of sign languages is a major focus, including Croatian Sign Language (HZJ), Austrian Sign Language (\u00d6GS), and Turkish Sign Language (T\u0130D).<ref>Wilbur, R. B. (ed.) 2006. Investigating Understudied Sign Languages: Croatian SL and Austrian SL, with comparison to American SL. Sign Language & Linguistics 9, special issue.</ref>\n\n==Bibliography (Selection)==\n*Wilbur, R. B. (1979). American Sign Language and sign systems. Univ Park Press.\n*Wilbur, R. B. (1987). American Sign Language: Linguistic and applied dimensions (2nd ed.). New York, NY, US: Little, Brown and Co.\n*Wilbur, R. B. (2011). Nonmanuals, semantic operators, domain marking, and the solution to two outstanding puzzles in ASL. Sign Language & Linguistics 14: 148-178.\n*Wilbur, R. B. (2011). Modality and the structure of language: Sign languages versus signed systems. In M. Marschark & P. Spencer (eds.), The handbook of deaf studies, language, and education, 332-346. Oxford: Oxford University Press.\n*Wilbur, R. B. (2011). Sign syllables. In van Oostendorp, Marc, Colin J. Ewen, Elizabeth Hume and Keren Rice (eds). The Blackwell Companion to Phonology, 1309-1334. Blackwell Publishing. Blackwell Reference Online. \n*Malaia, E, Wilbur, R.B. (2019). Syllable as a unit of information transfer in linguistic communication: the Entropy Syllable Parsing model. WIREs Cognitive Science e1518.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.purdue.edu/hhs/slhs/directory/faculty/wilbur_ronnie.html Personal webpage]\n* {{worldcat id|lccn-n78069270}}\n* [https://www.nsf.gov/awardsearch/showAward?AWD_ID=8317572&HistoricalAwards=false NSF Award: Syllable Structure and Phonological Rules in American Sign Language]\n* [https://www.nsf.gov/awardsearch/showAward?AWD_ID=0345314&HistoricalAwards=false NSF Award: A Basic Grammar of Croatian Sign Language]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilbur, Ronnie}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Linguists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Purdue University faculty]]\n[[Category:Linguists of sign languages]]\n[[Category:20th-century linguists]]\n[[Category:Women linguists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=September 2018}}\n{| class=\"infobox biography vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold\" |<span class=\"fn\">Ronnie Bring Wilbur</span>\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\" |<div>Wilbur in 2015</div>\n|}\n'''Ronnie Bring Wilbur''' is an American theoretical and experimental linguist and a professor of [[linguistics]] in the Department of Linguistics, School of Interdisciplinary Studies, College of Liberal Arts, at [[Purdue University]] in [[West Lafayette]], [[Indiana]]. She also has a joint appointment in the Department of Speech, Language, and Hearing Sciences in the College of Health and Human sciences. Her main focus is [[sign language|sign language linguistics]]. Some of Wilbur's major contributions to the subfield include the discovery that sign languages have [[syllable]]s similar to spoken languages and that blinks can be used grammatically to mark clause boundaries.<ref>'''Syllables''':     \nWilbur, R. B. (1982). A multi-tiered theory of syllable structure for American Sign Language. Paper presented at the Annual meeting, Linguistic Society of America, San Diego, CA.; Wilbur, R. B. (2011). Sign syllables. In van Oostendorp, Marc, Colin J. Ewen, Elizabeth Hume and Keren Rice (eds). The Blackwell Companion to Phonology, 1309-1334. Blackwell Publishing. Blackwell Reference Online. '''Blinks''':      Wilbur, R. B. 1994. Eyeblinks and ASL phrase structure. Sign Language Studies 84: 221 240. </ref> Wilbur is the director of the Sign Language Linguistics Laboratory at Purdue.<ref>https://www.purdue.edu/hhs/slhs/directory/faculty/wilbur_ronnie.html</ref> Research on the cross-linguistic typology of sign languages is a major focus, including Croatian Sign Language (HZJ), Austrian Sign Language (\u00d6GS), and Turkish Sign Language (T\u0130D).<ref> Wilbur, R. B. (ed.) 2006. Investigating Understudied Sign Languages: Croatian SL and Austrian SL, with comparison to American SL. Sign Language & Linguistics 9, special issue. </ref>\n\n==Bibliography (Selection)==\n*Wilbur, R. B. (1979). American Sign Language and sign systems. Univ Park Press.\n*Wilbur, R. B. (1987). American Sign Language: Linguistic and applied dimensions (2nd ed.). New York, NY, US: Little, Brown and Co.\n*Wilbur, R. B. (2011). Nonmanuals, semantic operators, domain marking, and the solution to two outstanding puzzles in ASL. Sign Language & Linguistics 14: 148-178.\n*Wilbur, R. B. (2011). Modality and the structure of language: Sign languages versus signed systems. In M. Marschark & P. Spencer (eds.), The handbook of deaf studies, language, and education, 332-346. Oxford: Oxford University Press.\n*Wilbur, R. B. (2011). Sign syllables. In van Oostendorp, Marc, Colin J. Ewen, Elizabeth Hume and Keren Rice (eds). The Blackwell Companion to Phonology, 1309-1334. Blackwell Publishing. Blackwell Reference Online. \n*Malaia, E, Wilbur, R.B. (2019). Syllable as a unit of information transfer in linguistic communication: the Entropy Syllable Parsing model. WIREs Cognitive Science e1518.\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.purdue.edu/hhs/slhs/directory/faculty/wilbur_ronnie.html Personal webpage]\n* {{worldcat id|lccn-n78069270}}\n* [https://www.nsf.gov/awardsearch/showAward?AWD_ID=8317572&HistoricalAwards=false NSF Award: Syllable Structure and Phonological Rules in American Sign Language]\n* [https://www.nsf.gov/awardsearch/showAward?AWD_ID=0345314&HistoricalAwards=false NSF Award: A Basic Grammar of Croatian Sign Language]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilbur, Ronnie}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Linguists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Purdue University faculty]]\n[[Category:Linguists of sign languages]]\n[[Category:20th-century linguists]]\n[[Category:Women linguists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ronnie_Wilbur"}
{"title_page": "Eloy Fritsch", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name        = Eloy Fritsch\n| image        = \n| image_size     = \n| landscape      = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt         = \n| caption       = Eloy Fritsch (2017)\n| background     = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name     = \n| native_name     = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| alias        = \n| birth_date     = {{birth year and age|1968}}\n| birth_place     = \n| origin       = [[Brazil]]\n| genre        = [[Electronic music]], [[new-age music]], [[progressive rock]], [[space music]]\n| occupation     = [[Musician]]/[[composer]]\n| instrument     = Electronic Keyboards, Synthesizer, Organ, Piano, Percussion, Sampler, Electronics and Computer.\n| years_active    = 1983&ndash;present\n| label        = [[Musea]], Rock Symphony, Atra\u00e7\u00e3o\n| associated_acts   = [[Apocalypse (band)|Apocalypse]]\n| website       = {{URL|http://www.ef.mus.br}} \n}}\n\n'''Eloy Fernando Fritsch''' (born 1968) is an electronic musician, keyboard player and main composer of Brazilian progressive rock band [[Apocalypse (band)|Apocalypse]]. As a solo artist he creates cosmic [[new-age music]].\n\n==History==\n\nIn 1983 Fritsch formed [[progressive rock]] band [[Apocalypse (band)|Apocalypse]]. They are considered pivotal in the development of progressive rock in Southern Brazil.<ref name=\"official\">[http://www.ef.mus.br Eloy Fritsch] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181222211901/http://ef.mus.br/ |date=22 December 2018 }}, Official Web Site. Retrieved 5 June 2008</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/perto-do-amanhecer-mw0000985165 |title=Perto do Amanhecer (review)|author=Cesar Lanzarini|work=AllMusic|accessdate=12 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, he moved to Porto Alegre and began his solo project composing [[electronic music]]. His first official solo album was ''Dreams'', recorded in 1994 and 1995. During 1997, he released his second solo album, ''Behind the Walls of Imagination'', which showcases his skills with various electronic and acoustic keyboard instruments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/behind-the-walls-of-imagination-mw0000985247 |title= Behind the Walls of Imagination (review)|author=Cesar Lanzarini|work=AllMusic|accessdate=24 September 2011}}</ref> In the mid-1990s, Fritsch secured a recording contract with French label Musea. His third album for them, ''Space Music'', was released in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/eloy-fritsch-mn0000964354 |last=Prato|first=Greg|title=Eloy Fritsch Biography|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=7 December 2009}}</ref><ref>(in Portuguese) Costa, Thiago. Cover Teclado. Eloy Fritsch: Progressivo Brasileiro. Interview with Eloy Fritsch. p. February, 2001. p. 22-25.</ref><ref>{{cite journal|work=Keyboard Magazine|title=Workspace: Eloy Fritsch|date=January 2001|page=168}}</ref>\n\nThe composer reveals his sci-fi style with ''[[Cyberspace (album)|Cyberspace]]''. In this album Fritsch offers 1970s-inspired keyboard symphonic/electronic progressive instrumental music. Fritsch performs electronic music that evolves between [[Vangelis]]' ambient and impressionist electronic, and the synthesized progressive rock of masters such as [[Rick Wakeman]].<ref name=\"Garden\">{{cite web|url=http://www.musearecords.com/boutique/anglais/index.php?ficheprod=1&artiste=Eloy%20FRITSCHhttp%3A%2F%2F&refp=36423 |work=Musea Records Le Classifique du Futur|title=Eloy Fritsch - The Garden Of Emotions (review)|accessdate=13 December 2011}}</ref> Nevertheless, Fritsch has found his own style within melodic electronic music framework. The compositions are very melodic and emotive, with multi-layered instrumental textures/voicings and solidly coherent arrangements.<ref>(in Spanish) [http://www.articmist.org/entrevistas/eloy_fritsch.htm Murad\u00e1s, Manuel Lemos. New Sounds Digital. Interview with Eloy Fritsch.] Retrieved 3-6-2001.</ref><ref>(in Portuguese) Teclado e Audio Magazine. A S\u00edntese de um Artista. Interview with Eloy Fritsch. p. 20-22. June 2005.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/artist/Eloy+Fritsch |work=Discogs|title=Eloy Fritsch|accessdate=12 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pugachov.ru/eem/fafram.html |last=Purgachov|first=Artemy|title=F|work=Encyclopedia of Electronic Music|accessdate= 1 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nFritsch has earned a PhD in [[computer music]], and has served as a teacher of electronic music at the [[Federal University of Rio Grande do Sul]] (UFRGS). During 1999, Fritsch created the Electronic Music Center in the Institute of Arts at UFRGS.<ref>[http://www.ufrgs.br/musicaeletronica Electronic Music Center at UFRGS ] Retrieved 01-02-2010</ref>\n\nIn parallel with his work as keyboard player of the group Apocalypse and his academic activity, Fritsch releases music as a solo musician (through the Musea and Rock Symphony labels), such as the album ''[[Mythology (Eloy Fritsch album)|Mythology]]'', a large variety of original musical works in which he brings to maturity the use of synthesizers to compose melodic electronic music.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/mythology-mw0001264207 |title=Mythology (review)|author=Cesar Lanzarini|work=All Music|accessdate=29 September 2011}}</ref> This ambitious work uses the whole panel of his electronic sounds to depict fifteen tracks exclusively dedicated to the different gods worshiped in the past. Different cultures, such as Brazilian, Mesopotamian, Hindu, Amerindian, Inca, African, Greek, Egyptian, Scandinavian, Roman and Chinese, are outlined in the ''Mythology'' album by an instrumental composition, thanks to his panoply of keyboards including a [[Roland System 700]] modular synthesizer.<ref>(in Portuguese) Ruiz, Fl\u00e1via, Audio M\u00fasica & Tecnologia Magazine. Eloy Fritsch Buscando Sempre Novos Caminhos. Interview with Eloy Fritsch. p. 137-141. 2001.</ref>\n\nEloy Fritsch's love of the sky inspired him to compose the electronic suite ''[[Atmosphere (Eloy Fritsch album)|Atmosphere]]'' (2003). Once again the composer reveals his ecological convictions: he presently defends the virtues of the gas envelope that allow everyone to live on Earth: the Atmosphere.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.articmist.org/criticas/atmosphere.htm |last=Sergio|first=Jorge.|work=Articmist|title= Eloy Fritsch Atmosphere|accessdate=10 October 2002}} (in Spanish)</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soniccuriosity.com/sc164.htm|work=Sonic Curiosity|title=Eloy Fritsch: Atmosphere|accessdate=9 October 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|work=21st Century Music Magazine|title=Eloy Fritsch: Nel Cosmo com Amore|pages=6\u20138|issue=13|date=December 2004}} (in Italian)</ref><ref>[http://www.last.fm/music/Eloy+Fritsch/+wiki Last FM. \"Eloy Fritsch Biography\".] retrieved 08-09-2011</ref>\n\n''[[Landscapes (Eloy Fritsch album)|Landscapes]]'' (2005) was Fritsch's next work to emerge on disc.<ref name=\"Garden\"/><ref>[http://duck.fm/Eloy+Fritsch/bio Duck FM. Eloy Fritsch Biography.] Retrieved 04-10-2012.</ref>\n\nIn 2007 Eloy Fritsch wrote the book \"Electronic Music\" that was released in 2008 during the Book Fair in Porto Alegre. The book is accompanied by a DVD containing the electroacoustic compositions Synapse 5.1, Synthetic Horizon, Public Market, Indian Sampler, Mystery and Silicon Child created during his research in Electronic Music Center at Federal University of Rio Grande do Sul, Brazil. Eloy Fritsch received the A\u00e7orianos Music Awards. The awards ceremony happened on 28 April 2008, Tuesday night at the S\u00e3o Pedro Theater, Porto Alegre, Brazil. The A\u00e7orianos Music Awards honor the best albums, musicians and contributions to the music in South o Brazil. The ceremony was broadcast on television and event production presented a short film about the music and artistic works of the composer.<ref name=\"official\"/>\n\nIn 2009 Eloy Fritsch played keyboards in several concerts with the Apocalypse.<ref>Tomasi, Eliton. The Apocalypse Hystory. Ed. Evangraf, Porto Alegre, 2011.</ref> He also released the album The Garden of Emotions.<ref>(in Portuguese) [http://artebrasilis.blogspot.com.br/2010/10/eloy-fritsch-emocao-e-musica.html Arte Brasilis. Eloy Fritsch Emo\u00e7\u00e3o e M\u00fasica Instrumental Brasileira.] Retrieved 12-10-2010.</ref> Musea company distributed the CD in Europe. The recorded company wrote the following lines about the album: \"The ninth album The Garden Of Emotions presents symphonic themes with choirs, analog and digital synthesizers dominating. Fans of classic VANGELIS, Jean-Michel JARRE and Rick WAKEMAN works will enjoy this. Some of the more solemn themes remind Isao TOMITA. \"Lumine Solis\" is one of the best compositions and a choir-laden track. \"Solar Energy\" introduces a spacier atmosphere, with phasing pads and Berlin School sequences. This is pure electronic music and a very good one, with all sorts of really fat analog timbres. \"Beyond The Mountains\" is a very cinematic and return to the classically inspired structures, with an extra ethnic elements. \"Electric Light\" is synthetic and even KRAFTWERK-like, with insisting sequences, vocoders and a simple repeating melodic theme. Flutes, marimba sound and percussion welcome the coming of \"Savage\" before a melodic synthesizers theme appears. \"Space Station\" is another foray into a purely synthetic world and you could also draw a comparison with Jean-Michel JARRE's \"Chronologie\". \"The Canyon Of Hope\" finishes this album with flowing synthesizers, symphonic textures and a reflective electric piano\".<ref name=\"Garden\"/>\n\nIn the same year Fritsch was also honored on the Journey of Literature event in the Passo Fundo city, Brazil. The composer received the trophy Vasco Prado.<ref name=\"official\"/>\n\nIn 2010 Fritsch worked on two major projects: In the production of ''The Apocalypse 25th Anniversary Box Set'' (2 CDs, 1 DVD and the book about the Apocalypse Hystory)<ref>[http://www.progarchives.com/artist.asp?id=23 ProgArchives Apocalypse]. Retrieved 01-10-2011</ref><ref name=\"Apocalypse Official\">{{cite web|url=http://www.apocalypseband.com |title=Apocalypse Official WebSite|accessdate=12 September 2012}}</ref> and the MCT Project - Music, Science and Technology funded by the Brazilian government. Fritsch has created the Brazilian Virtual Museum of Synthesizer and a documentary film about electronic music to be distributed to schools and music teachers. He also created an exhibition of Electronic Music at the Museum of the University.<ref>[http://www.ufrgs.br/mvs Virtual Museum of Synthesizer.] Retrieved 12-12-2011</ref>\n\nIn 2011 Eloy Fritsch perform in South of Brazil with [[Apocalypse (band)|Apocalypse]], Orchestra and Choral during the Symphonic Rock Concert<ref name=\"Apocalypse Official\"/> and the group received the A\u00e7orianos Music Awards. The awards ceremony happened on 9 May 2012, Wednesday night at the S\u00e3o Pedro Theater, Porto Alegre, Brazil. The A\u00e7orianos Music Awards honor contribution of the Apocalypse group to the music in South of Brazil.<ref name=\"Apocalypse Official\"/>\n\nThe tenth Eloy Fritsch CD brings Exogenesis Suite in four movements inspired by the genesis of the universe. In addition to this suite the CD contains more eight individual tracks. Joining the symphonic and electronic, but without forgetting the ethnic instruments and the voices, the composer of new-age music uses high technology in the service of emotions to create compositions. The CD cover and booklet images were created by European artists specializing in science fiction illustrations Maciej Rebisz and Mirek Drozd and refer to the creation of the cosmos and the existence of other life forms.<ref>(in Spanish,) [http://www.reviewsnewage.com/eloyfritsch.html Reviews New Age: Discovering Music.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120920055327/http://reviewsnewage.com/eloyfritsch.html |date=20 September 2012 }} Retrieved 14 September 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.newagemusicworld.com/ Olsen, John. new-age music World. Best Electronic Albums 2012.] retrieved 15 December 2012.</ref>\n\n==Selected discography==\n\n===With Apocalypse===\n* 1991 - ''Apocalypse'' \n* 1995 - ''Perto do Amanhecer'' \n* 1996 - ''Aurora dos Sonhos'' \n* 1997 - ''Lendas Encantadas'' \n* 1998 - ''The Best of Apocalypse'' (Compilation)\n* 2001 - ''Live in USA'' (Live)\n* 2003 - ''Refugio'' \n* 2004 - ''Magic'' \n* 2006 - ''Apocalypse Live in Rio'' \n* 2006 - ''DVD Apocalypse Live in Rio'' \n* 2006 - ''The Bridge of Light'' \n* 2006 - ''DVD The 25th Anniversary Concert'' \n* 2010 - ''Magic Spells'' \n* 2011 - ''2012 Light Years from Home'' \n* 2011 - ''The 25th Anniversary Box Set''\n* 2013 - ''DVD The Bridge of Light''\n\n===Solo works===\n* 1996 - ''[[Dreams (Eloy Fritsch album)|Dreams]]''\n* 1997 - ''[[Behind the Walls of Imagination]]'' \n* 1998 - ''[[Space music (album)|Space Music]]'' \n* 2000 - ''[[Cyberspace (album)|Cyberspace]]'' \n* 2001 - ''[[Mythology (Eloy Fritsch album)|Mythology]]'' \n* 2003 - ''Atmosphere - Electronic Suite'' \n* 2005 - ''Landscapes''\n* 2006 - ''Past and Future Sounds - 1996-2006'' \n* 2009 - ''The Garden of Emotions'' \n* 2012 - ''Exogenesis'' \n* 2014 - ''Spiritual Energy''\n* 2017 - ''Sailing to the Edge''\n* 2019 - ''Journey to the Future''\n\n=== Compilations featuring Eloy Fritsch ===\n* 1997 - ''Planeta Nova Era Vol. 7'' Track: Lake of Peace Movement 1 and 2\n* 1999 - ''Planeta Nova Era Vol. 13'' Track: Cosmic Winds\n* 1999 - ''Planeta Nova Era Vol. 14'' Track: Starlight\n* 2002 - ''Margen - Music from the Edge Vol. 6'' - Track: Ionosphere\n* 2005 - ''Edition #5'' Track: The Garden of Emotions Suite\n* 2006 - ''Brasil Instrumental 2006'' Track: The Garden of Emotions Suite\n* 2006 - ''Compact Mellotron 34'' Track: Andromeda\n* 2006 - ''Edition #13'' Track: Shiva\n* 2006 - ''Edition #14'' Track: Atlantis\n* 2006 - ''Edition #15'' Track: Andromeda\n* 2009 - ''Brazilian Electroacoustic Music Compilation'' Track: Synthetic Horizon\n* 2012 - ''Schwingungen Radio auf CD - Edition Nr.210 11/12.'' Track: Moonwalk\n\n== Keyboards used by Fritsch ==\n\nThroughout his albums Fritsch uses several instruments. Some of these are:\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Minimoog]]\n*[[Roland JD-800]]\n*[[Roland JP-8000]]\n*[[Roland JP-8080]]\n*[[Roland Juno-106]]\n*[[Roland JX-3P]]\n*[[Roland System 700]]\n*[[Roland AX-1]]\n*[[Roland VK-8]]\n*[[Casio CZ-5000]]\n*[[Casio AZ-1]]\n*[[Korg MS-10]]\n*[[Korg MS-20]]\n*[[Korg 01/W]]\n*[[Korg M1]]\n*[[Korg Triton]]\n*[[Korg Polysix]]\n*[[Korg Delta]]\n*[[Korg MS2000R]]\n*[[Yamaha SY77]]\n*[[Yamaha DX-21]]\n*[[Clavia Nord Modular]]\n*[[Kurzweil K-2600]]\n*[[Ensoniq MR76]]\n*[[Digitech Vocalist]]\n*[[AKAI S-5000]]\n*[[Tokai Tx5-DS Plus]]\n*[[Labolida Nano1]]\n*[[M-audio Piano Pro Keys 88]]\n*[[Korg Oasys]]\n*[[Korg Triton Extreme]]\n*[[Korg Kronos]]\n*[[Roland Sysytem-8]]\n*[[Roland Jupiter-80]]\n*[[Behringer DeepMind12]]\n*[[Roland Gaia]]\n*[[Roland FA-06]]\n*[[Roland FA-08]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Jean Michel Jarre]]\n* [[Isao Tomita|Tomita]]\n* [[Vangelis]]\n* [[Rick Wakeman]]\n* [[Keith Emerson]]\n* [[Larry Fast]]\n* [[Patrick Moraz]]\n* [[Kitaro]]\n* [[Tangerine Dream]]\n* [[Klaus Schulze]]\n* [[Krautrock]]\n* [[Progressive rock]]\n* [[Apocalypse (band)]]\n* [[Berlin School of electronic music]]\n* [[new-age music]]\n* [[Space music]]\n* [[Electronic music]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of ambient music artists]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|http://www.ef.mus.br}}\n* {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p532356}}\n* [http://www.rockprogressivo.com.br/eloy info and sounds].\n* [http://www.artistdirect.com/artist/eloy-fritsch/1710487 Eloy Fritsch music] on Artist Direct.\n* [http://www.discogs.com/Eloy-Fernando-Fritsch-Exogenesis/release/4646297 info, reviews and discography].\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fritsch, Eloy}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:New-age synthesizer players]]\n[[Category:Brazilian electronic musicians]]\n[[Category:Brazilian keyboardists]]\n[[Category:Progressive rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Rock keyboardists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New-age musicians]]\n[[Category:New-age composers]]\n[[Category:Art rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Brazilian people of German descent]]\n[[Category:People from Rio Grande do Sul]]\n[[Category:People from Caxias do Sul]]\n[[Category:Electroacoustic music composers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian composers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian rock musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name        = Eloy Fritsch\n| image        = \n| image_size     = \n| landscape      = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt         = \n| caption       = Eloy Fritsch (2017)\n| background     = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name     = \n| native_name     = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| alias        = \n| birth_date     = {{birth year and age|1968}}\n| birth_place     = \n| origin       = [[Brazil]]\n| genre        = [[Electronic music]], [[new-age music]], [[progressive rock]], [[space music]]\n| occupation     = [[Musician]]/[[composer]]\n| instrument     = Electronic Keyboards, Synthesizer, Organ, Piano, Percussion, Sampler, Electronics and Computer.\n| years_active    = 1983&ndash;present\n| label        = [[Musea]], Rock Symphony, Atra\u00e7\u00e3o\n| associated_acts   = [[Apocalypse (band)|Apocalypse]]\n| website       = {{URL|http://www.ef.mus.br}} \n}}\n\n'''Eloy Fernando Fritsch''' (born 1968) is an electronic musician, keyboard player and main composer of Brazilian progressive rock band [[Apocalypse (band)|Apocalypse]]. As a solo artist he creates cosmic [[new-age music]].\n\n==History==\n\nIn 1983 Fritsch formed [[progressive rock]] band [[Apocalypse (band)|Apocalypse]]. They are considered pivotal in the development of progressive rock in Southern Brazil.<ref name=\"official\">[http://www.ef.mus.br Eloy Fritsch] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181222211901/http://ef.mus.br/ |date=22 December 2018 }}, Official Web Site. Retrieved 5 June 2008</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/perto-do-amanhecer-mw0000985165 |title=Perto do Amanhecer (review)|author=Cesar Lanzarini|work=AllMusic|accessdate=12 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, he moved to Porto Alegre and began his solo project composing [[electronic music]]. His first official solo album was ''Dreams'', recorded in 1994 and 1995. During 1997, he released his second solo album, ''Behind the Walls of Imagination'', which showcases his skills with various electronic and acoustic keyboard instruments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/behind-the-walls-of-imagination-mw0000985247 |title= Behind the Walls of Imagination (review)|author=Cesar Lanzarini|work=AllMusic|accessdate=24 September 2011}}</ref> In the mid-1990s, Fritsch secured a recording contract with French label Musea. His third album for them, ''Space Music'', was released in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/eloy-fritsch-mn0000964354 |last=Prato|first=Greg|title=Eloy Fritsch Biography|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=7 December 2009}}</ref><ref>(in Portuguese) Costa, Thiago. Cover Teclado. Eloy Fritsch: Progressivo Brasileiro. Interview with Eloy Fritsch. p. February, 2001. p. 22-25.</ref><ref>{{cite journal|work=Keyboard Magazine|title=Workspace: Eloy Fritsch|date=January 2001|page=168}}</ref>\n\nThe composer reveals his sci-fi style with ''[[Cyberspace (album)|Cyberspace]]''. In this album Fritsch offers 1970s-inspired keyboard symphonic/electronic progressive instrumental music. Fritsch performs electronic music that evolves between [[Vangelis]]' ambient and impressionist electronic, and the synthesized progressive rock of masters such as [[Rick Wakeman]].<ref name=\"Garden\">{{cite web|url=http://www.musearecords.com/boutique/anglais/index.php?ficheprod=1&artiste=Eloy%20FRITSCHhttp%3A%2F%2F&refp=36423 |work=Musea Records Le Classifique du Futur|title=Eloy Fritsch - The Garden Of Emotions (review)|accessdate=13 December 2011}}</ref> Nevertheless, Fritsch has found his own style within melodic electronic music framework. The compositions are very melodic and emotive, with multi-layered instrumental textures/voicings and solidly coherent arrangements.<ref>(in Spanish) [http://www.articmist.org/entrevistas/eloy_fritsch.htm Murad\u00e1s, Manuel Lemos. New Sounds Digital. Interview with Eloy Fritsch.] Retrieved 3-6-2001.</ref><ref>(in Portuguese) Teclado e Audio Magazine. A S\u00edntese de um Artista. Interview with Eloy Fritsch. p. 20-22. June 2005.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/artist/Eloy+Fritsch |work=Discogs|title=Eloy Fritsch|accessdate=12 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pugachov.ru/eem/fafram.html |last=Purgachov|first=Artemy|title=F|work=Encyclopedia of Electronic Music|accessdate= 1 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nFritsch has earned a PhD in [[computer music]], and has served as a teacher of electronic music at the [[Federal University of Rio Grande do Sul]] (UFRGS). During 1999, Fritsch created the Electronic Music Center in the Institute of Arts at UFRGS.<ref>[http://www.ufrgs.br/musicaeletronica Electronic Music Center at UFRGS ] Retrieved 01-02-2010</ref>\n\nIn parallel with his work as keyboard player of the group Apocalypse and his academic activity, Fritsch releases music as a solo musician (through the Musea and Rock Symphony labels), such as the album ''[[Mythology (Eloy Fritsch album)|Mythology]]'', a large variety of original musical works in which he brings to maturity the use of synthesizers to compose melodic electronic music.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/mythology-mw0001264207 |title=Mythology (review)|author=Cesar Lanzarini|work=All Music|accessdate=29 September 2011}}</ref> This ambitious work uses the whole panel of his electronic sounds to depict fifteen tracks exclusively dedicated to the different gods worshiped in the past. Different cultures, such as Brazilian, Mesopotamian, Hindu, Amerindian, Inca, African, Greek, Egyptian, Scandinavian, Roman and Chinese, are outlined in the ''Mythology'' album by an instrumental composition, thanks to his panoply of keyboards including a [[Roland System 700]] modular synthesizer.<ref>(in Portuguese) Ruiz, Fl\u00e1via, Audio M\u00fasica & Tecnologia Magazine. Eloy Fritsch Buscando Sempre Novos Caminhos. Interview with Eloy Fritsch. p. 137-141. 2001.</ref>\n\nEloy Fritsch's love of the sky inspired him to compose the electronic suite ''[[Atmosphere (Eloy Fritsch album)|Atmosphere]]'' (2003). Once again the composer reveals his ecological convictions: he presently defends the virtues of the gas envelope that allow everyone to live on Earth: the Atmosphere.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.articmist.org/criticas/atmosphere.htm |last=Sergio|first=Jorge.|work=Articmist|title= Eloy Fritsch Atmosphere|accessdate=10 October 2002}} (in Spanish)</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soniccuriosity.com/sc164.htm|work=Sonic Curiosity|title=Eloy Fritsch: Atmosphere|accessdate=9 October 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|work=21st Century Music Magazine|title=Eloy Fritsch: Nel Cosmo com Amore|pages=6\u20138|issue=13|date=December 2004}} (in Italian)</ref><ref>[http://www.last.fm/music/Eloy+Fritsch/+wiki Last FM. \"Eloy Fritsch Biography\".] retrieved 08-09-2011</ref>\n\n''[[Landscapes (Eloy Fritsch album)|Landscapes]]'' (2005) was Fritsch's next work to emerge on disc.<ref name=\"Garden\"/><ref>[http://duck.fm/Eloy+Fritsch/bio Duck FM. Eloy Fritsch Biography.] Retrieved 04-10-2012.</ref>\n\nIn 2007 Eloy Fritsch wrote the book \"Electronic Music\" that was released in 2008 during the Book Fair in Porto Alegre. The book is accompanied by a DVD containing the electroacoustic compositions Synapse 5.1, Synthetic Horizon, Public Market, Indian Sampler, Mystery and Silicon Child created during his research in Electronic Music Center at Federal University of Rio Grande do Sul, Brazil. Eloy Fritsch received the A\u00e7orianos Music Awards. The awards ceremony happened on 28 April 2008, Tuesday night at the S\u00e3o Pedro Theater, Porto Alegre, Brazil. The A\u00e7orianos Music Awards honor the best albums, musicians and contributions to the music in South o Brazil. The ceremony was broadcast on television and event production presented a short film about the music and artistic works of the composer.<ref name=\"official\"/>\n\nIn 2009 Eloy Fritsch played keyboards in several concerts with the Apocalypse.<ref>Tomasi, Eliton. The Apocalypse Hystory. Ed. Evangraf, Porto Alegre, 2011.</ref> He also released the album The Garden of Emotions.<ref>(in Portuguese) [http://artebrasilis.blogspot.com.br/2010/10/eloy-fritsch-emocao-e-musica.html Arte Brasilis. Eloy Fritsch Emo\u00e7\u00e3o e M\u00fasica Instrumental Brasileira.] Retrieved 12-10-2010.</ref> Musea company distributed the CD in Europe. The recorded company wrote the following lines about the album: \"The ninth album The Garden Of Emotions presents symphonic themes with choirs, analog and digital synthesizers dominating. Fans of classic VANGELIS, Jean-Michel JARRE and Rick WAKEMAN works will enjoy this. Some of the more solemn themes remind Isao TOMITA. \"Lumine Solis\" is one of the best compositions and a choir-laden track. \"Solar Energy\" introduces a spacier atmosphere, with phasing pads and Berlin School sequences. This is pure electronic music and a very good one, with all sorts of really fat analog timbres. \"Beyond The Mountains\" is a very cinematic and return to the classically inspired structures, with an extra ethnic elements. \"Electric Light\" is synthetic and even KRAFTWERK-like, with insisting sequences, vocoders and a simple repeating melodic theme. Flutes, marimba sound and percussion welcome the coming of \"Savage\" before a melodic synthesizers theme appears. \"Space Station\" is another foray into a purely synthetic world and you could also draw a comparison with Jean-Michel JARRE's \"Chronologie\". \"The Canyon Of Hope\" finishes this album with flowing synthesizers, symphonic textures and a reflective electric piano\".<ref name=\"Garden\"/>\n\nIn the same year Fritsch was also honored on the Journey of Literature event in the Passo Fundo city, Brazil. The composer received the trophy Vasco Prado.<ref name=\"official\"/>\n\nIn 2010 Fritsch worked on two major projects: In the production of ''The Apocalypse 25th Anniversary Box Set'' (2 CDs, 1 DVD and the book about the Apocalypse Hystory)<ref>[http://www.progarchives.com/artist.asp?id=23 ProgArchives Apocalypse]. Retrieved 01-10-2011</ref><ref name=\"Apocalypse Official\">{{cite web|url=http://www.apocalypseband.com |title=Apocalypse Official WebSite|accessdate=12 September 2012}}</ref> and the MCT Project - Music, Science and Technology funded by the Brazilian government. Fritsch has created the Brazilian Virtual Museum of Synthesizer and a documentary film about electronic music to be distributed to schools and music teachers. He also created an exhibition of Electronic Music at the Museum of the University.<ref>[http://www.ufrgs.br/mvs Virtual Museum of Synthesizer.] Retrieved 12-12-2011</ref>\n\nIn 2011 Eloy Fritsch perform in South of Brazil with [[Apocalypse (band)|Apocalypse]], Orchestra and Choral during the Symphonic Rock Concert<ref name=\"Apocalypse Official\"/> and the group received the A\u00e7orianos Music Awards. The awards ceremony happened on 9 May 2012, Wednesday night at the S\u00e3o Pedro Theater, Porto Alegre, Brazil. The A\u00e7orianos Music Awards honor contribution of the Apocalypse group to the music in South of Brazil.<ref name=\"Apocalypse Official\"/>\n\nThe tenth Eloy Fritsch CD brings Exogenesis Suite in four movements inspired by the genesis of the universe. In addition to this suite the CD contains more eight individual tracks. Joining the symphonic and electronic, but without forgetting the ethnic instruments and the voices, the composer of new-age music uses high technology in the service of emotions to create compositions. The CD cover and blooket images were created by European artists specializing in science fiction illustrations Maciej Rebisz and Mirek Drozd and refer to the creation of the cosmos and the existence of other life forms.<ref>(in Spanish,) [http://www.reviewsnewage.com/eloyfritsch.html Reviews New Age: Discovering Music.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120920055327/http://reviewsnewage.com/eloyfritsch.html |date=20 September 2012 }} Retrieved 14 September 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.newagemusicworld.com/ Olsen, John. new-age music World. Best Electronic Albums 2012.] retrieved 15 December 2012.</ref>\n\n==Selected discography==\n\n===With Apocalypse===\n* 1991 - ''Apocalypse'' \n* 1995 - ''Perto do Amanhecer'' \n* 1996 - ''Aurora dos Sonhos'' \n* 1997 - ''Lendas Encantadas'' \n* 1998 - ''The Best of Apocalypse'' (Compilation)\n* 2001 - ''Live in USA'' (Live)\n* 2003 - ''Refugio'' \n* 2004 - ''Magic'' \n* 2006 - ''Apocalypse Live in Rio'' \n* 2006 - ''DVD Apocalypse Live in Rio'' \n* 2006 - ''The Bridge of Light'' \n* 2006 - ''DVD The 25th Anniversary Concert'' \n* 2010 - ''Magic Spells'' \n* 2011 - ''2012 Light Years from Home'' \n* 2011 - ''The 25th Anniversary Box Set''\n* 2013 - ''DVD The Bridge of Light''\n\n===Solo works===\n* 1996 - ''[[Dreams (Eloy Fritsch album)|Dreams]]''\n* 1997 - ''[[Behind the Walls of Imagination]]'' \n* 1998 - ''[[Space music (album)|Space Music]]'' \n* 2000 - ''[[Cyberspace (album)|Cyberspace]]'' \n* 2001 - ''[[Mythology (Eloy Fritsch album)|Mythology]]'' \n* 2003 - ''Atmosphere - Electronic Suite'' \n* 2005 - ''Landscapes''\n* 2006 - ''Past and Future Sounds - 1996-2006'' \n* 2009 - ''The Garden of Emotions'' \n* 2012 - ''Exogenesis'' \n* 2014 - ''Spiritual Energy''\n*