gn=center|43\n|Ahmet Pren\u00e7i\n|30 March 2007\n|28 October 2009\n|-\n|align=center|44\n|Hysni Burgaj\n|28 October 2009\n|9 September 2013\n|-\n|align=center|45\n|Artan Didi\n|10 October 2013\n|31 March 2015\n|-\n|align=center|46\n|Haki \u00c7ako\n|15 April 2015\n|8 January 2018\n|-\n|align=center|47\n|Ardi Veliu\n|5 February 2018\n|''Incumbent''\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Police_car_Albania_04.jpg|Cars used by ASP\nFile:Sterff.jpg|Albanian Police Training\nFile:RENEA_exhibition_ALMEX_2010.jpg|RENEA Special Forces Showcase in Tirana\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Law enforcement in Albania]]\n*[[General Directorate of Civil Emergencies]]\n*[[Sigurimi]]\n\n\n{{Police}}\n{{Law enforcement in Albania}}\n{{Albania topics}}\n[[Category:National law enforcement agencies]]\n[[Category:Law enforcement agencies of Albania]]\n[[Category:National Central Bureaus of Interpol]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|National police and law enforcement agency of Albania}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox law enforcement agency\n| agencyname        = Albanian State Police <br> <small>Policia e Shtetit Shqiptar</small>\n| nativename        = \n| nativenamea       = \n| nativenamer       = \n| commonname        = \n| abbreviation      = \n| logo              = [[File:Policia_e_Shtetit.svg|125px]]\n| logocaption       = Patch of the State Police\n| patch             = \n| patchcaption      = \n| badge             = \n| badgecaption      = \n| flag              = \n| flagcaption       = \n| motto             = \n| mottotranslated   = \n| mission           =\n| formedyear        = 1913\n| formedmonthday    = 13 January\n| preceding1        = *[[Royal Albanian Gendarmerie|Gendarmerie]] (1925\u20131939) \n*[[Albanian People's Police|People's Police]] (1945\u20131991)\n| employees         = ~ 10 958  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.punetebrendshme.gov.al/al/te-rejat/lajme/rriten-pagat-per-93-te-punonjesve-te-policise-se-shtetit|title=Rriten pagat p\u00ebr 93 % t\u00eb punonj\u00ebsve t\u00eb Policis\u00eb s\u00eb Shtetit|website=www.punetebrendshme.gov.al}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gazeta-shqip.com/lajme/2015/09/05/policia-rrit-me-21-numrin-e-punonjesve/|title=Policia rrit me 21% numrin e punonj\u00ebsve - Gazeta SHQIP Online|first=Bledi|last=Gilaj|date=5 September 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n| volunteers        = \n| budget            =\n| nongovernment     = \n| country           = Albania\n| countryabbr       = \n| national          = Yes\n| sizearea          = 28,748 km2\n| sizepopulation    = 3,038,594\n| legaljuris        = \n| governingbody     = Government of Albania\n| governingbodyscnd = \n| constitution1     = Law on \"State Police\"\n| police            = Yes\n| local             = Yes\n| overviewtype      = \n| overviewbody      = [[Ministry of Internal Affairs (Albania)|Ministry of Internal Affairs]]\n| headquarters      = [[Bajram Curri Boulevard]], [[Tirana]]\n| title =  \n| date = \n| hqlocmap          = \n| hqlocleft         = \n| hqloctop          = \n| hqlocmappoptitle  = \n| sworntype         = \n| sworn             = \n| unsworntype       = \n| unsworn           = \n| electeetype       = Minister\n| minister1name     = [[Sand\u00ebr Lleshaj]]\n| minister1pfo      = [[Ministry of Internal Affairs (Albania)|Minister]]\n| chief1name        = [[Ardi Veliu]]\n| chief1position    =\n| parentagency      = \n| child1agency      = \n| unittype          = \n| unitname          = \n| officetype        = \n| officename        = \n| provideragency    = \n| uniformedas       = \n| stationtype       = \n| stations          = \n| airbases          = \n| lockuptype        = \n| lockups           = \n| vehicle1type      = \n| vehicles1         =\n| boat1type         = \n| boats1            = \n| aircraft1type     =\n| aircraft1         =\n| animal1type       = \n| animals1          = \n| person1name       = \n| person1reason     = \n| person1type       = \n| programme1        = \n| activity1name     = \n| activitytype      = \n| anniversary1      = \n| award1            = \n| website           = [https://www.asp.gov.al/ Official website]\n| reference         = \n}}\n\nThe '''Albanian State Police''' ({{lang-sq|Policia e Shtetit}}) is the national police and law enforcement agency which operates throughout the [[Albania|Republic of Albania]]. The collapse of the [[People's Socialist Republic of Albania|Communist system]] and the establishment of political pluralism post-1991 brought important changes to the structure of the Albanian Police. The Ministry of Public Order and the General Directorate of Police were established in April 1991, and the new law of July 1991 established the Public Order Police. Nearly 80% of police manpower, i.e. personnel who had served under the previous system, were replaced by new recruits. On 4 November 1991, the Albanian Police was accepted as a member of [[Interpol]]. The emergency number is 129.\n\n==History==\nThe original '''Albanian Police''' was founded on 13 January 1913 by the government of [[Ismail Qemali]], Albania's first [[prime minister]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hri.org/news/balkans/ata/1998/98-01-11.ata.html#06|title=Albanian Telegraphic Agency (ATA), 98-01-11|website=www.hri.org}}</ref>\n[[File:Albanian State Police HQ in Tiran\u00eb.jpg|thumb|Building of the Albanian State Police Headquarters in Tiran\u00eb]]\n===The crisis of 1997===\n{{Main|Albanian Rebellion of 1997}}\nFollowing the collapse of the Albanian economy in January\u2013February 1997 in the wake of the implosion of [[Pyramid schemes in Albania|the Ponzi pyramid banking schemes]] promoted by the government,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/fandd/2000/03/jarvis.htm|title=Collapse of the Ponzi schemes 1997|publisher=International Monetary Fund|accessdate=2015-03-09}}</ref> increasing insurgency in early March led to the Police and Republican Guard deserting en masse because it became clear they were unlikely to be paid, leaving their armouries unlocked,<ref>[[Albanian Rebellion of 1997#Opening of the depots]]</ref> which were promptly looted by parties unknown, believed to mostly have been the local crime bodies and self-appointed militias: many of the weapons eventually surfaced in the ethnic fighting in Kosovo. \n[[File:97-9.jpg|thumb|left|Riot police in 1997 in Albania]]\nThe resulting anarchy led a number of nations to use military forces to evacuate citizens,<ref>[[Operation Silver Wake]]</ref><ref>[[Operation Libelle]]</ref> culminating in the UN authorising [[Operation Alba]] (\"Daybreak\"), a short-term military stabilisation force led by the Italian Army, tasked with facilitating the repatriation of foreigners and laying the foundations for another International Organisation to undertake the longer-term restabilisation. The political debate eventually settled in Europe within the body responsible for the defence diplomatic coordination of the Continent, the Council of the Western European Union. In a 2-hour meeting which convened at 1400 hrs on 2 May 1997,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defensie.nl/english/topics/historical-missions/contents/mission-overview/1997/multinational-advisory-police-element-mape-and-the-european-commission-police-assistance-in-albania-ecpa|title=NL MOD History of MAPE|publisher=Dutch Ministry of Defence|accessdate=2015-03-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309230257/https://www.defensie.nl/english/topics/historical-missions/contents/mission-overview/1997/multinational-advisory-police-element-mape-and-the-european-commission-police-assistance-in-albania-ecpa|archive-date=9 March 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> the WEU Council decided on the immediate establishment of the Multinational Advisory Police Element, sending a pathfinder officer, a Norwegian Police Colonel, the same evening.\nThe Italian force in Operation Alba predicated the Command structure of MAPE passing into the Italian Carabinieri, General Pietro Pistolese, previously commanding the Genoa region, bringing his team with him. Four phases followed, assessment, reconstruction, support of the Albanian Police control during the Kosovo Crisis, and finally build-down and handback in early 2001, which was somewhat accelerated ahead of the transfer of the WEU's operational responsibilities to the Council of the EU on 30 June 2001. The reconstruction principally involved the reconstruction of the Judicial system and the training of Police, but the Finance section also accommodated economic specialists acting as the principal feedback into the correction of the Judicial system. The Command Team later formed the core of the [[European Union Border Assistance Mission Rafah]] from 2005 onwards.\n\n===Public Perception===\nAccording to a survey produced in 2009 for the [[USAID|United States Agency for International Development]] Albanian's perception of the police was as follows:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idra-al.org/cs2009/index2.php |title=Corruption in Albania 2009 - Summary of Findings |publisher=Institute for Development Research and Alternatives |accessdate=2010-09-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821172525/http://www.idra-al.org/cs2009/index2.php |archivedate=21 August 2010 }}</ref>\n\n*On a scale of 0-100 with 0 being Very Honest and 100 being Very Corrupt, Policemen were given a score of 63.1 points\n*When asked to what extent the police help to fight corruption, 0 being Not at All and 100 being Helps a Lot, the Police were given a score of 45.5\n*When asked about trust in institutions, 0 being No Trust at All and 100 being Trust a Lot, the Police were given a score of 47.8\n*When asked if during the previous year they had been asked for a bribe 7.8% said Yes\n*\"When asked how they were treated by the police, the proportion of respondents that replied \"Poorly\" or \"Very poorly\" was 26.6%, a decrease of 10.9 percentage points from 37.5% in 2005\"\n\nGiven that this was within eight years of the departure of the MAPE rebuilding mission, great concern must be expressed about the capacity of the police force to maintain the legal norms required of an aspirant EU State.\n\n\n===Modernization===\n[[File:Flamuri i Policis\u00eb s\u00eb Shtetit.svg|180px|thumb|right|Police flag]]\nIn 2014, the Ministry of Internal Affairs started a modernization process of the Albanian police, to modernize its equipment and methods. The first step was the acquisition of new police vans and cruisers, the next one was the installment of body cameras on police officers to improve their service and to be analysed after an operation. Uniforms of the every uniformed department of the Albanian police were overhauled and the logo was also changed.{{fact|date=June 2019}}\n\nSeveral operations were held from the years 2014 to 2016, in various criminally active regions of Albania (i.e. [[Lazarat]]) to restore confidence and belief of the Albanian public to support the actions of police. Body cameras are becoming an integral part of the Albanian police, used on various drug busts and high-profile operations, released afterwards to the public.{{fact|date=June 2019}}\n\n==Ranks==\nIn 2015, the State Police underwent reorganizational reforms which were expected to continue for several years.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Republic of|first1=Albania|title=Modernizimi i Policis\u00eb s\u00eb Shtetit|url=http://www.punetebrendshme.gov.al/al/te-rejat/lajme/prezantohen-uniformat-e-reja-te-policise-se-shtetit&page=30|website=www.punetebrendshme.gov.al|publisher=Ministry of Internal Affairs}}</ref> It implemented a new hierarchical structure composed of nine hierarchic ranks.<ref name=\"Ranks of Albanian police\">{{cite book|last1=Law on State Police|first1=Albania|title=Ranks of Albanian police|date=2014|publisher=Ministry of Internal Affairs|location=Albania|page=22|url=https://mb.gov.al/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/LIGJI_I_POLICISE_SE_SHTETIT_-_2014.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"Ranks insignia of the Albanian police officers\">{{cite book|last1=Albanian State Police insignia|first1=Albania|title=Ranks insignia of the Albanian police officers|date=2016|publisher=General Directorate of State Police|location=Albania|pages=5-14; 53|url=https://arkiva.asp.gov.al/images/pdf/Gradat_simbolet_uniformat_dhe_shenjat_e_Policise_se_Shtetit_1.pdf|accessdate=24 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| style=\"width:50%; border:1px solid #8888aa; background:#fff; padding:0; font-size:90%; margin:0 12px 12px 0; text-align:center;\"\n|- style=\"background:#DCDCDC;\"\n!\n! colspan=\"9\" | Rank insignia of the Albanian State Police\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#efefef;\"\n| Service Uniform\n|[[File:Grada Drejtues Madhor (Policia e Shtetit).svg|35px]]\n|[[File:Grada Drejtues i Lart\u00eb (Policia e Shtetit).svg|35px]]\n|[[File:Grada Drejtues i Par\u00eb (Policia e Shtetit).svg|35px]]\n|[[File:Grada Drejtues (Policia e Shtetit).svg|35px]]\n|[[File:Grada Kryekomisar (Policia e Shtetit).svg|35px]]\n|[[File:Grada Komisar (Policia e Shtetit).svg|35px]]\n|[[File:Grada N\u00ebnkomisar (Policia e Shtetit).svg|35px]]\n|[[File:Grada Inspektor (Policia e Shtetit).svg|35px]]\n|[[File:Grada Kursant\u00eb (Policia e Shtetit).svg|35px]]\n|-  style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n| Ceremonial Uniform\n|[[File:Grad\u00eb ceremoniali, Drejtues Madhor (Policia e Shtetit).svg|35px]]\n|[[File:Grad\u00eb ceremoniali, Drejtues i Lart\u00eb (Policia e Shtetit).svg|35px]]\n|[[File:Grad\u00eb ceremoniali, Drejtues i Par\u00eb (Policia e Shtetit).svg|35px]]\n|[[File:Grad\u00eb ceremoniali, Drejtues (Policia e Shtetit).svg|35px]]\n|[[File:Grad\u00eb ceremoniali, Kryekomisar (Policia e Shtetit).svg|35px]]\n|[[File:Grad\u00eb ceremoniali, Komisar (Policia e Shtetit).svg|35px]]\n|[[File:Grad\u00eb ceremoniali, N\u00ebnkomisar (Policia e Shtetit).svg|35px]]\n|[[File:Grad\u00eb ceremoniali, Inspektor (Policia e Shtetit).svg|35px]]\n|[[File:Grad\u00eb ceremoniali, Kursant\u00eb (Policia e Shtetit).svg|35px]]\n|-\n| Rank:\n| Chief Director <br> ''Drejtues Madhor''\n| Senior Director <br> ''Drejtues i Lart\u00eb''\n| First Director <br> ''Drejtues i Par\u00eb''\n| Director <br> ''Drejtues''\n| Chief <br>  Commissioner <br> ''Kryekomisar''\n| [[Police commissioner|Commissioner]] <br> ''Komisar''\n| Sub-<br>commissioner <br> ''N\u00ebnkomisar''\n| [[Inspector]] <br> ''Inspektor''\n| [[Cadet]] <br> ''Kursant\u00eb''\n|}\n\n===Pre-2015 ranks===\n{| style=\"width:50%; border:1px solid #8888aa; background:#fff; padding:0; font-size:90%; margin:0 12px 12px 0; text-align:center;\"\n|- style=\"background:#DCDCDC;\"\n!\n! colspan=\"13\" | Rank insignia of the Albanian State Police 1991-2014<ref name=\"Pre-2015\">{{cite web|title=Albanian Police|date=2013|publisher=Uniforminsignia.net|url=http://mobile.www.uniforminsignia.org/?option=com_insigniasearch&Itemid=53&result=1766|accessdate=26 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#efefef;\"\n| Uniform\n|[[File:None.svg|35px]]\n|[[File:None.svg|35px]]\n|[[File:None.svg|35px]]\n|[[File:None.svg|35px]]\n|[[File:None.svg|35px]]\n|[[File:None.svg|35px]]\n|[[File:None.svg|35px]]\n|[[File:None.svg|35px]]\n|[[File:None.svg|35px]]\n|[[File:None.svg|35px]]\n|[[File:None.svg|35px]]\n|[[File:None.svg|35px]]\n|[[File:None.svg|35px]]\n|-\n| Rank:\n| First Director <br> ''Drejtues i Par\u00eb''\n| Director <br> ''Drejtues''\n| Chief Commissioner <br> ''Kryekomisar''\n| Commissioner <br> ''Komisar''\n| Lieutenant Commissioner<br> ''Komisar toger''\n| Chief Inspector <br> ''Kryeinspektor''\n| Inspector <br> ''Inspektor''\n| Lieutenant Inspector <br> ''Inspektor toger''\n| Chief Assistant <br> ''Kryeasistent''\n| First Assistant <br> ''Asistent i par\u00eb''\n| Assistant <br> ''Asistent''\n| First Agent <br> ''Agjent i par\u00eb''\n| Agent <br> ''Agjent''\n|}\n\n==Branch units==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width: 50%;\"\n|-\n! Patch !! Branch unit\n|-\n| [[File:Policia e Rendit.svg|center|33px]] || '''[[Order Police (Albania)|Policia e Rendit]]'''<br>The Order Police is tasked to deal with issues of public order.\n|-\n| [[File:Policia Kufitare.svg|center|33px]] || '''[[Border and Migration Police (Albania)|Policia Kufitare dhe Migracionit]]'''<br/>The Border Police is in charge of patrolling the border.\n|-\n| [[File:Policia Rrugore.svg|center|33px]] || '''[[Road Police (Albania)|Policia Rrugore]]'''<br>The Road Police administers road safety.\n|-\n| [[File:Forcat e Nd\u00ebrhyrjes s\u00eb Shpejt\u00eb.svg|center|33px]] || '''[[Rapid Intervention Force (Albania)|Forcat e Nd\u00ebrhyrjes s\u00eb Shpejt\u00eb]]'''<br>The Rapid Intervention Force is the quick intervention unit dealing mostly with cases of violent riots, special operations, etc.\n|-\n| [[File:Shqiponjat.svg|center|33px]] || '''[[Shqiponjat (police unit)|Shqiponjat]]'''<br>The Eagles are a rapid intervention unit that handles domestic criminal activities.\n|-\n| [[File:RENEA.svg|center|33px]] || '''[[RENEA]]'''<br>The Department of Neutralization of Armed Elements is the main [[counter-terrorism]] and critical incident response unit.\n|}\n\n==Equipment==\n* [[Glock 34]]\n* [[TT-33]]\n* [[Beretta 92]]\n* [[Beretta PX4 Storm]]\n* [[Beretta ARX 160]]\n* [[HS Produkt VHS]]\n* [[Heckler & Koch MP5]]\n* [[Heckler & Koch MP7]]\n* [[AK-47]]\n*[[Sako TRG M10]]\n*[[Land Rover Defender|Land Rover Defend]] [[4x4]] [[Turkey]] has donated armored vehicles<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://armyrecognition.com/january_2020_global_defense_security_army_news_industry/turkey_has_donated_armored_vehicles_and_security_equipment_to_albania_police.html|website=armyrecognition.com|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n\n== Directors == \n{| cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"3\" style=\"border:1px solid #000000; font-size:88%; line-height: 1.5em;\"\n|-\n|'''{{underline|No.}}'''\n|'''{{underline|Name}}'''\n|colspan=\"2\"|<center>'''{{underline|Term in office}}'''</center>\n|-\n|align=center|1\n|Halim Gostivari\n|13 January 1913\n|24 May 1913\n|-\n|align=center|2\n|Feim Mezhgorani\n|24 May 1913\n|30 January 1914\n|-\n|align=center|3\n|[[Hil Mosi]]\n|1 February 1914\n|30 March 1914\n|-\n|align=center|4\n|Veli Vasjari\n|1 April 1914\n|30 June 1914\n|-\n|align=center|5\n|Sulejman K\u00ebr\u00e7iku\n|2 October 1914\n|27 January 1916\n|-\n|align=center|6\n|Halim Gostivari\n|28 August 1919\n|17 December 1920\n|-\n|align=center|7\n|Ahmet Sinani\n|17 December 1920\n|10 January 1922\n|-\n|align=center|8\n|Veli Vasjari\n|11 January 1922\n|22 April 1922\n|-\n|align=center|9\n|Halim Gostivari\n|22 April 1922\n|21 August 1922\n|-\n|align=center|10\n|Musa \u00c7elepia\n|21 August 1922\n|26 December 1922\n|-\n|align=center|11\n|Hamza Isaraj\n|10 December 1924\n|25 December 1924\n|-\n|align=center|12\n|Qazim Bodinaku\n|24 February 1926\n|7 July 1926\n|-\n|align=center|13\n|Rrustem Ymeri\n|20 December 1926\n|1927\n|-\n|align=center|14\n|[[Hil Mosi]]\n|3 September 1928\n|1929\n|-\n|align=center|15\n|Zef Kadarja\n|31 August 1940\n|23 March 1942\n|-\n|align=center|16\n|Theodor Stamati\n|24 March 1942\n|26 November 1942\n|-\n|align=center|17\n|Shyqyri Borshi\n|26 November 1942\n|4 June 1943\n|-\n|align=center|18\n|Gjush Deda\n|4 June 1943\n|30 August 1943\n|-\n|align=center|19\n|Kol\u00eb Radovani\n|1 September 1943\n|13 October 1943\n|-\n|align=center|20\n|Sk\u00ebnder Selmanaj\n|15 October 1943\n|10 January 1944\n|-\n|align=center|21\n|Tahir Kolgjini\n|10 January 1944\n|24 November 1944\n|-\n|align=center|22\n|Namik Xhafa\n|24 November 1944\n|20 March 1947\n|-\n|align=center|23\n|Lako Polena\n|24 March 1947\n|2 February 1948\n|-\n|align=center|24\n|[[Sali Orm\u00ebni]]\n|16 February 1948\n|2 March 1951\n|-\n|align=center|25\n|Maqo \u00c7omo\n|2 March 1951\n|March 1952\n|-\n|align=center|26\n|Delo Balili\n|March 1952\n|1 May 1956\n|-\n|align=center|27\n|Xhule \u00c7iraku\n|1 May 1956\n|February 1968\n|-\n|align=center|28\n|Kas\u00ebm Kaso\n|February 1968\n|January 1980\n|-\n|align=center|29\n|Agron Tafa\n|January 1980\n|August 1982\n|-\n|align=center|30\n|Kas\u00ebm Kaso\n|August 1982\n|31 December 1984\n|-\n|align=center|31\n|Dilaver Bengasi\n|1 January 1987\n|17 July 1990\n|-\n|align=center|32\n|Fadil Cani\n|17 July 1990\n|1 May 1992\n|-\n|align=center|33\n|Astrit Mehaj\n|1 May 1992\n|22 June 1993\n|-\n|align=center|34\n|Sabri Jacaj\n|22 June 1993\n|15 June 1995\n|-\n|align=center|35\n|Agim Shehu\n|15 June 1995\n|30 June 1997\n|-\n|align=center|36\n|Sokol Baraj\n|3 July 1997\n|16 May 1998\n|-\n|align=center|37\n|Besnik Bregu\n|16 May 1998\n|4 September 1998\n|-\n|align=center|38\n|Hasan Ahmetaj\n|4 September 1998\n|9 November 1998\n|-\n|align=center|39\n|Veton Gjoliku\n|9 November 1998\n|20 January 1999\n|-\n|align=center|40\n|Veli Myftari\n|20 January 1999\n|22 November 2000\n|-\n|align=center|41\n|Bilbil Mema\n|23 November 2000\n|19 August 2002\n|-\n|align=center|42\n|Bajram Ibraj\n|12 September 2002\n|30 March 2007\n|-\n|align=center|43\n|Ahmet Pren\u00e7i\n|30 March 2007\n|28 October 2009\n|-\n|align=center|44\n|Hysni Burgaj\n|28 October 2009\n|9 September 2013\n|-\n|align=center|45\n|Artan Didi\n|10 October 2013\n|31 March 2015\n|-\n|align=center|46\n|Haki \u00c7ako\n|15 April 2015\n|8 January 2018\n|-\n|align=center|47\n|Ardi Veliu\n|5 February 2018\n|''Incumbent''\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Police_car_Albania_04.jpg|Cars used by ASP\nFile:Sterff.jpg|Albanian Police Training\nFile:RENEA_exhibition_ALMEX_2010.jpg|RENEA Special Forces Showcase in Tirana\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Law enforcement in Albania]]\n*[[General Directorate of Civil Emergencies]]\n*[[Sigurimi]]\n\n\n{{Police}}\n{{Law enforcement in Albania}}\n{{Albania topics}}\n[[Category:National law enforcement agencies]]\n[[Category:Law enforcement agencies of Albania]]\n[[Category:National Central Bureaus of Interpol]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePublic Perception:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 0-100 \u2192 0\u2013100", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albanian_Police"}
{"title_page": "Chai Vang", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|text = [[Murder of Cha Vang|Cha Vang]], another Hmong American who was murdered in another racially motivated attack in [[Green Bay, Wisconsin|Green Bay]], [[Wisconsin]]}}\n{{Infobox murderer\n| image      = Vang-mug.jpg\n| image_size =\n| occupation = [[Truck driver]]\n| birth_name  = Chai Soua Vang\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1968|09|24}} \n| birth_place   = [[Laos]]\n| death_date      = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place =\n| death_cause = \n| penalty    = Six consecutive life terms plus seventy years\n| parents    =\n| spouse     =\n| children = 7\n| date       = November 21, 2004\n| time       =\n| targets    =\n| locations  = [[Meteor, Wisconsin|Meteor]], Wisconsin, US\n| fatalities = 6\n| injuries   = 2\n| weapons    = [[7.62\u00d739mm]] [[Saiga semi-automatic rifle|Saiga]]\n}}\n\n'''Chai Soua Vang''' (born September 24, 1968) is a [[Hmong American]] who was convicted of [[murder]] by an all-white jury, having claimed self-defense after suffering a racially motivated attack. Vang, a six-year veteran of the [[California National Guard]], shot eight people after being shot at while he was on a [[hunting]] trip in northern Wisconsin on November 21, 2004; six were killed and two were wounded.\n\nVang, who lived in [[Saint Paul, Minnesota]] at the time of the shootings, is imprisoned at the [[Iowa State Penitentiary|Anamosa State Penitentiary]], as of 2006.<ref>\n{{cite web|title= Chai Vang moved to Iowa prison|url= http://www.tcdailyplanet.net/news/2006/04/25/chai-vang-moved-iowa-prison|author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date= 25 April 2006|publisher= [[Daily Planet]]|access-date= 17 December 2015|quote= According to officials at the Wisconsin Department of Corrections, Chai Vang was moved to an Iowa prison because of security concerns.|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100514173853/http://www.tcdailyplanet.net/news/2006/04/25/chai-vang-moved-iowa-prison|archive-date= 2010-05-14|url-status= live}}\n</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nVang's father had served in a [[Laotian Civil War|secret war]] that was funded and organized by the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA). During the war, the CIA recruited the [[Hmong people|Hmong]] who lived in Laos and they assisted the CIA by disrupting supply routes which stretched from [[Laos]] to [[Vietnam]] during the [[Vietnam War]]. [[Vang Pao|General Vang Pao]] was the leader of this army and as a result, he was regarded as a father figure by the Hmong. After the United States made the decision to withdraw troops from Laos in 1972, Vang and his family escaped the Hmong genocide that was ordered by the [[Pathet Lao]] in order to \"exterminate the Hmong down to the last root\" in retaliation for their assistance to the United States. Many Hmong were able to relocate to the U.S., however, thousands of them were left behind and killed. Vang and his siblings relocated to the United States in 1980 and settled in [[California]]. Vang lived in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] and eventually enlisted in the [[California National Guard]].\n\nSometime around 2000, Vang and his family moved to the Twin Cities Capital City of [[St. Paul]], neighboring Minneapolis, Minnesota.\n\nVang is the father of seven children. He is also a family [[shaman]]<ref>\n{{cite news|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2004/12/01/us/hmong-hunter-charged-with-6-murders-is-said-to-be-a-shaman.html|title= Hmong Hunter Charged With 6 Murders Is Said to Be a Shaman|last1= Kinzer|first1= Stephen|date= 1 December 2004|newspaper= [[The New York Times]]|access-date= 17 December 2015|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160504124052/http://www.nytimes.com/2004/12/01/us/hmong-hunter-charged-with-6-murders-is-said-to-be-a-shaman.html|archive-date= 2016-05-04|url-status= live}}\n</ref> and was a hunting enthusiast.\n\n== Shootings ==\nOn the weekend of the shootings, Vang went out deer hunting with two friends and their two sons in northwest [[Wisconsin]], a region where deer hunting is particularly popular, east of [[Birchwood, Wisconsin]] around the town of [[Meteor, Wisconsin|Meteor]]. Meteor extends over a large sparsely populated area.  The land in the area is a mix of public and private.  It is believed that Vang and his friends began their day on public land, but he later went onto a private 400 [[acre]] (1.6&nbsp;km\u00b2) tract of land.\n\nOn Sunday, November 21, a hunting party of about 15 people were in a [[hunting cabin|cabin]] on this private land.  Terry Willers, one of the two co-owners of the land, left the cabin and saw Vang sitting in a deer stand. Willers used a handheld [[radio]] to ask the people still in the cabin whether or not anyone should be in the stand. Upon receiving a response in the negative, he approached Vang and told him to leave the property. Vang then apologized and started moving south towards a trail through a forested area of the property.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://madison.com/news/the-vang-trial-witness-landowner-swore-at-vang/article_a976cb77-d669-5ca9-b451-6df3fb95eb41.html|title=THE VANG TRIAL WITNESS: LANDOWNER SWORE AT VANG|first=ROBERT IMRIE Associated|last=Press|website=madison.com}}</ref> According to Terry Willers' testimony, \"As Bob got back on the radio and asked me where he was at and I said, uh, he's heading south down on the food plot right now. I radioed in to the cabin that I had a tree-rat and I had chased him off.\" At that point five of the hunters from the cabin who had heard the radio message arrived at the tree stand. Lauren Hesebeck, a surviving victim, stated \"Bob had said I'm going to go talk to him to find out who he is, why he's there, and make sure he doesn't, you know, knows that he's on private property and that he's not welcomed there. Denny had said to me this ought to be interesting, let's go and see what's going on. We got in the back of it standing up (ATV), hanging on the rear bar.\"<ref>http://www.beloitdailynews.com/wisconsin/survivor-owner-of-woods-had-kicked-out-hunters/article_87179c3c-c2ed-5d7e-8007-4f5d19cef6b7.html{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DNqvvtL-ggw&list=TL4RUw6Nqwu7ui-vcnq7jF0L6Ie0R-0MX4|title=Chai Vang|via=YouTube}}</ref> After following the directions given by Willers, they proceeded to approach Vang further down the trail. Crotteau then suggested making a note of his hunting license number to make a report to the DNR and, according to Hesebeck's testimony, Crotteau \"flipped over the hunting tag on Vang's back to get his license number\".<ref name=ImrieAP>{{cite news|last1=Imrie|first1=Robert|title=Survivor of hunting clash testifies; Jury in Vang trial is told land owner 'was sick' of Hmong trespassers|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-11176563.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220194943/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-11176563.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=20 February 2016|accessdate=16 November 2015|agency=Associated Press|date=14 September 2005}}</ref>\n\nThe events after the confrontation are disputed.  A violent altercation broke out and four of the eight victims were shot in the back, and three of these four were hit by multiple rounds. Vang is believed to have fired about 20 rounds from a Saiga rifle chambered in [[7.62\u00d739mm]], which was recovered by police.  One of the wounded hunters died the next day, bringing the toll to six dead and two wounded.\n\nVang fled the scene on foot and discarded his remaining ammunition, later stating that he did not want to shoot anyone else.  Vang eventually came across another hunter riding an ATV (who had no affiliation with the victims), and this hunter offered to give Vang a ride, eventually taking him to Vang's cabin.  Vang was arrested when he returned to his cabin five hours after the shooting.  An officer waiting for Vang placed him into custody and transported him to the Sawyer County Jail.  His bail was set at $2.5 million.\n\n=== Victims ===\nThe victims were part of a group of about 15 people who made an annual opening-weekend trip to the Crotteau-Willers property.  Among those killed were father and son Robert and Joey Crotteau and Willers' daughter Jessica Willers.\n\nThose who were killed:\n\n* Robert Crotteau, 42\n* Joey Crotteau, 20\n* Alan Laski, 43\n* Mark Roidt, 28\n* Jessica Willers, 27\n* Denny Drew, 55\n\nThose who were wounded:\n* Lauren Hesebeck, 48\n* Terry Willers, 47\n\n== Investigation ==\nThere were conflicting reports about what may have led to the shootings. According to subsequent oral statements by Vang, one of the local hunters, Terry Willers, took the first shots at him from about 100 feet (30 m) away, and therefore the shootings in retaliation were in self-defense. No shell casing was ever recovered from Willers' gun as it was not analysed even though during the trial Hesebeck had admitted to firing a single shot later during the incident when Vang, noticing that Hesebeck was still alive, fired at him again. Hesebeck testified that no shot was fired before Vang started shooting. Additional forensic analysis of Willers' gun was not performed by the local law enforcement. The statements of both Vang and Hesebeck state that Vang removed the scope from his rifle before firing his first shot. \n\n===Racial motivation===\n\nVang stated that [[Race (classification of human beings)|racial]] resentment was a factor, alleging that during the verbal dispute, some of the local hunters yelled out racial slurs at him such as \"[[chink]]\" and \"[[gook]].\" On the stand, Hesebeck admitted that Robert Crotteau had called Vang a \"Hmong a--hole\" and \"chink\". Hesebeck also claimed that he told law enforcement that Robert Crotteau had problems with trespassers in the past, specifically citing Hmong hunters, who often travel to Wisconsin from Minnesota to hunt. He also claimed that the term \"Mud Duck\" is often used in Western Wisconsin to refer to Minnesota residents and in turn the term \"Cheesehead\" being used to describe Wisconsin residents. Willers used this term to describe Chai Vang when he radioed back to the cabin. Though the term does not necessarily have a racial connotation, the defense argued that it did, due to the fact that Willers and the others did not know at the time that Vang was from Minnesota.\n\nThe criminal complaint states that Vang shot four of the victims in the back, and Vang himself admits he shot one victim in the back. The all-white prosecution made use of these facts in arguing against the claim of self-defense.\n\n== Trial ==\nThe trial of Chai Soua Vang began Saturday, September 10, 2005 in Sawyer County Courthouse.  All fourteen jurors were selected from [[Dane County, Wisconsin]], and bused about {{convert|280|mi|km}} northwest to Sawyer County, where they were sequestered.\n\nVang told the jury he feared for his life and began firing only after another hunter's shot nearly hit him. He detailed for the jurors how the other hunters approached him, and how he responded by shooting at each one.  He says he shot two of the victims in the back because they were \"disrespectful.\" He recounted with clarity how he killed each victim. While saying on the stand, \"(he wished) it wasn't happening,\" Vang contended that three of the hunters deserved to die:\n\n\"Did Mr. Crotteau deserve to die?\" Wisconsin Attorney General Peg Lautenschlager asked.\n\n\"Yes,\" Chai Soua Vang replied.\n\nVang further testified that Joseph Crotteau deserved to die \"because he accused me of giving him the finger and tried to cut in front of me to stop me from leaving.\" And Laski deserved to die because he had a gun, he said.<ref>{{cite news |title= Vang tells his story to Jury |newspaper = [[St. Paul Pioneer Press]] |date= 16 September 2005}}</ref> Vang re-enacted his deeds while on the stand, using his hands and arms to imitate the motions of firing a rifle. Vang's lawyers commented that some of his abnormal remarks were due to the [[language barrier]]. Therefore, when Vang responded affirmatively to the question that Mr. Crotteau and Mr. Laski \"deserved to die,\" his meaning implied that the men contributed to the circumstances that led to their deaths.\n \n=== Conviction ===\nOn September 16, 2005, Chai Soua Vang was found guilty of all six charges of first-degree intentional homicide and three charges of attempted homicide by a jury of eight women and four men, all white. On November 8, 2005, he was sentenced to six consecutive life terms plus seventy years (forty for two counts of attempted homicide plus five additional years for each count of homicide in the first degree); a sentence of [[life without parole]]. At the time, [[Wisconsin]] was one of 12 states in the United States that did not have the [[death penalty]].<ref>\n{{cite web| url= http://www.nbcnews.com/id/9972929/ns/us_news-crime_and_courts/t/hunter-receives-life-prison-killing-six-men/#.VnJhgRV96VM| title= Hunter receives life in prison for killing six men| author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->| publisher= NBC News| agency= Associated Press| date= 11 August 2005| accessdate= 17 December 2015| quote= Judge Norman Yackel ordered Chai Soua Vang, 37, to serve six life prison terms, one after the other, guaranteeing he would never be freed from prison. Wisconsin does not have a death penalty ... Vang ... was convicted on six counts of first-degree intentional homicide and three counts of attempted homicide in the Nov. 21 slayings ... The judge also sentenced Vang to three concurrent terms of 40 years in prison on the attempted homicide charges.| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151007182627/http://www.nbcnews.com/id/9972929/ns/us_news-crime_and_courts/t/hunter-receives-life-prison-killing-six-men/#.VnJhgRV96VM#.VnJhgRV96VM| archive-date= 2015-10-07| url-status= live}}\n</ref>\n\n== Reaction ==\n\nCustom Now, a store in the River Hills Mall, began selling bumper stickers saying, \"Save a deer, shoot a Mung.\" After receiving complaints about the [[racist]] nature of the stickers, the store soon stopped selling them.<ref>http://www.nbcnews.com/id/6709956/ns/us_news-life/t/bumper-sticker-advocates-anti-hmong-violence/</ref> Sometime later that year after the shooting, Chai Vang's home was burned down; the fire was deemed to be suspicious due to graffiti being found with profane and racist language on the concrete blocks by the home, but it was never investigated further.<ref>http://www.weau.com/home/headlines/2020507.html</ref>\n\nIt was speculated that the killing of another Hmong individual, a 30-year-old man named Cha Vang, by [[James Nichols (convicted murderer)|James Nichols]] was influenced by the trial of Chai Vang. Cha Vang was shot with a shotgun, stabbed six times in the face and neck, and had his corpse hidden in the woods. Before killing Vang, Nichols made statements that Hmong people are \"mean\", \"bad\", and \"go for anything that moves\". His employer testified that two months before the killing, Nichols mentioned that he would have killed a Hmong hunter that he had seen in the woods if he had been carrying a shotgun.<ref>https://www.newspapers.com/clip/1400868/cha_vang_murder/</ref><ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20071011005001/http://www.cnn.com/2007/US/10/06/hunter.homicide.ap/index.html</ref> On October 6, 2007, an all-white jury found Nichols guilty of a lesser charge of second-degree intentional homicide and sentenced him to 60 years in prison. \"The message sent to the Hmong community is that someone can shoot a Hmong hunter and not get the maximum sentence,\" said Tou Ger Xiong, spokesman for the Coalition for Community Relations in St. Paul, Minnesota.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20071011005001/http://www.cnn.com/2007/US/10/06/hunter.homicide.ap/index.html</ref>\n\n== Military experience ==\n* Six years in the California National Guard, 1989\u20131995\n* Sharpshooter qualification badge (mid-level, above \"[[Marksman]]\")\n* Good Conduct medal\n\n==See also==\n*[[Racial discrimination in jury selection]]\n*[[Murder of Vincent Chin]]\n\n==Sources==\n* Ashley H. Grant (November 24, 2004). [http://www.duluthsuperior.com/mld/duluthsuperior/news/politics/10258341.htm \"Shooting suspect had Army sharpshooting badge,\"]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}  ''Duluth News Tribune''/Associated Press.  Accessed November 27, 2004.\n* \"Victims in the Shootings That Killed Six Deer Hunters,\" ''Duluth News Tribune''/Associated Press.  Posted on Sep. 04,2005.\n* Kevin Harter \"Vang Tells His Story,\" ''Pioneer Press'', (September 16, 2005).\n* \"Hmong Hunters Are Up For a New Season,\" ''Asian Week'', (November 11, 2005).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://wcca.wicourts.gov/caseDetails.do;jsessionid=2568C7FBE8811864364A76DDE7D54C0D.render12?caseNo=2004CF000141&countyNo=57&cacheId=2DC441EBEDBF986645848DAE3CDB193A&recordCount=46&offset=20 Wisconsin Court Record]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070503020622/http://www.courttv.com/trials/vang/ Court TV's complete coverage of the Chai Vang trial]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vang, Chai}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Laotian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American people of Hmong descent]]\n[[Category:American mass murderers]]\n[[Category:American prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 2004]]\n[[Category:2004 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:Murder in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:2004 mass shootings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Attacks in the United States in 2004]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Racially motivated violence against Asian-Americans]]\n[[Category:Xenophobia]]\n[[Category:Hatred]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|text = [[Murder of Cha Vang|Cha Vang]], another Hmong American who was murdered in another racially motivated attack in [[Green Bay, Wisconsin|Green Bay]], [[Wisconsin]]}}\n{{Infobox murderer\n| image      = Vang-mug.jpg\n| image_size =\n| occupation = [[Truck driver]]\n| birth_name  = Chai Soua Vang\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1968|09|24}} \n| birth_place   = [[Laos]]\n| death_date      = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place =\n| death_cause = \n| penalty    = Six consecutive life terms plus seventy years\n| parents    =\n| spouse     =\n| children = 7\n| date       = November 21, 2004\n| time       =\n| targets    =\n| locations  = [[Meteor, Wisconsin|Meteor]], Wisconsin, US\n| fatalities = 6\n| injuries   = 2\n| weapons    = [[7.62\u00d739mm]] [[Saiga semi-automatic rifle|Saiga]]\n}}\n\n'''Chai Soua Vang''' (born September 24, 1968) is a [[Hmong American]] who was convicted of [[murder]] by an all-white jury, having claimed self-defense after suffering a racially motivated attack. Vang, a six-year veteran of the [[California National Guard]], shot eight people after being shot at while he was on a [[hunting]] trip in northern Wisconsin on November 21, 2004; six were killed and two were wounded.\n\nVang, who lived in [[Saint Paul, Minnesota]] at the time of the shootings, is imprisoned at the [[Iowa State Penitentiary|Anamosa State Penitentiary]], as of 2006.<ref>\n{{cite web|title= Chai Vang moved to Iowa prison|url= http://www.tcdailyplanet.net/news/2006/04/25/chai-vang-moved-iowa-prison|author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date= 25 April 2006|publisher= [[Daily Planet]]|access-date= 17 December 2015|quote= According to officials at the Wisconsin Department of Corrections, Chai Vang was moved to an Iowa prison because of security concerns.|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100514173853/http://www.tcdailyplanet.net/news/2006/04/25/chai-vang-moved-iowa-prison|archive-date= 2010-05-14|url-status= live}}\n</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nVang's father had served in a [[Laotian Civil War|secret war]] that was funded and organized by the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA). During the war, the CIA recruited the [[Hmong people|Hmong]] who lived in Laos and they assisted the CIA by disrupting supply routes which stretched from [[Laos]] to [[Vietnam]] during the [[Vietnam War]]. [[Vang Pao|General Vang Pao]] was the leader of this army and as a result, he was regarded as a father figure by the Hmong. After the United States made the decision to withdraw troops from Laos in 1972, Vang and his family escaped the Hmong genocide that was ordered by the [[Pathet Lao]] in order to \"exterminate the Hmong down to the last root\" in retaliation for their assistance to the United States. Many Hmong were able to relocate to the U.S., however, thousands of them were left behind and killed. Vang and his siblings relocated to the United States in 1980 and settled in [[California]]. Vang lived in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] and eventually enlisted in the [[California National Guard]].\n\nSometime around 2000, Vang and his family moved to the Twin Cities Capital City of [[St. Paul]], neighboring Minneapolis, Minnesota.\n\nVang is the father of seven children. He is also a family [[shaman]]<ref>\n{{cite news|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2004/12/01/us/hmong-hunter-charged-with-6-murders-is-said-to-be-a-shaman.html|title= Hmong Hunter Charged With 6 Murders Is Said to Be a Shaman|last1= Kinzer|first1= Stephen|date= 1 December 2004|newspaper= [[The New York Times]]|access-date= 17 December 2015|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160504124052/http://www.nytimes.com/2004/12/01/us/hmong-hunter-charged-with-6-murders-is-said-to-be-a-shaman.html|archive-date= 2016-05-04|url-status= live}}\n</ref> and was a hunting enthusiast.\n\n== Shootings ==\nOn the weekend of the shootings, Vang went out deer hunting with two friends and their two sons in northwest [[Wisconsin]], a region where deer hunting is particularly popular, east of [[Birchwood, Wisconsin]] around the town of [[Meteor, Wisconsin|Meteor]]. Meteor extends over a large sparsely populated area.  The land in the area is a mix of public and private.  It is believed that Vang and his friends began their day on public land, but he later went onto a private 400 [[acre]] (1.6&nbsp;km\u00b2) tract of land.\n\nOn Sunday, November 21, a hunting party of about 15 people were in a [[hunting cabin|cabin]] on this private land.  Terry Willers, one of the two co-owners of the land, left the cabin and saw Vang sitting in a deer stand. Willers used a handheld [[radio]] to ask the people still in the cabin whether or not anyone should be in the stand. Upon receiving a response in the negative, he approached Vang and told him to leave the property. Vang then apologized and started moving south towards a trail through a forested area of the property.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://madison.com/news/the-vang-trial-witness-landowner-swore-at-vang/article_a976cb77-d669-5ca9-b451-6df3fb95eb41.html|title=THE VANG TRIAL WITNESS: LANDOWNER SWORE AT VANG|first=ROBERT IMRIE Associated|last=Press|website=madison.com}}</ref> According to Terry Willers' testimony, \"As Bob got back on the radio and asked me where he was at and I said, uh, he's heading south down on the food plot right now. I radioed in to the cabin that I had a tree-rat and I had chased him off.\" At that point five of the hunters from the cabin who had heard the radio message arrived at the tree stand. Lauren Hesebeck, a surviving victim, stated \"Bob had said I'm going to go talk to him to find out who he is, why he's there, and make sure he doesn't, you know, knows that he's on private property and that he's not welcomed there. Denny had said to me this ought to be interesting, let's go and see what's going on. We got in the back of it standing up (ATV), hanging on the rear bar.\"<ref>http://www.beloitdailynews.com/wisconsin/survivor-owner-of-woods-had-kicked-out-hunters/article_87179c3c-c2ed-5d7e-8007-4f5d19cef6b7.html{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DNqvvtL-ggw&list=TL4RUw6Nqwu7ui-vcnq7jF0L6Ie0R-0MX4|title=Chai Vang|via=YouTube}}</ref> After following the directions given by Willers, they proceeded to approach Vang further down the trail. Crotteau then suggested making a note of his hunting license number to make a report to the DNR and, according to Hesebeck's testimony, Crotteau \"flipped over the hunting tag on Vang's back to get his license number\".<ref name=ImrieAP>{{cite news|last1=Imrie|first1=Robert|title=Survivor of hunting clash testifies; Jury in Vang trial is told land owner 'was sick' of Hmong trespassers|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-11176563.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220194943/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-11176563.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=20 February 2016|accessdate=16 November 2015|agency=Associated Press|date=14 September 2005}}</ref>\n\nThe events after the confrontation are disputed.  A violent altercation broke out and four of the eight victims were shot in the back, and three of these four were hit by multiple rounds. Vang is believed to have fired about 20 rounds from a Saiga rifle chambered in [[7.62\u00d739mm]], which was recovered by police.  One of the wounded hunters died the next day, bringing the toll to six dead and two wounded.\n\nVang fled the scene on foot and discarded his remaining ammunition, later stating that he did not want to shoot anyone else.  Vang eventually came across another hunter riding an ATV (who had no affiliation with the victims), and this hunter offered to give Vang a ride, eventually taking him to Vang's cabin.  Vang was arrested when he returned to his cabin five hours after the shooting.  An officer waiting for Vang placed him into custody and transported him to the Sawyer County Jail.  His bail was set at $2.5 million.\n\n=== Victims ===\nThe victims were part of a group of about 15 people who made an annual opening-weekend trip to the Crotteau-Willers property.  Among those killed were father and son Robert and Joey Crotteau and Willers' daughter Jessica Willers.\n\nThose who were killed:\n\n* Robert Crotteau, 42\n* Joey Crotteau, 20\n* Alan Laski, 43\n* Mark Roidt, 28\n* Jessica Willers, 27\n* Denny Drew, 55\n\nThose who were wounded:\n* Lauren Hesebeck, 48\n* Terry Willers, 47\n\n== Investigation ==\nThere were conflicting reports about what may have led to the shootings. According to subsequent oral statements by Vang, one of the local hunters, Terry Willers, took the first shots at him from about 100 feet (30 m) away, and therefore the shootings in retaliation were in self-defense. No shell casing was ever recovered from Willers' gun as it was not analysed even though during the trial Hesebeck had admitted to firing a single shot later during the incident when Vang, noticing that Hesebeck was still alive, fired at him again. Hesebeck testified that no shot was fired before Vang started shooting. Additional forensic analysis of Willers' gun was not performed by the local law enforcement. The statements of both Vang and Hesebeck state that Vang removed the scope from his rifle before firing his first shot. \n\n===Racial motivation===\n\nVang stated that [[Race (classification of human beings)|racial]] resentment was a factor, alleging that during the verbal dispute, some of the local hunters yelled out racial slurs at him such as \"[[chink]]\" and \"[[gook]].\" On the stand, Hesebeck admitted that Robert Crotteau had called Vang a \"Hmong a--hole\" and \"chink\". Hesebeck also claimed that he told law enforcement that Robert Crotteau had problems with trespassers in the past, specifically citing Hmong hunters, who often travel to Wisconsin from Minnesota to hunt. He also claimed that the term \"Mud Duck\" is often used in Western Wisconsin to refer to Minnesota residents and in turn the term \"Cheesehead\" being used to describe Wisconsin residents. Willers used this term to describe Chai Vang when he radioed back to the cabin. Though the term does not necessarily have a racial connotation, the defense argued that it did, due to the fact that Willers and the others did not know at the time that Vang was from Minnesota.\n\nThe criminal complaint states that Vang shot four of the victims in the back, and Vang himself admits he shot one victim in the back. The all-white prosecution made use of these facts in arguing against the claim of self-defense.\n\n== Trial ==\nThe trial of Chai Soua Vang began Saturday, September 10, 2005 in Sawyer County Courthouse.  All fourteen jurors were selected from [[Dane County, Wisconsin]], and bused about {{convert|280|mi|km}} northwest to Sawyer County, where they were sequestered.\n\nVang told the jury he feared for his life and began firing only after another hunter's shot nearly hit him. He detailed for the jurors how the other hunters approached him, and how he responded by shooting at each one.  He says he shot two of the victims in the back because they were \"disrespectful.\" He recounted with clarity how he killed each victim. While saying on the stand, \"(he wished) it wasn't happening,\" Vang contended that three of the hunters deserved to die:\n\n\"Did Mr. Crotteau deserve to die?\" Wisconsin Attorney General Peg Lautenschlager asked.\n\n\"Yes,\" Chai Soua Vang replied.\n\nVang further testified that Joseph Crotteau deserved to die \"because he accused me of giving him the finger and tried to cut in front of me to stop me from leaving.\" And Laski deserved to die because he had a gun, he said.<ref>{{cite news |title= Vang tells his story to Jury |newspaper = [[St. Paul Pioneer Press]] |date= 16 September 2005}}</ref> Vang re-enacted his deeds while on the stand, using his hands and arms to imitate the motions of firing a rifle. Vang's lawyers commented that some of his abnormal remarks were due to the [[language barrier]]. Therefore, when Vang responded affirmatively to the question that Mr. Crotteau and Mr. Laski \"deserved to die,\" his meaning implied that the men contributed to the circumstances that led to their deaths.\n \n=== Conviction ===\nOn September 16, 2005, Chai Soua Vang was found guilty of all six charges of first-degree intentional homicide and three charges of attempted homicide by a jury of eight women and four men. On November 8, 2005, he was sentenced to six consecutive life terms plus seventy years (forty for two counts of attempted homicide plus five additional years for each count of homicide in the first degree); a sentence of [[life without parole]]. At the time, [[Wisconsin]] was one of 12 states in the United States that did not have the [[death penalty]].<ref>\n{{cite web| url= http://www.nbcnews.com/id/9972929/ns/us_news-crime_and_courts/t/hunter-receives-life-prison-killing-six-men/#.VnJhgRV96VM| title= Hunter receives life in prison for killing six men| author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->| publisher= NBC News| agency= Associated Press| date= 11 August 2005| accessdate= 17 December 2015| quote= Judge Norman Yackel ordered Chai Soua Vang, 37, to serve six life prison terms, one after the other, guaranteeing he would never be freed from prison. Wisconsin does not have a death penalty ... Vang ... was convicted on six counts of first-degree intentional homicide and three counts of attempted homicide in the Nov. 21 slayings ... The judge also sentenced Vang to three concurrent terms of 40 years in prison on the attempted homicide charges.| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151007182627/http://www.nbcnews.com/id/9972929/ns/us_news-crime_and_courts/t/hunter-receives-life-prison-killing-six-men/#.VnJhgRV96VM#.VnJhgRV96VM| archive-date= 2015-10-07| url-status= live}}\n</ref>\n\n== Reaction ==\n\nCustom Now, a store in the River Hills Mall, began selling bumper stickers saying, \"Save a deer, shoot a Mung.\" After receiving complaints about the [[racist]] nature of the stickers, the store soon stopped selling them.<ref>http://www.nbcnews.com/id/6709956/ns/us_news-life/t/bumper-sticker-advocates-anti-hmong-violence/</ref> Sometime later that year after the shooting, Chai Vang's home was burned down; the fire was deemed to be suspicious due to graffiti being found with profane and racist language on the concrete blocks by the home, but it was never investigated further.<ref>http://www.weau.com/home/headlines/2020507.html</ref>\n\nIt was speculated that the killing of another Hmong individual, a 30-year-old man named Cha Vang, by [[James Nichols (convicted murderer)|James Nichols]] was influenced by the trial of Chai Vang. Cha Vang was shot with a shotgun, stabbed six times in the face and neck, and had his corpse hidden in the woods. Before killing Vang, Nichols made statements that Hmong people are \"mean\", \"bad\", and \"go for anything that moves\". His employer testified that two months before the killing, Nichols mentioned that he would have killed a Hmong hunter that he had seen in the woods if he had been carrying a shotgun.<ref>https://www.newspapers.com/clip/1400868/cha_vang_murder/</ref><ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20071011005001/http://www.cnn.com/2007/US/10/06/hunter.homicide.ap/index.html</ref> On October 6, 2007, an all-white jury found Nichols guilty of a lesser charge of second-degree intentional homicide and sentenced him to 60 years in prison. \"The message sent to the Hmong community is that someone can shoot a Hmong hunter and not get the maximum sentence,\" said Tou Ger Xiong, spokesman for the Coalition for Community Relations in St. Paul, Minnesota.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20071011005001/http://www.cnn.com/2007/US/10/06/hunter.homicide.ap/index.html</ref>\n\n== Military experience ==\n* Six years in the California National Guard, 1989\u20131995\n* Sharpshooter qualification badge (mid-level, above \"[[Marksman]]\")\n* Good Conduct medal\n\n==See also==\n*[[Racial discrimination in jury selection]]\n*[[Murder of Vincent Chin]]\n\n==Sources==\n* Ashley H. Grant (November 24, 2004). [http://www.duluthsuperior.com/mld/duluthsuperior/news/politics/10258341.htm \"Shooting suspect had Army sharpshooting badge,\"]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}  ''Duluth News Tribune''/Associated Press.  Accessed November 27, 2004.\n* \"Victims in the Shootings That Killed Six Deer Hunters,\" ''Duluth News Tribune''/Associated Press.  Posted on Sep. 04,2005.\n* Kevin Harter \"Vang Tells His Story,\" ''Pioneer Press'', (September 16, 2005).\n* \"Hmong Hunters Are Up For a New Season,\" ''Asian Week'', (November 11, 2005).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://wcca.wicourts.gov/caseDetails.do;jsessionid=2568C7FBE8811864364A76DDE7D54C0D.render12?caseNo=2004CF000141&countyNo=57&cacheId=2DC441EBEDBF986645848DAE3CDB193A&recordCount=46&offset=20 Wisconsin Court Record]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070503020622/http://www.courttv.com/trials/vang/ Court TV's complete coverage of the Chai Vang trial]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vang, Chai}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Laotian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American people of Hmong descent]]\n[[Category:American mass murderers]]\n[[Category:American prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 2004]]\n[[Category:2004 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:Murder in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:2004 mass shootings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Attacks in the United States in 2004]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Racially motivated violence against Asian-Americans]]\n[[Category:Xenophobia]]\n[[Category:Hatred]]\n", "name_user": "Specion", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCo