{"title_page": "Theodosia Wingfield", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Theodosia Wingfield\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Theodosia Anne Howard\n| birth_date         = 1800\n| birth_place        = County Wicklow, Ireland\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|df=y|1836|12|31|1800}}\n| death_place        = Dublin\n| occupation         = evangelical religious writer\n}}\n\n'''Viscountess Powerscourt Theodosia Wingfield''' (1800 \u2013 31 December 1836) was an Irish evangelical religious writer.<ref name=Beaumont>{{cite book|last1=Beaumont|first1=Daniel|editor1-last=McGuire|editor1-first=James|editor2-last=Quinn|editor2-first=James|title=[[Dictionary of Irish Biography]]|date=2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|chapter=Wingfield, Theodosia}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nTheodosia Wingfield was born Theodosia Anne Howard in 1800 in [[County Wicklow]]. Her parents were the gentleman landowner, the Honourable Hugh Howard, and Catherine (n\u00e9e Bligh). Her family were one of a small number of closely related families in the gentry of County Wicklow, who all shared a religious piety around the early 1800s. Wingfield would have seen and met the Reverend [[Robert Daly (bishop)|Robert Daly]] as a child, when he was the rector of [[Powerscourt Estate]]. Wingfield appears to have been deeply affected by the death of the first wife of [[Richard Wingfield, 5th Viscount Powerscourt]], her cousin Francis Theodosia Bligh, at age 25 in 1820, inspiring an intense spirituality. In her earliest printed letters from 1821, she agnoises over the issues raised in sermons, and feels guilt over not praying regularly enough. She married Richard Wingfield in June 1822. He died in August 1823. For the rest of her life, Wingfield earned the title \"good Lady Powerscourt\", by engaging in letter-writing and convening religious meetings in her house.<ref name=\"Beaumont\" /><ref name=\"Bjorie\">{{cite web |last1=Bjorie |first1=John |title=Theodosia, Lady Powerscourt |url=http://www.uplook.org/1994/02/theodosia-lady-powerscourt/ |website=www.uplook.org |accessdate=31 March 2020 |date=1 February 1994}}</ref>\n\nHer letters from the 1820s detail her feelings of feeling \"unworthy\" and needing to suffer more like Christ. She is concerned by the calls for [[Catholic emancipation]], but found solace in the growing numbers of Anglicans in England, Scotland and Europe who held similar beliefs to hers. Wingfield attended the first meetings of the Albury Prophetic Conference in [[London]], and was a frequent attendee at lectures by [[Edward Irving]]. Inspired by this, she organised her own conferences on the meaning of prophecy at Powerscourt from 1827. From the late 1820s she had developed a strong interest in Christ's second coming and charismatic manifestations. She traveled to Brussels and Paris in 1829 and 1830 to meet evangelical preachers, and frequently visited London. She died on 31 December 1836 in Dublin, and is buried at Powerscourt.<ref name=\"Beaumont\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Theodosia Howard |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p3373.htm#i33730 |website=www.thepeerage.com |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThrough her writings, meetings, and connections within the community of evangelical Christians in Ireland, Wingfield was an influential figure throughout the 1820s and 1830s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Powerscourt House and Gardens |url=https://www.irishtourism.com/powerscourt-house-and-gardens1/ |website=Irish Tourism |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> She became famous for her piety after her death after the publication of some of her letters and papers in 1838 by Robert Daly. Daly may have edited her letters to remove elements which did not fit with his beliefs, in particular that she supported the secession of some Anglicans from the [[Church of Ireland]].<ref name=\"Beaumont\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wingfield, Theodosia}}\n[[Category:1800 births]]\n[[Category:1836 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from County Wicklow]]\n[[Category:Irish Anglicans]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Theodosia Wingfield\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Theodosia Anne Howard\n| birth_date         = 1800\n| birth_place        = County Wicklow, Ireland\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|df=y|1836|12|31|1800}}\n| death_place        = Dublin\n| occupation         = evangelical religious writer\n}}\n\n'''Viscountess Powerscourt Theodosia Wingfield''' (1800 \u2013 31 December 1836) was an Irish evangelical religious writer.<ref name=Beaumont>{{cite book|last1=Beaumont|first1=Daniel|editor1-last=McGuire|editor1-first=James|editor2-last=Quinn|editor2-first=James|title=[[Dictionary of Irish Biography]]|date=2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|chapter=Wingfield, Theodosia}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nTheodosia Wingfield was born Theodosia Anne Howard in 1800 in [[County Wicklow]]. Her parents were the gentleman landowner, the Honourable Hugh Howard, and Catherine (n\u00e9e Bligh). Her family were one of a small number of closely related families in the gentry of County Wicklow, who all shared a religious piety around the early 1800s. Wingfield would have seen and met the Reverend [[Robert Daly (bishop)|Robert Daly]] as a child, when he was the rector of [[Powerscourt Estate]]. Wingfield appears to have been deeply affected by the death of the first wife of [[Richard Wingfield, 5th Viscount Powerscourt]], her cousin Francis Theodosia Bligh, at age 25 in 1820, inspiring an intense spirituality. In her earliest printed letters from 1821, she agnoises over the issues raised in sermons, and feels guilt over not praying regularly enough. She married Richard Wingfield in June 1822. He died in August 1823. For the rest of her life, Wingfield earned the title \"good Lady Powerscourt\", by engaging in letter-writing and convening religious meetings in her house.<ref name=\"Beaumont\" /><ref name=\"Bjorie\">{{cite web |last1=Bjorie |first1=John |title=Theodosia, Lady Powerscourt |url=http://www.uplook.org/1994/02/theodosia-lady-powerscourt/ |website=www.uplook.org |accessdate=31 March 2020 |date=1 February 1994}}</ref>\n\nHer letters from the 1820s detail her feelings of feeling \"unworthy\" and needing to suffer more like Christ. She is concerned by the calls for [[Catholic emancipation]], but found solace in the growing numbers of Anglicans in England, Scotland and Europe who held similar beliefs to hers. Wingfield attended the first meetings of the Albury Prophetic Conference in [[London]], and was a frequent attendee at lectures by [[Edward Irving]]. Inspired by this, she organised her own conferences on the meaning of prophecy at Powerscourt from 1827. From the late 1820s she had developed a strong interest in Christ's second coming and charismatic manifestations. She traveled to Brussels and Paris in 1829 and 1830 to meet evangelical preachers, and frequently visited London. She died on 31 December 1836 in Dublin, and is buried at Powerscourt.<ref name=\"Beaumont\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Theodosia Howard |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p3373.htm#i33730 |website=www.thepeerage.com |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThrough her writings, meetings, and connections within the community of evangelical Christians in Ireland, Wingfield was an influential figure throughout the 1820s and 1830s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Powerscourt House and Gardens |url=https://www.irishtourism.com/powerscourt-house-and-gardens1/ |website=Irish Tourism |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> She became famous for her piety after her death after the publication of some of her letters and papers in 1838 by Robert Daly. Daly may have edited her letters to remove elements which did not fit with his beliefs, in partial that she supported the secession of some Anglicans from the [[Church of Ireland]].<ref name=\"Beaumont\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wingfield, Theodosia}}\n[[Category:1800 births]]\n[[Category:1836 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from County Wicklow]]\n[[Category:Irish Anglicans]]\n", "name_user": "Aineireland", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theodosia_Wingfield"}
{"title_page": "Royal Oak Middle School", "text_new": "{{distinguish|text = Royal Oak Middle School of the [[Royal Oak Neighborhood Schools]] in Michigan, U.S.}}\n{{Infobox school\n|name                   = Royal Oak Middle School\n|logo                   = \n|seal_image             = \n|image                  = \n|image_size             = \n|alt                    = \n|caption                = \n|motto                  = Every Student, Every Day; Whatever It Takes\n|motto_translation      = \n|location               = \n|streetaddress          = 303 S. Glendora Ave. Covina, CA 91724 \n|county                 = Los Angeles\n|coordinates            = {{coord|34.0836|-117.8645|type:edu_globe:earth_region:US-CA|display=ti}}\n|schooltype             = Middle School \n|fundingtype            = [[State school|Public]]\n|opened                 = 1927\n|district               = Charter Oak Unified School District\n|us_nces_district_id    = 0608190\n|school code            = 19-64378-6012116\n|us_nces_school_id      = \n|principal              = Dr. Micheal Williams\n|teaching_staff         = 0 cause there broke\n|grades                 =6th, 7th and 8th \n|enrollment             = 1014\n|enrollment_as_of       = (2018-2019)\n|colors                 = {{Color box|blue|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|gray|border=darkgray}} Blue and Gray\n|slogan                 = \n|mascot                 = Roadrunner\n|publication            = \n|communities            = Covina, Glendora, and San Dimas \n|url                    = {{URL|1=http://www.cousd.net/royaloak}}\n\n}}\n'''Royal Oak Middle School''' is the only [[middle school]] in the [[Charter Oak Unified School District]] and is located in the City of [[Covina, California |Covina]], [[California]], in the [[San Gabriel Valley ]] east of [[Los Angeles]]. Royal Oak was a 1996 [[California Distinguished School]] <ref> {{cite web |url=http://www.cde.ca.gov/ta/sr/cs/documents/distinguished.xls | title=1986-2009 Distinguished Schools Data File | format=XLS | website=California Department of Education | access-date=June 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nRoyal Oak Middle School opened in 1985 on the site of the former Royal Oak High School, which opened in 1965. Originally, the middle school served students in sixth through eighth grades.  In 2007, the mission of the school changed to serve only seventh- and eighth-grade students. <ref> {{cite web |url=http://www.sarconline.org/Sarc/About/19643786012116 | title=School Accountability Report Card | website= California Department of Education | access-date=June 13, 2017}} </ref>\n\n==Special programs==\n* [[Advancement Via Individual Determination]]<ref> {{cite web |url=http://www.sarconline.org/Sarc/About/19643786012116 | title=School Accountability Report Card | website= California Department of Education | access-date=June 13, 2017}} </ref>\n* [[Accelerated Reader]]<ref> {{cite web |url=http://www.sarconline.org/Sarc/About/19643786012116 | title=School Accountability Report Card | website= California Department of Education | access-date=June 13, 2017}} </ref>\n* [[Accelerated Math]]<ref> {{cite web |url=http://www.sarconline.org/Sarc/About/19643786012116 | title=School Accountability Report Card | website= California Department of Education | access-date=June 13, 2017}} </ref>\n* [[Gifted and Talented Education]] <ref> {{cite web |url=http://www.couse.net/royaloak | title=Royal Oak Middle School | website= Charter Oak Unified School District | access-date=June 13, 2017}} </ref>\n* [[Positive Behavior Interventions and Supports]]<ref> {{cite web |url=http://www.sarconline.org/Sarc/About/19643786012116 | title=School Accountability Report Card | website= California Department of Education | access-date=June 13, 2017}} </ref>\n* [[Project Lead the Way]] <ref> {{cite web |url=http://www.couse.net/royaloak | title=Royal Oak Middle School | website= Charter Oak Unified School District | access-date=June 13, 2017}} </ref> \n* [[STEAM fields|STEAM]] Academy <ref> {{cite web |url=http://www.couse.net/royaloak | title=Royal Oak Middle School | website= Charter Oak Unified School District | access-date=June 13, 2017}} </ref>\n\n==Enrollment==\n\nEnrollment in the 2016\u20132017 school year is 712. The majority of students are [[Hispanic]], with a large [[white people|white]] minority and smaller minorities of [[African Americans]] and [[Asian Americans]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"text-align:center;  font-size:85%; margin:0px; margin-left:2em;\"\n|+ \nEthnic composition of student body: 2016-17<ref>{{cite web |url=  http://dq.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/dqcensus/EnrEthLevels.aspx?cds=19643786012116&agglevel=school&year=2016-17 | title=2016-17 Enrollment by Ethnicity|publisher=California Department of Education |access-date=June 13, 2017}}</ref>\n! !! Percent\n|-\n! Hispanic or Latino\n| 65.3%\n|-\n! American Indian or Alaska Native\n| 1.0%\n|-\n! Asian\n| 5.6%\n|-\n! Pacific Islander\n| 0.1%\n|-\n! Filipino\n| 1.7%\n|-\n! African American\n| 2.5%\n|-\n! White\n| 20.6%\n|-\n! Two or more Races\n| 3.1%\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Schools in Los Angeles County, California]]\n[[Category:Charter middle schools in California]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1927]]\n[[Category:1927 establishments in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|text = Royal Oak Middle School of the [[Royal Oak Neighborhood Schools]] in Michigan, U.S.}}\n{{Infobox school\n|name                   = Royal Oak Middle School\n|logo                   = \n|seal_image             = \n|image                  = \n|image_size             = \n|alt                    = \n|caption                = \n|motto                  = Every Student, Every Day; Whatever It Takes\n|motto_translation      = \n|location               = \n|streetaddress          = 303 S. Glendora Ave. Covina, CA 91724 \n|county                 = Los Angeles\n|coordinates            = {{coord|34.0836|-117.8645|type:edu_globe:earth_region:US-CA|display=t