{"title_page": "Sunderland A.F.C.", "text_new": "{{For|the Ladies football club|Sunderland A.F.C. Ladies}}\n{{Redirect|SAFC}}\n{{pp-semi-indef|small=yes}}\n{{Short description|Association football club}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| nickname = The Black Cats\n| ground = [[Stadium of Light]]\n| capacity = 49,000\n| season = {{English football updater|Sunderld2}}\n| position = {{English football updater|Sunderld3}}\n| current = 2019\u201320 Sunderland A.F.C. season\n| pattern_la1   = \n| pattern_b1    = _sunderland1920h\n| pattern_ra1   = \n| pattern_sh1   = _adidasred\n| pattern_so1   = _3_stripes_white\n| leftarm1      = FFFFFF\n| body1         = FD1220\n| rightarm1     = FFFFFF\n| shorts1       = 000000\n| socks1        = FF0000\n| pattern_la2   = _sunderland1920a\n| pattern_b2    = _sunderland1920a\n| pattern_ra2   = _sunderland1920a\n| pattern_sh2   = _adidasred\n| pattern_so2   = _color_3_stripes_red\n| leftarm2      = 0000DD\n| body2         = 0000DD\n| rightarm2     = 0000DD\n| shorts2       = 0000DD\n| socks2        = 0000DD\n| clubname = Sunderland A.F.C.\n| image = Logo Sunderland.svg\n| upright = .8\n| fullname = Sunderland Association Football Club\n| short name = SAFC\n| founded = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1879}}<br/>(as ''Sunderland and District Teachers'')\n| owner = [[Stewart Donald]]\n| chairman = \n| manager = [[Phil Parkinson]]\n| league = {{English football updater|Sunderld}}\n| website = http://www.safc.com/\n}}\n'''Sunderland Association Football Club''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=en-uk-Sunderland.ogg|\u02c8|s|\u028c|n|d|\u0259r|l|\u0259|n|d}}, {{IPAc-en|local|\u02c8|s|\u028a|n|d|l|\u0259|n}}) is an English professional [[association football|football]] club based in the city of [[Sunderland]], [[Tyne and Wear]]. Sunderland play in [[EFL League One|League One]], the third tier of English football. Since its formation in 1879,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/teams2.sd?teamid=2493|title=Sunderland|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=19 September 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100510200457/http://www.soccerbase.com/teams2.sd?teamid=2493#|archive-date=10 May 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> the club has won six top-flight ([[Football League First Division|First Division]], now the [[Premier League]]) titles (1892, 1893, 1895, 1902, 1913 and 1936), a total only bettered by five other clubs, and has finished runners-up five times. The club has also won the [[FA Cup]] twice (1937 and 1973) and been runners-up twice (1913 and 1992), as well as winning the [[FA Community Shield|FA Charity Shield]] in 1936 and being finalists the following year. Sunderland have also been [[Football League Cup]] finalists in 1985 and 2014.\n\nSunderland play their home games at the 49,000-capacity [[all-seater stadium|all-seater]] [[Stadium of Light]] having moved from [[Roker Park]] in 1997. The original ground capacity was 42,000 which was increased to 49,000 following expansion in 2000. Sunderland have a long-standing rivalry with their neighbouring club [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], with whom they have contested the [[Tyne\u2013Wear derby]] since 1898.\n\n==History==\n{{main|History of Sunderland A.F.C.}}\n{{For|a statistical breakdown by season|List of Sunderland A.F.C. seasons}}\n\n===Early years and \"the team of all talents\" (1879\u20131908)===\n[[File:Sunderland-1884.jpg|thumb|left|Team photo taken in 1884]]\nThe club was founded as ''<nowiki/>'Sunderland and District Teachers A.F.C''.' by [[schoolmaster]] [[James Allan (footballer, born 1857)|James Allan]] in what has commonly been believed to be October 1879.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.safc.com/history/beginnings|title=Beginnings|work=Sunderland Association Football Club|access-date=6 April 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> However, evidence suggests that the club was not formally created until a year later, on 25 September 1880.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestatcat.co.uk/Article1.aspx|title=Sunderland AFC \u2013 Statistics, History and Records \u2013 from TheStatCat|website=www.thestatcat.co.uk|access-date=2019-01-04}}</ref> It was renamed as ''<nowiki/>'Sunderland A.F.C.''' and became open to more than just school teachers in October 1880.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n[[File:John Middleton Campbell.jpg|thumb|left|[[John Campbell (footballer, born 1870)|John Campbell]], a part of \"the team of all talents\", and league top scorer in Sunderland's first three titles.]]\nSunderland joined [[English Football League|The Football League]] for the [[1890\u201391 Sunderland A.F.C. season|1890\u201391 season]].<ref name=\"History\" /> They replaced [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke]], who had failed to be re-elected, becoming the first new club to join the league since its inauguration in 1888.<ref>Days, p 27.</ref> [[Tom Watson (football manager)|Tom Watson]] became Sunderland's first manager when he was appointed in 1888.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/history/?page_id=2997|title=Past Managers 1889\u20131939|publisher=Sunderland A.F.C.|accessdate=6 January 2009}}</ref> During the late 19th century, they were declared the \"Team of All Talents\" by [[William McGregor (football)|William McGregor]],<ref name=\"Days21\">Days, p 21.</ref> the founder of the league, after a 7\u20132 win against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]].<ref name=\"Days21\" /> Sunderland won the league championship in the [[1891\u201392 Sunderland A.F.C. season|1891\u201392 season]], one season after joining The Football League. The club's 42 points were five clear of nearest rivals [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]], and this performance led ''[[The Times]]'' to describe the players as \"a wonderfully fine team\".<ref name=\"TheTimes\">Days, pp 29\u201330.</ref> Sunderland successfully defended the title the following season, aided by their Scottish [[forward (association football)|centre forward]] [[John Campbell (footballer born 1870)|John Campbell]], who broke the 30-goal mark for the second time in consecutive seasons. In the process, they became the first team to score 100 goals in a season, a feat not matched until [[1919\u201320 in English football|1919\u201320]], when [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] set a new record.<ref>Days, pp 31\u201332.</ref>\n[[File:Thomas Hemy Sunderland v Aston Villa 1895 A Corner Kick.jpg|thumbnail|right|One of the earliest football paintings in the world, Thomas MM Hemy's \"Sunderland v. [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] 1895\" depicts a match between the two most successful English teams of the decade.]]\n\nSunderland came close to winning a third successive league championship in the [[1893\u201394 in English football|1893\u201394 season]], finishing second behind Aston Villa. However, they regained the title in the [[1894\u201395 in English football|1894\u201395 season]], ending the season five points ahead of [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], with Campbell becoming league top scorer for the third time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2016/7/20/12222208/sunderland-s-first-great-centre-forward|title=Sunderland's First Great Centre Forward|date=20 July 2016|website=Roker Report}}</ref> After winning the English League Championship, Sunderland beat [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]], the champions of the Scottish League, 5\u20133 in a game described as the ''[[1894/95 World Championship|Championship of the World]]'' title match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heartsfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/HeartsHistory/0,,10289~985232,00.html|title=Hearts History 1894\u20131904|publisher=Hearts F.C.|accessdate=8 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090101160956/http://www.heartsfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/HeartsHistory/0%2C%2C10289~985232%2C00.html|archivedate=1 January 2009}}</ref><ref>Days, pp 35\u201336.</ref>\n\nImportant to Campbell's success in attack were other \"Team of all Talents\" players from [[Scotland]]: [[Jimmy Hannah]] and [[Jimmy Millar (footballer, born 1870)|Jimmy Millar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ryehillfootball.co.uk/stories/johnny-campbell/|title=Johnny Campbell \u2013 Ryehill Football}}</ref> Their goalkeeper [[Ned Doig]] set a 19th-century world record by not conceding any goals in 87 of his 290 top division appearances (30%).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://iffhs.de/history-curiosities-of-world-football-1891-1900/|title=HISTORY : CURIOSITIES OF WORLD FOOTBALL (1891-1900)|date=25 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter taking Sunderland to three English League championship titles manager Watson resigned at the end of the 1895\u201396 season, in order to join Liverpool.<ref name=\"p39\">Days, p. 39.</ref> [[Robert Campbell (football manager)|Robert Campbell]] replaced him.<ref name=\"p39\"/> From 1886 until 1898, Sunderland's home ground was in Newcastle Road.<ref>Days, p. 44.</ref> In 1898, the club moved to what would become their home for almost a century, [[Roker Park]].<ref name=\"rokerpark\">Days, pp. 45\u201346.</ref> Initially the ground had a capacity of 30,000.<ref name=\"rokerpark\"/> However, over the following decades it was continually expanded, and at its peak would hold an official crowd of over 75,000 in a sixth round FA Cup replay against [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] on 8 March 1933.<ref>Days, p. 134.</ref> Campbell did not achieve the same playing success as former manager Watson, as Sunderland failed to win any titles in his three seasons at the club, which he left in the [[1898\u201399 in English football|1898\u201399 season]] to join [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]].<ref>Days, p. 45.</ref>\n\nScotsman [[Alex Mackie]] replaced Campbell as manager for the 1899 season.<ref>Days, pp. 55\u201356.</ref> Following a second-place finish in 1900\u201301, the club won their fourth league title in the [[1901\u201302 in English football|1901\u201302 season]], beating Everton by a three-point margin.<ref>Days, pp 55\u201356.</ref> They followed this up with victory in the [[Sheriff of London Charity Shield]], a competition featuring the best amateur and professional sides in England and precursor to the [[FA Community Shield|Charity Shield]]. Sunderland beat leading amateurs [[Corinthian F.C.|Corinthians]] 3\u20130.<ref>Days, pp. 59\u201360.</ref>\n\nIn December 1902, [[Arthur Bridgett]] joined Sunderland. He went on to captain the \"Black Cats\" for ten years and gain eleven England caps, making him the club's second most-capped England international behind [[David Watson (footballer, born 1946)|Dave Watson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.englandstats.com/club.php?cid=104|title=England Players from Sunderland|accessdate=19 January 2020|publisher=englandstats.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1904, Sunderland's management was embroiled in a payment scandal involving player [[Andy McCombie|Andrew McCombie]]. The club was said to have given the player \u00a3100 (\u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|100|1904|r=-2}}|0}} today) to help him start his own business, on the understanding that he would repay the money after his benefit game.{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}} However, McCombie refused to repay the money, claiming it had been a gift. An investigation conducted by the [[The Football Association|Football Association]] concluded that the money given to McCombie was part of a \"re-signing/win/draw bonus\", which violated the Association's rules. Sunderland were fined \u00a3250 (\u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|250|1904|r=-2}}|0}} today), and six directors were suspended for two and a half years for not showing a true record of the club's financial dealings. Mackie was also suspended for three months for his involvement in the affair.{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}}<ref name=mackie>Days, p 63.</ref>\n\n===Further league championship titles (1908\u20131950)===\nOn 5 December 1908, Sunderland achieved their highest ever league win, against north-east rivals Newcastle United. They won the game 9\u20131; [[Billy Hogg]] and [[George Holley]] each scored [[hat-trick]]s, while [[Arthur Bridgett]] scored two.<ref>Days, pp 73\u201376.</ref> Under [[Ireland|Irish]] manager [[Bob Kyle]] and with [[Scotland|Scottish]] [[Charles Thomson (footballer, born 1878)|Charles Thomson]] as captain, the club won the league again in 1913,<ref>Days, pp 85\u201386.</ref> but lost their first [[FA Cup final]] 1\u20130 to Aston Villa, in a very tough loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=257177|title=English FA Cup&nbsp;\u2014 Final 1913|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=19 December 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050222213709/http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=257177#|archive-date=22 February 2005|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This was the closest the club has come to winning the league title and the FA Cup in the same season.<ref>Days, pp 87\u201388.</ref>\n\nThis period in their history also saw the goalscoring of [[Charlie Buchan]], who went on to score 221 goals for Sunderland,<ref>Dykes, pp. 58\u201359.</ref> making himthe second highest goalscorer in the club's history, behind [[Bob Gurney]].<ref>Dykes, pp. 170\u2013171.</ref> Holley was the league's top scorer in the season before Sunderland won the title.\n\nTwo seasons later the First World War brought the league to a halt. After the league's resumption, Sunderland came close to winning another championship in the [[1922\u201323 in English football|1922\u201323 season]], when they were runners-up to Liverpool.<ref>Days, pp 107\u2013108.</ref> They also came close the following season, finishing third, four points from the top of the league.<ref>Days, pp 111\u2013112.</ref> The club escaped relegation from the First Division by one point in the [[1927\u201328 in English football|1927\u201328 season]] despite 35 goals from [[Dave Halliday]].[[File:Rokerlads1937.jpg|thumb|right|Sunderland's 1937 FA Cup winning side]] The point was won in a match against [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]], and they finished in fifteenth place.<ref>Days, pp 121\u2013122.</ref> Halliday improved his goal scoring to 43 goals in 42 games the following season,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engtops.html#1920-1|title=Football League Div 1 & 2 Leading Goalscorers 1920\u201339|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=5 December 2008}}</ref> an all-time Sunderland record for goals scored in a single season.<ref name=\"History\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.safc.premiumtv.co.uk.p.preprod.performgroup.com/page/ClubHistoryDetail/0,,10281,00.html |title=Club History |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |access-date=8 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180406232607/http://www.safc.premiumtv.co.uk.p.preprod.performgroup.com/page/ClubHistoryDetail/0,,10281,00.html |archive-date=6 April 2018 |url-status=dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe club's sixth league championship came in the [[1935\u201336 in English football|1935\u201336]] season under [[Scotland|Scottish]] manager [[Johnny Cochrane]].<ref>Days, pp 139\u2013140.</ref> They scored 109&nbsp;goals during the season, with [[Raich Carter]] and [[Bobby Gurney]] each scoring 31.<ref>Days, pp. 139\u2013142.</ref> The League championship led to Sunderland playing in the Charity Shield against FA Cup-winners Arsenal. Sunderland won the shield after goals from [[Eddie Burbanks]] and Raich Carter.<ref name=\"shield\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engsupcuphist.html|title=England&nbsp;\u2014 List of FA Charity/Community Shield Matches|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=30 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nDespite winning the league, the season did not go without tragedy. The young goalkeeper of the team, [[Jimmy Thorpe]], died as a result of a kick in the head and chest after he had picked up the ball following a [[backpass]] in a game against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] at [[Roker Park]]. He continued to take part until the match finished, but collapsed at home afterwards and died in hospital four days later from [[diabetes mellitus]] and heart failure 'accelerated by the rough usage of the opposing team'.<ref name=\"Goalkeeper's Death\">{{cite news|title=Goalkeeper's Death|url=http://archive.timesonline.co.uk/tol/viewArticle.arc?articleId=ARCHIVE-The_Times-1936-02-14-16-001&pageId=ARCHIVE-The_Times-1936-02-14-16 | location=London | work=The Times|date=14 February 1936}}</ref> This tragic incident led to a change in the rules, whereby players were no longer allowed to raise their foot to a goalkeeper when he had control of the ball in his arms.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?xml=/sport/2006/10/04/soinve04.xml |location=London |title=On the run with dogs and a long-dead goalkeeper - Telegraph |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311055415/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?xml=%2Fsport%2F2006%2F10%2F04%2Fsoinve04.xml |archive-date=11 March 2007 |df= }}</ref>\n\nThey won the FA Cup the following season, after a 3\u20131 victory against Preston North End at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.soccerbase.com/teams/team.sd?team_id=2493&season_id=66&teamTabs=results|title=Sunderland Results 1936/37|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe remainder of the decade saw mid-table finishes, until the league and FA Cup were suspended for the duration of the Second World War. Some football was still played as a morale boosting exercise, in the form of the [[Football League War Cup]]. Sunderland were finalists in the tournament in [[1942 Football League War Cup Final|1942]], but were beaten by [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]].<ref>Days, p 154.</ref>\n\nFor Sunderland, the immediate post-war years were characterised by significant spending; the club paid \u00a318,000 (\u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|18000|1949|r=-3}}|0}} today) for [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]]'s [[Ivor Broadis]] in January 1949.{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}} Broadis was also Carlisle's manager at the time, and this is the first instance of a player transferring himself to another club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/1904999.broadis_still_bubbling_along_at_85/|title=Broadis still; bubbling along at 85|last=Amos|first=Mike|date=14 December 2007|work=The Northern Echo|accessdate=19 September 2008}}</ref> This, along with record-breaking transfer fees to secure the services of [[Len Shackleton]] and the Welsh international [[Trevor Ford]], led to a contemporary nickname, the \"[[Bank of England club]]\".<ref>Days, pp 169\u2013170.</ref> The club finished third in the First Division in [[1949\u201350 in English football|1950]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/engpaul/FLA/1949-50.html|title=Season 1949\u201350|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=8 September 2010}}</ref> their highest finish since the 1936 championship.\n\nShackleton, known as the \"Clown Prince of Soccer\", later admitted that the players were more a collection of talented individuals than a true team, and that \"it takes time to harness and control a team of [[thoroughbred]]s. It took time to achieve the blend at Roker Park\".<ref>{{harvnb|Malam|2004|p=84}}</ref>{{full citation needed|date=September 2019}} Shackleton and centre-forward Ford would never build any kind of relationship on or off the pitch however, and Ford once threatened to never play in the same Sunderland team as Shackleton until he was forced to back down by manager [[Bill Murray (footballer, born 1901)|Bill Murray]].<ref name=\"Malam 2004 87\">{{harvnb|Malam|2004|p=87}}</ref>{{full citation needed|date=September 2019}} Ford was sold on to [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] in November 1953.<ref>{{harvnb|Malam|2004|p=88}}</ref>{{full citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n===Financial troubles and three cup finals (1950\u20131995)===\nThe late 1950s saw a sharp downturn in Sunderland's fortunes, and the club was once again implicated in a major financial scandal in 1957.<ref name=mackie/> Found guilty of making payments to players in excess of the [[Salary cap|maximum wage]], they were fined \u00a35,000 (\u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|5000|1957|r=-3}}}} today), and their chairman and three directors were suspended.{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}}<ref>Days, pp 183\u2013184.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.givemefootball.com/pfa/pfa-history/the-jimmy-hill-years-pfa-chairman-1957-1961 |title=The Jimmy Hill Years: PFA Chairman 1957\u20131961 |publisher=Professional Footballers' Association |accessdate=4 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100915053426/http://www.givemefootball.com/pfa/pfa-history/the-jimmy-hill-years-pfa-chairman-1957-1961 |archivedate=15 September 2010 }}</ref> The following year, Sunderland were [[promotion and relegation|relegated]] from the highest division for the first time in their 68-year league history.<ref>Days, p 187.</ref>\n[[File:Ianporterfieldgoal.jpg|thumb|right|Ian Porterfield's winning goal in the 1973 FA Cup Final]]\nSunderland's absence from the top flight lasted six years. The club came within one game of promotion back to the First Division in the [[1962\u201363 in English football|1962\u201363 season]]. Sunderland required only a draw in their final game against promotion rivals Chelsea, who had another game left to play after this match, to secure promotion. However, they were defeated,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.soccerbase.com/teams/team.sd?team_id=2493&season_id=92&teamTabs=results|title=Sunderland Results 1962/63|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref> and Chelsea won their last game 7\u20130 to clinch promotion, finishing ahead of Sunderland on [[goal average]].<ref>Days, pp 199\u2013200.</ref> After the close call in the previous season, the club was promoted to Division One in 1964 after finishing in second place. Sunderland beat [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] in the final stages of the season, where they clinched promotion with a game to spare.<ref>Days, pp 201\u2013202.</ref> At the end of the decade, they were again relegated to the Second Division after finishing 21st.<ref>Days, pp 217\u2013218.</ref>\n\n[[File:1973facuphomecoming.jpg|thumb|left|upright|The homecoming open top bus parade after victory in the 1973 FA Cup final]]\nSunderland won their last major trophy in 1973, in a 1\u20130 victory over [[Don Revie]]'s [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] in the FA Cup Final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/FACompetitions/TheFACup/History/HistoryOfTheFACup/1973SunderlandLeeds|title=1973 Sunderland v Leeds|publisher=TheFA|accessdate=8 September 2010}}</ref> A [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] club at the time, Sunderland won the game thanks mostly to the efforts of their goalkeeper [[Jimmy Montgomery]], who saved two of Leeds shots at goal in quick succession, one being from hot-shot [[Peter Lorimer]].<ref name=\"1973FACupfinal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2003/12/FACup_200304_3R_Montgomery.htm|archive-url=https://archive.is/20041211150904/http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2003/12/FACup_200304_3R_Montgomery.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=11 December 2004|title=Monty wanting more heroics|author=Richard Morgan|date=31 December 2003|publisher=The FA|accessdate=28 November 2008}}</ref> [[Ian Porterfield]] scored a [[volley (football)|volley]] in the 30th minute to beat Leeds and take the trophy.<ref name=\"1973FACupfinal\"/> Since 1973 only two other clubs, [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] in 1976,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/FACompetitions/TheFACup/History/HistoryOfTheFACup/1976SouthamptonManUnited|title=1976 Southampton v Man United|publisher=TheFA|accessdate=8 September 2010}}</ref> and [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in 1980,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/columnists/henrywinter/2296500/Ledley-volley-sends-Cardiff-City-to-FA-Cup-final.html|title=Ledley volley sends Cardiff City to FA Cup final|author=Henry Winter|date=7 April 2008|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=28 November 2008|location=London}}</ref> have equalled Sunderland's achievement of lifting the FA Cup while playing outside the top tier of English football.\n\nBy winning the [[1973 FA Cup Final]], Sunderland qualified for the [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]], the club's only appearance in European competition to date.<ref name=\"Euro\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec197374.html#cwc|title=European Competitions 1973\u201374|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=19 December 2008}}</ref> Sunderland beat [[Vasas SC|Vasas Budapest]] 3\u20130 on [[Two-legged tie|aggregate]], and were drawn against Lisbon club [[Sporting Clube de Portugal|Sporting]] in the [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup 1973\u201374#Second round|second round]].<ref name=\"Euro\"/> They won the first leg at [[Roker Park]] 2\u20131 but were defeated 2\u20130 in the away leg, and were knocked out of the competition 3\u20132 on aggregate.<ref name=\"Euro\"/> After spending six seasons in the Second Division, Sunderland were promoted to Division One in the [[1975\u201376 in English football|1975\u201376 season]]; they topped the table over [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] by three points.<ref>Days, pp 235\u2013236.</ref> However, Sunderland were relegated the following season back into Division Two, without their FA Cup Final winning manager Bob Stokoe, who had resigned because of health problems at the start of the season.<ref>Days, pp 239\u2013240.</ref> The club celebrated its 100-year centenary in the [[1979\u201380 in English football|1979\u201380 season]] with a [[testimonial match|testimonial]] against an England XI side, which they lost 2\u20130.<ref>Days, pp 247\u2013248.</ref>\n\nSunderland appeared in their first [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] [[1985 Football League Cup Final|final]] in 1985, but lost 1\u20130 to [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engleagcuphistfull.html#85|title=England League Cup Full Results 1960\u20131996|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=8 September 2010}}</ref> In 1987, Sunderland saw one of the lowest points in their history, when they were relegated to the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] of the English league for the first time.<ref>Days, pp 265\u2013266.</ref> Under new chairman [[Bob Murray (businessman)|Bob Murray]] and new manager [[Denis Smith (football manager)|Denis Smith]], the club was promoted the following season.<ref>Days, pp 269\u2013270.</ref> In 1990, they were promoted back to the top flight in unusual circumstances. Sunderland lost to [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] in the play-off final, but Swindon's promotion was revoked after the club was found guilty of financial irregularities and Sunderland were promoted instead.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/wiltshire/3976405.stm|title=Football fan's 1,000 game milestone|author=Chris Kelly|date=4 November 2004|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref> They stayed up for one year before being relegated on the final day of the following season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/engpaul/FLA/1990-91.html|title=Season 1990\u201391|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=8 September 2010}}</ref>\n[[File:Peter Reid Sunderland 1998small.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Peter Reid was appointed Sunderland manager in 1997, and served until 2002]]\nSunderland's next outing in a major final came in [[1992 FA Cup Final|1992]] when, as a Second Division club, they returned to the FA Cup final. There was to be no repeat of the heroics of 1973, as Sunderland lost 2\u20130 to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fa-cupfinals.co.uk/1992.htm |title=Liverpool 2 Sunderland 0 |publisher=FA Cup Finals |accessdate=8 September 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071023204315/http://www.fa-cupfinals.co.uk/1992.htm |archivedate=23 October 2007 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===New stadium, promotions and relegations (1995\u20132006)===\nIn 1995, they faced the prospect of a return to the third-tier of English football.<ref>Days, pp 291\u2013292.</ref> [[Peter Reid]] was brought in as manager, and quickly turned things around. Reid's time in charge had a stabilising effect; he remained manager for seven years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/managers2.sd?managerid=1031|title=Peter Reid's managerial career|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=20 September 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071124052357/http://www.soccerbase.com/managers2.sd?managerid=1031#|archive-date=24 November 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> After promotion from Division One in the [[1995\u201396 in English football|1995\u201396 season]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/engpaul/FLA/1995-96.html|title=England 1995/96|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=8 September 2010}}</ref> Sunderland began their first season in the [[Premier League]], but finished third from the bottom and were relegated back to the First Division,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/engpaul/FLA/1996-97.html|title=Season 1996\u201397|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=8 September 2010}}</ref> despite beating Manchester United,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=241571|title=Sunderland 2&nbsp;\u2013 1 Man Utd|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=6 January 2009}}</ref> Arsenal<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=241525|title=Sunderland 1&nbsp;\u2013 0 Arsenal|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=6 January 2009}}</ref> and Chelsea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=242206|title=Sunderland 3&nbsp;\u2013 0 Chelsea|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=6 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, Sunderland left [[Roker Park]], their home for 99 years. Bearing fond memories of the stadium, former Sunderland player [[Len Shackleton]] said, \"There will never be another place like Roker\".<ref>Days, p 298.</ref> The club moved to the [[Stadium of Light]], a 42,000-seat arena that, at the time, was the largest stadium built in England after the Second World War.<ref name=\"SOL\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.safc.com/club/stadium-of-light |title=Stadium of Light |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |access-date=8 September 2010}}</ref> The capacity was later increased to 49,000.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/clubs/profile.stadium.html/sunderland |title=Club Profile &#124; Sunderland |publisher=Premierleague.com |accessdate=17 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208114958/http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/clubs/profile.stadium.html/sunderland |archivedate= 8 February 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\nSunderland returned to the Premier League as First Division champions in 1999 with a then-record 105 points.<ref>Days, p 312.</ref> Sunderland's [[1999\u20132000 in English football|1999\u20132000]] season started at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]], where Chelsea beat them 4\u20130.<ref name=\"soccerbase\">{{cite web|url=https://www.soccerbase.com/teams/team.sd?team_id=2493&season_id=129&teamTabs=results|title=Sunderland Results 1999/00|publisher=[[Soccerbase]]|accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref> However, in the return match later in the season Sunderland turned the tables on Chelsea, avenging their 4\u20130 defeat with a 4\u20131 win at the Stadium of Light.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/fa_carling_premiership/550014.stm|title=Chelsea shot down in flames|date=5 December 1999|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=2 November 2008}}</ref>  Sunderland also achieved a 2\u20131 victory over rivals Newcastle United at St. James' Park,<ref name=\"soccerbase\"/> a result which helped bring about the resignation of Newcastle's manager, [[Ruud Gullit]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nufc.com/html/gullit-resigns.html|title=Gullit Resignation Statement|date=28 August 1999|publisher=Newcastle United F.C.|accessdate=2 November 2008}}</ref> At the end of the season Sunderland finished seventh, with [[Kevin Phillips (footballer)|Kevin Phillips]] winning the [[European Golden Shoe]] in his first top-flight season, scoring 30 goals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sunderland/856691.stm|title=Phillips nets Golden prize|date=29 July 2000|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=2 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nAnother seventh-place finish in the 2000\u201301 season was followed by two less successful seasons, and they were relegated to the second-tier with a then-record low 19 points in 2003.<ref name=\"History\" /><ref name=\"recent\">{{cite web|url=http://www.premierleague.com/page/sunderland|title=Club Profile|publisher=Premier League|accessdate=20 September 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509075844/http://www.premierleague.com/page/sunderland|archivedate=9 May 2008}}</ref> Former [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Ireland]] manager [[Mick McCarthy]] took over at the club, and, in 2005, he took Sunderland up as champions for the third time in less than 10 years.<ref name=\"History\" /> However, the club's stay in the top flight was short-lived as Sunderland were once again relegated, this time with a new record-low total of 15 points. McCarthy left the club in mid-season, and he was replaced temporarily by former Sunderland player [[Kevin Ball]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sunderland/4778496.stm|title=Sunderland sack manager McCarthy|date=6 March 2006|publisher=BCB Sport|accessdate=8 September 2010}}</ref> The record-low 15-point performance was surpassed in the [[Premier League 2007\u201308|2007\u201308 season]] by [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]], who finished on 11 points.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sunderland/4856682.stm#Derby|title=Where do woeful Derby rank?|last=Stevenson|first=Jonathon|date=29 March 2008|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=20 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Drumaville Consortium takeover and Ellis Short era (2006\u20132016)===\n[[File:Quinn, Niall.jpg|thumb|Former player Niall Quinn led the takeover of the club in 2006, and spent six more years at the club in the roles of manager, chairman and Director of International Development]]\nFollowing Sunderland's relegation from the Premier League, the club was taken over by the Irish [[Drumaville Consortium]],<ref name=\"History\" /> headed by ex-player [[Niall Quinn]], who appointed former [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] captain [[Roy Keane]] as the new manager.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sunderland/5290778.stm|title=Keane becomes new Sunderland boss|date=28 August 2006|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 September 2008}}</ref> Under Keane, the club rose steadily up the table with an unbeaten run of 17 games<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/apr/23/match.sunderland|title=Keane's march to the top falters on tiny Colchester's own ambitions|last=Alexander|first=Jeremy|date=23 April 2007|work=The Guardian|accessdate=21 September 2008 | location=London}}</ref> to win promotion to the Premier League,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/6578817.stm|title=Crystal Palace 2\u20130 Derby|last=Mercer|first=Nathan|date=29 April 2007|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 September 2008}}</ref> and were named winners of the [[Football League Championship|Championship]] after beating [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] 5\u20130 at [[Kenilworth Road]] on 6 May 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/may/07/match.sunderland|title=Sunderland's title has Keane almost smiling|last=Walker|first=Michael|date=7 May 2007|work=The Guardian|accessdate=21 September 2008 | location=London}}</ref> Following an inconsistent start to the [[2008\u201309 in English football|2008\u201309 season]], Keane resigned.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sunderland/8066360.stm|title=Sbragia resigns from Sunderland|date=25 May 2009|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=26 September 2009}}</ref> Before the start of the following campaign, Irish-American businessman [[Ellis Short]] completed a full takeover of the club,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/sunderland/5392742/Steve-Bruce-set-for-Sunderland-talks-while-Ellis-Short-completes-takeover.html|title=Steve Bruce set for Sunderland talks while Ellis Short completes takeover|author=Rob Stewart|date=27 May 2009|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=27 May 2011|location=London}}</ref> and [[Steve Bruce]] was announced as the next manager on 3 June.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sunderland/8080762.stm|title=Bruce named as Sunderland manager|date=3 June 2009|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=26 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nOne of Bruce's first signings, [[Darren Bent]], cost a club record fee of \u00a310 million, broken a year later when they bought Ghana international [[Asamoah Gyan]] for around \u00a313&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"gyan\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/8958346.stm|title=Asamoah Gyan joins Sunderland for record \u00a313m fee|date=31 August 2010|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=8 September 2010}}</ref> Sunderland started the 2010\u201311 season strongly, but after Bent left for [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in January 2011 in a deal potentially worth \u00a324 million, a record transfer fee received for the club,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/jan/17/darren-bent-sunderland-aston-villa|title=Darren Bent heads for Aston Villa in record \u00a324m deal|author=Louise Taylor|date=17 January 2011|work=The Guardian|accessdate=30 November 2011|location=London}}</ref> they eventually finished 10th&nbsp;\u2014 which was still their highest top-flight finish for 10 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/sport/sunderland-afc/chris-young-column/west_ham_0_sunderland_3_win_means_sunderland_finish_above_newcastle_1_3407202?commentssort=1&commentspage=10|title=West Ham 0 Sunderland 3: Win means Sunderland finish above Newcastle|date=22 May 2011|publisher=Sunderland Echo|accessdate=30 November 2011}}</ref> After being named Sunderland's Young Player of the Year for two seasons in a row,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/sunderland-afcs-academy-graduates-now-15359267|title=Sunderland AFC's academy graduates - where are they now?|first=Sean|last=McCormick|date=2 November 2018|website=nechronicle}}</ref> at the end of the [[2010\u201311 Premier League|2010-11]] season, [[Jordan Henderson]] was transferred to [[Liverpool FC]], where he went on to become captain and win the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://talksport.com/football/550057/liverpool-damien-comolli-jordan-henderson-super-cup-champions-league/|title=Former Liverpool chief explain Jordan Henderson transfer cost him his job|date=15 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/jurgen-klopp-turned-down-jordan-16635323|title=Inside story of what happened on night of Liverpool's CL final win|first=Ian|last=Doyle|date=24 July 2019|website=liverpoolecho}}</ref>\n\nShort replaced Quinn as chairman in October 2011, with Quinn becoming Director of International Development.<ref>{{cite news|author=|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15159659.stm |title=Niall Quinn steps down as Sunderland chairman |publisher=BBC Sport |date=3 October 2011 |accessdate=17 February 2012}}</ref> Bruce was sacked in November 2011,<ref>{{cite news|author=|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15975008.stm |title=Sunderland sack Steve Bruce as manager |publisher=BBC Sport |date=30 November 2011 |accessdate=17 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Press Association |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/nov/30/steve-bruce-leaves-sunderland |title=Steve Bruce sacked by Sunderland |work=The Guardian |date= 30 November 2011|accessdate=17 February 2012 |location=London}}</ref> and replaced by [[Martin O'Neill]].<ref>{{cite news|author=|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15997197.stm |title=Martin O'Neill named Sunderland manager |publisher=BBC Sport |date=3 December 2011 |accessdate=17 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Press Association |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/dec/03/martin-oneill-sunderland |title=Martin O'Neill named as Sunderland manager after signing three-year deal |work=The Guardian |date=3 December 2011 |accessdate=17 February 2012 |location=London}}</ref> In February 2012, Quinn left the club with immediate effect.<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/sunderland/9092819/Niall-Quinn-leaves-Sunderland-with-immediate-effect-to-concentrate-on-business-interests-outside-football.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Niall Quinn leaves Sunderland with immediate effect to concentrate on business interests outside football | date=20 February 2012}}</ref> O'Neill was sacked in March 2013<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11695/8608743/Martin-O-Neill-sacked-as-Sunderland-manager-after-Manchester-United-defeat|title=Martin O'Neill sacked as Sunderland manager after Manchester United defeat|work=SkySports|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref> and Italian [[Paolo Di Canio]] was announced as his  replacement the following day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21990117 |title=Paolo Di Canio appointed Sunderland head coach |publisher=BBC Sport |date=31 March 2013 |accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref> The appointment prompted the immediate resignation of club Vice Chairman [[David Miliband]] due to Di Canio's \"past political statements\".<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-21991812 | work=BBC News | title=Di Canio: David Miliband quits Sunderland role | date=1 April 2013}}</ref> It also met opposition from the [[Durham Miners' Association]],<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tyne-22049080 | work=BBC News | title=Miners' Di Canio protest 'will only end with Sunderland campaign support' | date=6 April 2013}}</ref> which threatened to remove one of its mining banners from Sunderland's [[Stadium of Light]], which is built on the former site of the [[Wearmouth Colliery]], as a symbol of its anger over the appointment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tyneandwear.sky.com/news/article/62109/durham-miners-association-our-issues-with-di-canio-now-resolved |title=Durham Miners' Association: Our Issues With Di Canio At Sunderland Now Resolved |accessdate=2013-04-24 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130625103549/http://tyneandwear.sky.com/news/article/62109/durham-miners-association-our-issues-with-di-canio-now-resolved |archivedate=25 June 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/apr/02/paolo-di-canio-sunderland-miners-banner | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Matthew | last=Taylor | title=Sunderland miners demand return of banner after Paolo Di Canio's arrival | date=2 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nSunderland went on to avoid relegation with one game to go. Di Canio was sacked after a poor start to the 2013\u201314 season, and reports of a complete breakdown in relations with his players.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/paolo-di-canio-was-fired-by-sunderland-for-systematic-destruction-of-his-players-8835606.html|title=Paolo Di Canio was fired by Sunderland for 'systematic destruction' of|date=24 September 2013|work=The Independent}}</ref> [[Gus Poyet]] was announced as his replacement,<ref>{{cite web|author=Dennis, Ian |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24441758 |title=Gus Poyet: Sunderland name Uruguayan as head coach |publisher=BBC Sport |date=8 October 2013 |accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref> and led Sunderland to the [[2014 Football League Cup Final]], where they were defeated 3\u20131 by [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]].<ref>{{cite news|last=McNulty |first=Phil |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26311649 |title=Manchester City 3\u20131 Sunderland |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2 March 2014 |accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref> In March 2015 Poyet was sacked,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31902933|title=Gus Poyet: Sunderland sack manager after crisis talks|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref> and veteran Dutchman [[Dick Advocaat]] was appointed as the club's new head coach,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31919801|title=Sunderland: Dick Advocaat appointed Black Cats boss|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref> saving the club from relegation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32716700|title=Arsenal 0\u20130 Sunderland|author=Phil McNulty|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref> Eight games into the 2015\u201316 season he resigned from the position.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34437620|title=Dick Advocaat: Sunderland boss quits Premier League strugglers|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref> [[Sam Allardyce]] was appointed the next manager in October 2015, and the club was again saved from relegation at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35733486 | title=Sunderland 3\u20130 Everton | publisher=BBC Sport | date=11 May 2016 | accessdate=12 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Back-to-back relegations and sale (2016\u2013present)===\nIn July 2016, Allardyce left the club to be announced as manager for the [[England national football team|English national team]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/12016/10508367/sam-allardyce-appointed-new-england-manager-football-association-confirms|title=Sam Allardyce appointed new England manager on two-year deal|publisher=}}</ref> and former Everton and Manchester United manager [[David Moyes]] was appointed as his replacement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36874200 |title=Sunderland: David Moyes replaces Sam Allardyce as manager |date=23 July 2016 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref> Under Moyes, Sunderland made the worst ever start to a Premier League season, taking just two points from their opening 10 matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/10636619/sunderland-make-worst-ever-start-to-a-premier-league-season|title=Sunderland make worst ever start to a Premier League season|publisher=}}</ref> The club was relegated to the second tier for the first time in 10 years at the end of the 2016\u201317 season, finishing bottom of the table with 24 points,<ref>{{cite news|title=Sunderland 0\u20131 AFC Bournemouth|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39676422|accessdate=29 April 2017|publisher=BBC Sport|date=29 April 2017}}</ref> and Moyes resigned as manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40003697|title=David Moyes resigns as Sunderland boss after relegation from Premier League|date=22 May 2017|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> In June 2017, goalkeeper [[Jordan Pickford]], a product of  Sunderland's academy who joined the club aged eight, was transferred to Everton for a fee of \u00a325 million, rising to a possible \u00a330 million, a record for a British goalkeeper.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40258852|title=Jordan Pickford: Everton confirm \u00a325m, rising to \u00a330m, deal with Sunderland|date=15 June 2017|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nFollowing relegation, [[Simon Grayson]] was announced as the new manager of the club.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/jun/29/sunderland-shelve-takeover-talks-close-preston-simon-grayson |title= Sunderland appoint Simon Grayson as manager after shelving takeover talks |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=29 June 2017 |accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref> Under Grayson, the club made a very poor start to the [[2017\u201318 EFL Championship]] season (which was documented in the [[Netflix]] series ''[[Sunderland 'Til I Die]]''), taking only 2 wins in 14 games. Following a 3\u20133 draw against Bolton, Grayson was sacked,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/oct/31/simon-grayson-sacked-sunderland-manager|title=Simon Grayson sacked as Sunderland manager after draw with Bolton|last=Association|first=Press|date=31 October 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=19 November 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and [[Wales national football team|Wales]] head coach [[Chris Coleman (footballer)|Chris Coleman]] replaced him in November 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.safc.com/news/team-news/2017/november/coleman-named-new-manager|title=Coleman named new manager|date=19 November 2017|publisher=Sunderland A.F.C.|access-date=19 November 2017}}</ref> In April 2018, after a second consecutive relegation, this time to [[EFL League One|League One]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43762308|title=Sunderland 1\u20132 Burton Albion|publisher=BBC Sport|date=21 April 2018}}</ref> the club was sold to a group led by [[Stewart Donald]], the chairman of [[Eastleigh F.C.|Eastleigh]], and Coleman was released from his contract.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/apr/29/chris-coleman-sackedd-manager-sunderland |title=Sunderland sold by Ellis Short as Chris Coleman is sacked |date=29 April 2018 |work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n[[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] manager [[Jack Ross (footballer, born 1976)|Jack Ross]] was appointed as the new manager in May 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44238168|title=Jack Ross: Sunderland name St Mirren boss as new manager|date=25 May 2018 |work=BBC sport}}</ref> In the club's first season in League One they finished 5th and reached the play-off final, but lost to [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] at Wembley. After a disappointing start to the 2019\u201320 season, Ross was sacked in October 2019.<ref>https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11695/11830823/sunderland-sack-jack-ross-as-manager</ref> He was replaced by former Bolton manager [[Phil Parkinson]] on 17 October.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50081814</ref>\n\n==Colours and crest==\n[[File:Sunderland_AFC_cat_badge.jpg|thumb|left|Sunderland's club badge until 1972]]\n[[File:SAFC1972-97crest.svg|thumb|right|upright|Sunderland's club badge, used from 1972\u201397]]\nSunderland played in an all blue [[Kit (association football)|strip]] from their formation until 1884,<ref name=\"History\" /> when they adopted a red and white halved strip.<ref name=\"rokerpark2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.roker-roar.com/pauldays/navbar/redandwhite.html |title=Red and white stripes |publisher=Roker Park |accessdate=19 September 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080603122644/http://www.roker-roar.com/pauldays/navbar/redandwhite.html |archivedate=3 June 2008 }}</ref> They assumed the current strip of red and white stripes in the [[1887\u201388 in English football|1887\u201388 season]].<ref>Days, p 15.</ref> Their badge included a ship, the upper part of the [[Coat of arms of Sunderland|Sunderland coat of arms]], a black cat, and a football in front of Sunderland's red and white stripes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uefaclubs.com/showlogos.php?club=Sunderland%20AFC&logo=5|title=European Football Club Logos|publisher=UEFA Clubs|accessdate=20 December 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002105118/http://uefaclubs.com/showlogos.php?club=Sunderland%20AFC&logo=5|archivedate=2 October 2011}}</ref> In 1972 the badge was changed,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sunderlandecho.com/sport/football/sunderland-afc/sunderland-afc-news/views-divided-on-sunderland-afc-s-new-badge-1-5634662|title=Views divided on Sunderland AFC's new badge|website=www.sunderlandecho.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-17}}</ref> removing the black cat but still including a ship, a football and the background of red and white stripes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uefaclubs.com/showlogos.php?club=Sunderland%20AFC&logo=2|title=European Football Club Logos|publisher=UEFA Clubs|accessdate=20 December 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002105127/http://uefaclubs.com/showlogos.php?club=Sunderland%20AFC&logo=2|archivedate=2 October 2011}}</ref> This badge was first used on the match day shirt in 1977, replacing the simple black 'SAFC' initials which had been used since 1973.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Sunderland/Sunderland.htm|title=Sunderland - Historical Football Kits|website=www.historicalkits.co.uk|access-date=2019-05-17}}</ref> The top section and border of the badge was coloured in blue until 1991, when it changed to black.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nTo coincide with the move from Roker Park to the Stadium of Light in 1997, Sunderland released a new crest divided into four quarters; the upper right and lower left featured their traditional red and white colours, but the ship was omitted. The upper left section features the [[Penshaw Monument]] and the lower right section shows the [[Wearmouth Bridge]].<ref name=\"Presentcrest\">{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/page/ClubCrest|title=SAFC Crest|publisher=Sunderland A.F.C.|accessdate=8 September 2010}}</ref> A colliery wheel at the top of the crest commemorates County Durham's mining history, and the land the Stadium of Light was built on, formerly the [[Monkwearmouth Colliery]]. The crest also contains two lions, the black cats of Sunderland, and a banner displaying the club's motto, ''Consectatio Excellentiae'', which means \"In pursuit of excellence\".<ref name=\"Presentcrest\"/>\n\n==Stadium==\n{{See also|List of Sunderland A.F.C. Grounds}}\n[[File:Roker Park August 1976.jpg|left|thumb|Sunderland's stadium for 99 years, Roker Park]]\n[[File:Safcattendances.JPG|thumb|250px|right|Average match attendances since 1891]]\nSunderland have had eight grounds throughout their history; the first was at [[Blue House Field]] in [[Hendon, Sunderland|Hendon]] in 1879. The ground was close to the place where Sunderland formed, at Hendon Board School; at that time the rent for use of the ground was \u00a310 (\u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|10|1879|r=-2}}|0}} today).{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.safc.com/history/stadiums/blue-house-field |title=Blue House Field, Hendon |date=22 June 2009 |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |access-date=8 September 2010}}</ref> The club then used a number of fields, one of which was near The Cedars road,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.safc.com/history/stadiums/the-cedars|title=The Cedars|work=Sunderland Association Football Club|access-date=6 April 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> before relocating to [[Groves Field]] in [[Ashbrooke]] in 1882 for one season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.safc.com/history/stadiums/groves-field |title=The Grove, Ashbrooke |date=22 June 2009 |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |access-date=8 September 2010}}</ref> The club's third stadium was [[Horatio Street]] in [[Roker]], the first Sunderland stadium north of the [[River Wear]]; the club played a single season there before another move,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.safc.com/history/stadiums/horatio-street |title=Horatio Street, Roker |date=22 June 2009 |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |access-date=8 September 2010}}</ref> this time to [[Abbs Field]] in [[Fulwell, Tyne and Wear|Fulwell]] for two seasons. Abbs Field was notable for being the first Sunderland ground to which they charged admission.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.safc.com/history/stadiums/abbs-field |title=Abbs Field, Fulwell |date=22 June 2009 |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |access-date=8 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nSunderland moved to [[Newcastle Road (stadium)|Newcastle Road]] in 1886. By 1898, the ground reached a capacity of 15,000 after renovations, and its rent had risen to \u00a3100 (\u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|100|1898|r=-2}}|0}} today) a year.{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.safc.com/history/stadiums/newcastle-road |title=Newcastle Road |date=22 June 2009 |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |access-date=8 September 2010}}</ref> Near the turn of the 20th century, Sunderland needed a bigger stadium. They returned to Roker and set up home in [[Roker Park]]. It was opened on 10 September 1898, and the home team played a match the same day against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]],<ref name=\"rokerparksafc\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.safc.com/history/stadiums/roker-park |title=Roker Park |date=22 June 2009 |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |access-date=8 September 2010}}</ref> which they won. The stadium's capacity increased to 50,000 after redevelopment with architect [[Archibald Leitch]] in 1913. Sunderland were nearly bankrupted by the cost of renovating the Main Stand, and Roker Park was put up for sale but no further action was taken. On&nbsp;8 March 1933, an overcrowded Roker Park recorded the highest ever attendance at a Sunderland match, 75,118 against [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] in a [[FA Cup]] sixth round replay.<ref name=\"History\" /> Roker Park suffered a bombing in 1943, in which one corner of the stadium was destroyed. A [[special constable]] was killed while patrolling the stadium. By the 1990s, the stadium was no longer large enough, and had no room for possible expansion.<ref>Days, pp 153\u2013154.</ref> In January 1990, the [[Taylor Report]] was released after overcrowding at the [[Hillsborough Stadium]] resulted in 96 deaths, an incident known as the [[Hillsborough Disaster]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/merseyside/3627261.stm|title=Service marks Hillsborough deaths|date=15 April 2004|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 January 2009}}</ref> The report recommended that all major stadiums must be converted to an all-seater design.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southyorks.police.uk/sites/default/files/foi/significantpublicinterest/hillsborough%20stadium%20disaster%20final%20report.zip|title=Lord Taylor's final report on the Hillsborough stadium disaster (zipped pdf)|author=Lord Justice Taylor|date=January 1990|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=5 January 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330053408/http://southyorks.police.uk/sites/default/files/hillsborough%20stadium%20disaster%20final%20report.pdf|archivedate=30 March 2014}}</ref> As a result, Roker Park's capacity was reduced. It was demolished in 1997 and a housing estate built in its place.<ref name=\"rokerparksafc\" /> [[File:Stadium of Light, Sunderland afc.jpg|thumb|left|250px|The [[Stadium of Light]] has been Sunderland's home ground since 1997.]]\nIn 1997, Sunderland moved to their present ground, [[Stadium of Light]] in [[Monkwearmouth]], which was opened by [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York]]. Built with an original capacity of 42,000, it hosted its first game against Dutch team [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]].<ref name=\"SOL\" /> The stadium bears a similar name to the Portuguese club [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]]'s ground [[Est\u00e1dio da Luz]], albeit in a different language.\n\nStadium expansion in 2000 saw the capacity increase to 49,000. A [[Davy lamp]] monument stands outside the stadium, and a miners banner was presented to the club by the [[Durham Miners' Association]],<ref>{{cite news|first1=Matthew|last1=Taylor|accessdate=2019-08-28|title=Sunderland miners demand return of banner after Paolo Di Canio's arrival|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/apr/02/paolo-di-canio-sunderland-miners-banner|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=2 April 2013|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> as a reminder of the [[Monkwearmouth Colliery]] pit the stadium was built on.\n\n==Supporters and rivalries==\n{{See also|Sunderland A.F.C. league record by opponent}}\nSunderland held the seventh highest average home attendance out of the 20 clubs in the Premier League at the end of the [[2013\u201314 Premier League|2013\u201314]] season with an average of 41,089,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/stats/attendance/_/league/eng.1/year/2011/barclays-premier-league?cc=5739 |title=Barclays Premier League Team Attendance Statistics \u2013 2011\u201312 \u2013 ESPN Soccernet |publisher=Soccernet.espn.go.com |date=13 May 2012 |accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref> and held the sixth highest average attendance in the [[2014\u201315 Premier League|2014\u201315]] season with an average of over 43,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caughtoffside.com/2014/09/12/ten-highest-premier-league-attendances-for-201415-with-arsenal-2nd-liverpool-5th/5/|title=Ten Highest Premier League Attendances For 2014/15, With Arsenal 2nd & Liverpool 5th|work=CaughtOffside|accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref> Sunderland fans often sell out allocations for away games: in the 2013\u201314 season, 9,000<ref name=\"BBC News Online 22 January 2014\">{{cite news |last= McNulty |first= Phil |title= League Cup: Results| url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25740123| date= 22 January 2014| website= [[BBC News Online]] | accessdate= 16 October 2015 }}</ref> Sunderland fans attended [[Old Trafford]] for the second leg of the Football League Cup semi-final, which they won to go through to the final. At Wembley, London was taken over by thousands of [[Mackem]]s, the sights of Covent Garden and Leicester Square were awash with red and white, local shops completely sold out of alcohol but only one arrest was reported by the police.<ref name=\"101 Great Goals 2 March 2014\">{{cite news |last= Newman |first= Benjamin |title= 1000s of Sunderland fans mobbed Covent Garden on Saturday before the Capital One Cup final v Man City| url= http://www.101greatgoals.com/blog/1000s-of-sunderland-fans-mobbed-covent-garden-on-saturday-night-before-the-capital-one-cup-final-v-man-city/| date= 2 March 2014| work= 101 Great Goals | accessdate= 16 October 2015 }}</ref> Support is drawn from across the [[North East England|North East]], in particular [[County Durham]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/newcastle-united/11306241/Newcastle-vs-Sunderland-Why-is-the-Tyne-Wear-derby-such-a-big-deal.html|title=Newcastle vs Sunderland: Why is the Tyne-Wear derby such a big deal?|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=7 October 2015}}</ref> and beyond. The club has many supporter branches across the world, including the United States, Australia, Canada, Cambodia, and Greece.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/news/20050302/supporter-branches_2256213_1710147|title=Supporter Branches|publisher=Sunderland A.F.C.|accessdate=8 September 2010}}</ref> According to [[YouGov]] statistics, supporters of Sunderland predominantly lean to the political [[left-wing|left]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2014/nov/18/you-gov-premier-league-profiles-20-clubs|title=Are you an average fan? Find out with YouGov's Premier League profiles|work=The Guardian|accessdate=7 October 2015}}</ref> and often sing \"[[The Red Flag]]\" during games.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/everton-vs-sunderland-match-report-danny-graham-and-jermain-defoe-fire-black-cats-closer-to-premier-10238451.html|title=Everton vs Sunderland match report: Danny Graham and Jermain Defoe fire Black Cats closer to Premier League safety|author=Tim Rich|date=9 May 2015|work=The Independent|accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nTraditionally, Sunderland's main rivals are Newcastle United, with whom they contest the [[Tyne\u2013Wear derby]]. The club shared a rivalry with the now defunct [[Sunderland Albion]] in the 1880s and 1890s, a breakaway club formed by Sunderland's founder James Allan.<ref name=\"page19\">Days, p 19.</ref> In recent seasons the club has also developed a minor rivalry with [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]], mainly stemming from the clubs meeting each other 5 times in the 18/19 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/sunderland-portsmouth-story-so-far-16284128|title=Sunderland vs Portsmouth: A story of red cards, penalties and a simmering rivalry|first=Sean|last=Tighe|date=16 May 2019|website=nechronicle}}</ref> Conversely, sections of fans share a mutual friendship with Dutch club [[Feyenoord]]; this was developed after Wearside shipbuilders found jobs in Rotterdam during the 1970s and 80s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1724981-7-friendships-between-football-clubs/page/3|title=7 Friendships Between Football Clubs|publisher=Bleacher Report|accessdate=7 October 2015}}</ref> The club also has good relations with [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]], matches between the two clubs being known as the ''[[Friendship Trophy]],'' following good rapport in the [[1985 Football League Cup Final|1985 Milk Cup final]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/what-heck-friendship-trophy-footballs-oddest-closed-cup-competitions|title=What the heck is the Friendship Trophy? Football's oddest closed cup competitions|last=House|first=Future Publishing Limited Quay|last2=Ambury|first2=The|date=2016-04-15|website=FourFourTwo|language=en|access-date=2019-07-16|last3=Engl|first3=Bath BA1 1UA All rights reserved|last4=number 2008885|first4=Wales company registration}}</ref>\n\nThe club had an official quarterly magazine, called the ''Legion of Light'', which season ticket holders received at no cost.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/shop/?page_id=15449|title=Magazine&nbsp;\u2014 Legion of Light|publisher=Sunderland A.F.C.|accessdate=21 September 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080823120217/http://www.safc.com/shop/?page_id=15449|archivedate=23 August 2008}}</ref> It was discontinued in January 2017. One of the club's current [[fanzine]]s is ''[[A Love Supreme (Sunderland)|A Love Supreme]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.a-love-supreme.com/|title=A Love Supreme&nbsp;\u2014 The Independent Sunderland Football Club Fanzine|publisher=ALS Publications|accessdate=19 September 2008}}</ref> Others in the past have been ''It's The Hope I Can't Stand'',  ''It's An Easy One For Norman/It's An Easy One For Given'', ''Sex and Chocolate'', ''Wise Men Say'' and ''The Roker Roar'' (later ''The Wearside Roar'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.a-love-supreme.com/S%20and%20C%20archive/S&Carchive001.htm|title=History of Fanzines|publisher=ALS Publications|accessdate=19 September 2008}}</ref> In recent years, blogging sites such as ''[[Roker Report]]'' have been popular.\n\nThere are over 70 branches of official Supporters' Clubs in [[England]] and around the world, including [[North America]], which started in 2013;<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/charlie-methven-how-sunderland-plan-15683807 | title=How Sunderland plan to chase the American dream| date=16 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2018/11/18/18094711/meet-the-branches-chatting-with-the-sunderland-north-american-supporters-association-nasa |title = Meet the Branches: Chatting with the Sunderland North American Supporters Association (NASA)!|date = 18 November 2018}}</ref> [[Scotland]];<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2019/2/21/18226257/meet-the-branches-och-aye-its-the-newly-formed-scottish-sunderland-supporters-branch |title = Meet the Branches: \"Och Aye!\" - It's the newly formed Scottish Sunderland Supporters Branch!|date = 21 February 2019}}</ref> [[South Africa]];<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2019/5/21/18263424/meet-the-branches-say-sawubona-to-the-south-african-sunderland-supporters-branch | title=Meet the Branches: Say 'Sawubona' to the South African Sunderland supporters branch!| date=21 May 2019}}</ref> [[Germany]];<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2019/3/21/18270693/meet-the-branches-how-fifa12-netflix-convinced-this-fan-to-start-a-german-sunderland-branch |title = Meet the Branches: How FIFA12 & Netflix convinced this fan to start a German Sunderland branch!|date = 21 March 2019}}</ref> a united [[Denmark|Danish]] and [[Ireland|Irish]] Supporters Branch;<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2019/2/26/18237253/meet-the-branches-finding-out-about-the-intriguing-danish-irish-sunderland-supporters-branch | title=Meet the Branches: Finding out about the intriguing Danish & Irish Sunderland supporters branch!| date=26 February 2019}}</ref> a separate [[Dublin]] supporters club;<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2019/2/28/18244360/meet-the-branches-sunderlands-dublin-supporters-branch-flying-the-flag-on-the-emerald-isle |title = Meet the Branches: Sunderland's Dublin Supporters Branch - Flying the flag on the Emerald Isle!|date = 28 February 2019}}</ref> [[Sydney]], [[Australia]];<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2018/9/2/17803722/meet-the-branches-introducing-the-brand-new-sydney-sunderland-supporters-group | title=MEET THE BRANCHES: Introducing the BRAND NEW Sydney Sunderland supporters group!| date=2 September 2018}}</ref> [[United Arab Emirates]];<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2018/11/20/18087306/meet-the-branches-uae-sunderland-supporters-branch-following-the-lads-from-4500-miles-away |title = Meet the Branches: UAE Sunderland Supporters Branch - following the lads from 4500 miles away!|date = 20 November 2018}}</ref> [[Switzerland]];<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2016/3/10/11118984/mackems-abroad-meet-the-swiss-branch |title = Mackems Abroad: Meet the Swiss Branch|date = 10 March 2016}}</ref> and even [[North Korea]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11695/11654819/sunderland-open-new-supporters-club-branch-in-north-korea |title = Sunderland open new Supporters Club branch in North Korea}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/47442923 |title = Sunderland's North Korea fan club: Supporter aims to build fan base|work = BBC Sport|date = 4 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Charitable associations===\n{{See also|Foundation of Light}}\nA charity, the [[Foundation of Light]], is affiliated with the club and helps encourage educational development through football, and offers learning centres in addition to scholarships.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sunderlandecho.com/sport/football/sunderland-afc/sunderland-s-foundation-of-light-launches-north-durham-football-scholarship-1-9071904|title=Sunderland's Foundation of Light launches North Durham Football Scholarship|newspaper=Sunderland Echo|date=19 March 2018|accessdate=20 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Affiliated clubs===\nSunderland have recently created affiliations with several African clubs including Ghana's [[Asante Kotoko SC|Asante Kotoko]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2896/premier-league/2011/07/18/2580268/sunderland-seal-partnership-with-ghana-giants-asante-kotoko |title=Sunderland seal partnership with Ghana giants Asante Kotoko |publisher=Goal.com |date=18 July 2011 |accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref> Egypt's [[El-Ittihad El-Iskandary]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/5745851/bruce-away-form-must-improve|title=Bruce \u2013 Away form must improve|work=SkySports|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref> and South Africa's [[Bidvest Wits F.C.|Bidvest Wits]]. Sunderland also have an affiliation with Belgian side [[Lierse S.K.]], allowing the possibility for young African players who would not qualify for a UK work permit to spend three years with Lierse to gain a Belgian passport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espnfc.com/news/story/_/id/1184672/sunderland-announce-link-with-belgian-side-lierse-sk?cc=5739 |title=Sunderland announce link with Belgian side Lierse SK |publisher=Espn Fc |date=8 October 2012 |accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref> In August 2014, Sunderland announced a commercial partnership with [[Washington, D.C.|Washington D.C.]] based [[MLS]] club [[D.C. United]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/aug/08/dc-united-sunderland-mls-premier-league-partnership |title=DC United and Sunderland announce MLS-Premier League partnership |work=The Guardian |location=London |accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nSunderland were the subject, together with [[Aston Villa FC|Aston Villa]], of one of the earliest football paintings in the world - possibly the earliest - when in 1895 the artist Thomas M. M. Hemy painted a picture of a game between the teams at Sunderland's then ground [[Newcastle Road]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2017/11/21/16681978/the-famous-sunderland-v-aston-villa-painting-that-hangs-in-the-lobby-of-the-sol-a-history-of |title = The famous Sunderland v Aston Villa painting that hangs in the lobby of the SoL - a history of|date = 21 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Thomas Hemy Sunderland v Aston Villa 1895 A Corner Kick.jpg|thumbnail|right|One of the earliest football paintings in the world, Thomas MM Hemy's \"Sunderland v. [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] 1895\" depicts a match between the two most successful English teams of the decade.]]\n\nIn 1973, [[Bobby Knoxall]] recorded \"Sunderland All The Way\" for the [[1973 FA Cup Final]] record.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2009/07/21/9324/end_of_a_north-east_legend|title=End of a North-East legend : News 2009 : Chortle : The UK Comedy Guide|first=Steve|last=Bennett|website=www.chortle.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nSunderland AFC were mentioned in the show [[Auf Wiedersehen, Pet]], in the episode \"[[List of Auf Wiedersehen, Pet episodes|The Girls They Left Behind]]\". In the episode, characters Dennis & Oz go to support Sunderland in [[Li\u00e9ge]] despite being [[Newcastle United|Newcastle]] fans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0516479/|title=The Girls They Left Behind|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998 and following the demolition of Roker Park, playwright Tom Kelly and actor Paul Dunn created a one-man play called \"I Left My Heart at Roker Park\" about a fan struggling with the move and what Roker Park meant for him - the play originally ran in 1997, and had a few revivals since.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2014/8/11/5990401/i-left-my-heart-at-roker-park-roker-report-meets-paul-dunn|title=I Left My Heart In Roker Park|date=11 August 2014|website=Roker Report}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thepauldunn.co.uk/projects/past-projects/2014-2/i-left-my-heart-in-roker-park-by-tom-kelly/|title=I Left My Heart In Roker Park by Tom Kelly|date=13 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishtheatreguide.info/reviews/rokerpark-rev|title=Theatre review: I Left My Heart in Roker Park... (And Extra Time at the Stadium of Light) at Customs House, South Shields|website=British Theatre Guide}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/share-your-stadium-of-light-tales-357411|title=Share your Stadium of Light tales|website=www.sunderlandecho.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, BBC broadcast a six-part documentary named [[Premier Passions]]. It chronicled Sunderland A.F.C. during the [[1996\u201397 in English football|1996\u201397 season]], in which the club was [[Promotion and relegation|relegated]] from the [[Premier League]], the year after winning [[promotion and relegation|promotion]] from the [[Football League First Division]], and the move to [[Stadium of Light]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0364860/plotsummary|title=Premier Passions (TV Series 1998\u2013 ) - IMDb|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/sunderlands-premier-passions-remembered-20-13166765|title=Sunderland's Premier Passions remembered 20 years after fly-on-the-wall TV came to Roker Park|first=James|last=Hunter|date=11 June 2017|website=nechronicle}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Netflix released an eight-part documentary called [[Sunderland 'Til I Die]]. It documented the events around Sunderland A.F.C. during their [[2017-18 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2017\u201318 season]] which saw them relegated from the [[EFL Championship]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/sunderland-afc-netflix-documentary-gets-15064738 |title=Sunderland AFC Netflix documentary gets a release date and a title too |last=Johns |first=Craig |date=26 November 2018 |work=Evening Chronicle |access-date=29 January 2019}}</ref> As a result of the success of the first series, a second season was confirmed, despite opposition from many club members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.businesstimes.cn/articles/117639/20190825/sunderland-til-i-die-season-2-will-happen-despite-club-members-disapproval-to-documentary-series.htm|title='Sunderland 'Til I Die' Season 2 Will Happen Despite Club Members' Disapproval To Documentary Series|first=Business|last=Times|date=25 August 2019|website=Business Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sunderlandecho.com/sport/football/sunderland-afc/latest-sunderland-afc-news/sunderland-til-i-die-everything-we-know-so-far-about-season-two-popular-netflix-series-634112|title=This is when season two of Sunderland 'Til I Die is set to be released|website=www.sunderlandecho.com}}</ref> The opposition was mostly to do with players fearing the series would cause their failures being associated with them for the rest of their careers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/49254051|title=Sunderland: Jack Ross on Netflix, promotion & his legacy|date=9 August 2019|via=www.bbc.com|work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n==Nicknames==\n[[File:BLACK CATS.jpg|thumbnail|left|A Black Cat logo on the exterior of the Stadium of Light]]\nSunderland's official nickname is 'The Black Cats'. The previous nickname, 'The Rokerites', was made redundant after the club left Roker Park for the Stadium of Light in 1997.<ref name=\"nickname\">{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/page/BlackCatsNickname|title=Black Cats Nickname|publisher=Sunderland A.F.C.|accessdate=19 September 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090725202042/https://www.safc.com/page/BlackCatsNickname|archivedate=25 July 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> The new name was decided upon in a public vote that year.<ref name=\"safc.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/the-club/history/black-cats|title=Black Cats Nickname|date=17 July 2012|publisher=SAFC|accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/football/2000/feb/22/newsstory.sport4 Sunderland find new identity as The Black Cats], The Guardian, 22 February 2000</ref>\n\nDespite the nickname being made official only relatively recently, the black cat has been used as an emblem of the club throughout most of its history. Photographs exist of players holding a black cat which made Roker Park its home in the 1900s and 1910s, and which was fed and watered by the football club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ryehillfootball.co.uk/stories/the-original-sunderland-black-cat/|title=The Original Sunderland Black Cat \u2013 Ryehill Football|website=ryehillfootball.co.uk|language=en-US|access-date=19 May 2017}}</ref> The club's first official badge featured a black cat sitting prominently in its centre.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thebeautifulhistory.wordpress.com/clubs/sunderland/|title=Sunderland|date=28 May 2011|work=The Beautiful History|access-date=6 August 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> Since the 1960s the emblem of the Sunderland A.F.C. Supporters Association has been a black cat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.safcsahoe.co.uk/|title=Heart of England Branch|publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. Supporters Association|accessdate=19 September 2008}}</ref> A Sunderland supporter, Billy Morris, took a black cat in his chest pocket as a good luck charm to the 1937 FA Cup final in which Sunderland brought home the trophy for the first time.<ref name=\"nickname\"/> Reference has also been made to a \"Black Cat Battery\", an [[Artillery battery]] based on the [[River Wear]] during the [[Napoleonic Wars]].<ref name=\"nickname\" />\n\nAs well as club nicknames, names have been used to define memorable periods in the club's history. The \"Team of All Talents\" moniker was used during Sunderland's successful period in the 1890s,<ref name=\"History\" /> and Sunderland were known as the \"[[Bank of England]] club\" during the 1950s. This was in reference to the club's spending in the [[transfer market]] at the time, which saw the transfer-record broken twice.<ref name=\"History\" />\n\n==Statistics and records==\n{{main|List of Sunderland A.F.C. statistics and records}}\n[[File:Sunderland AFC League Performance.svg|right|thumb|300px|League positions since 1890\u201391 season.]]\nThe holder of the record for the most league appearances is [[Jimmy Montgomery]], having made 527&nbsp;first team appearances between 1961 and 1976.<ref>Dykes, pp 280\u2013282.</ref> The club's top league goal scorer is [[Charlie Buchan]], who scored 209&nbsp;goals from 1911\u20131925;<ref name=\"soccerbaserecords\">{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/team_records.sd?teamid=2493|title=Sunderland all time records|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=19 September 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080926194651/http://www.soccerbase.com/team_records.sd?teamid=2493#|archive-date=26 September 2008|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Bobby Gurney]] is the record goalscorer over all competitions with 228&nbsp;goals between 1926&nbsp;and&nbsp;1939.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.safc.premiumtv.co.uk.p.preprod.performgroup.com/page/PlayersArticleDetail/0,,10281~1929361,00.html |title=11. Bobby Gurney |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |access-date=8 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407043306/http://www.safc.premiumtv.co.uk.p.preprod.performgroup.com/page/PlayersArticleDetail/0,,10281~1929361,00.html |archive-date=7 April 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Dave Halliday]] holds the record for the most goals scored in a season: 43&nbsp;in the [[1928\u201329 in English football|1928\u201329 season]] in the Football League First Division.<ref name=\"soccerbaserecords\"/> As of October 2014 [[John O'Shea]] is the most capped player for the club, making 100&nbsp;appearances for the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]].<ref name=\"soccerbaserecords\"/>\n\nThe club's widest victory margin in the league was in the 9\u20131 win against Newcastle United in the First Division in 1908. Sunderland's biggest ever win in the FA cup was against Fair field (a non-league team) and the final score was 11\u20131.<ref name=\"page443\"/> Their heaviest defeats in the league were 8\u20130 against [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] in 1911, [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in 1968, [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] in 1982 and [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] in 2014<ref name=\"page443\">Mason, p 443.</ref> Sunderland joined the top division in England, [[The Football League]], in the [[1890\u201391 in English football|1890\u201391 season]] and were not relegated until [[1957\u201358 in English football|1957\u201358]] (a span of 67&nbsp;seasons). In October 2015, Sunderland defeated rivals Newcastle United for the sixth consecutive time, a new record.\n\nSunderland's record home attendance is 75,200 for a sixth round replay FA Cup match against Derby County on 8 March 1933.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stadiumguide.com/rokerpark.htm|title=Roker Park|publisher=The Stadium Guide|accessdate=21 December 2008}}</ref>\n\n=== Record goalscorers ===\n11 Sunderland players have scored 100 goals or more in all competitions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestatcat.co.uk/|title=Sunderland AFC - Statistics, History and Records - from TheStatCat|website=www.thestatcat.co.uk|access-date=2019-01-23}}</ref> They are as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!\n!Name\n!Goals\n|-\n|'''1'''\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Bobby Gurney]]\n|228\n|-\n|'''2'''\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Charlie Buchan]]\n|222\n|-\n|'''3'''\n|{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Dave Halliday]]\n|165\n|-\n|'''4'''\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[George Holley]]\n|159\n|-\n|'''5'''\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Kevin Phillips (footballer)|Kevin Phillips]]\n|130\n|-\n|'''6'''\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Raich Carter]]\n|128\n|-\n|'''7'''\n|{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Jimmy Millar (footballer, born 1870)|Jimmy Millar]]\n|127\n|-\n|'''8'''\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Arthur Bridgett]]\n|116\n|-\n|'''9'''\n|{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Patrick Gallacher|Patsy Gallacher]]\n|107\n|-\n|'''10'''\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Gary Rowell]]\n|103\n|-\n|'''11'''\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Len Shackleton]]\n|100\n|}\n\n===Transfers===\nThe biggest transfer fee Sunderland have ever received for one of their players is \u00a330 million for [[Jordan Pickford]], who moved to [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] on 1 July 2017. This was also the biggest fee Sunderland have received for a player produced by the Sunderland academy. The biggest transfer fee paid by Sunderland is the eventual \u00a317.1 million for [[Didier Ibrahim Ndong|Didier Ndong]], who was bought from [[FC Lorient]] in August 2016.\n\n===Overall===\n*Seasons spent at Level 1 of the [[English football league system|football league system]]: 86\n*Seasons spent at Level 2 of the football league system: 30\n*Seasons spent at Level 3 of the football league system: 3\n*Seasons spent at Level 4 of the football league system: 0\nAs of the [[2019\u201320 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2019\u201320 season]]\n\n==Kit sponsorship==\n\nThe first sponsor to appear on Sunderland kits was Cowie's, the business group of then chairman [[Tom Cowie]], between 1983\u201385.<ref name=\"kit\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/Sir-Tom-gets-own-campus.598289.jp|title=Sir Tom gets own campus!|date=27 August 2002|work=Sunderland Echo|accessdate=8 January 2009}}</ref> The club was sponsored by the [[Vaux Breweries]] between 1985 and 1999, with drink brands such as Lambtons sometimes appearing on kits. Subsequently, the club were sponsored by Sunderland car dealership company Reg Vardy from 1999 to 2007.<ref name=\"kit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/page/Kit|title=Kit History|publisher=Sunderland A.F.C.|accessdate=8 January 2009}}</ref> Sunderland were sponsored by the Irish bookmaker [[Boylesports]], who signed a four-year contract with the club in 2007 estimated to be worth \u00a38&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/sport/arena/a-safe-bet-38737.html|title=A safe bet|work=Irish Examiner|date=1 August 2007|access-date=1 December 2018}}</ref> In April 2010, Sunderland signed a two-year shirt sponsorship deal with [[Tombola (bingo company)|tombola]], a local online bingo company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/news/20100413/tombola-to-become-club-sponsor_2256213_2022672|title=Tombola to become club sponsor|publisher=Sunderland A.F.C.|date=13 April 2010|accessdate=13 April 2010}}</ref> On 25 June 2012, Sunderland announced the strengthening of their partnership with the Invest in Africa initiative, with the initiative becoming the club's shirt sponsor for two years. The project is closely linked with [[Tullow Oil]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/news/20120625/sunderland-steps-up-african-partnership_2256213_2821265|title=- SAFC|work=safc.com|accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref> However, after a year the club announced a new sponsorship deal with South African company [[Bidvest Group|Bidvest]]. On 1 June 2015 Sunderland announced a new sponsorship with [[Dafabet]] to appear on the kits for the following season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/sunderland-afc-announce-new-shirt-9365782|title=Sunderland AFC announce new shirt sponsor will be eGaming operator Dafabet|first=Craig|last=Johns|date=1 June 2015|website=nechronicle}}</ref>\n\nThe first kit manufacturer to appear on Sunderland kits was [[Umbro]], between 1975\u201381. French brand [[Le Coq Sportif]] produced kits between 1981\u201383. [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]]'s first stint as kit manufacturer came between 1983\u201386, before kits from [[Patrick (sportswear)|Patrick]] (1986\u201388), [[Hummel International|Hummel]] (1988\u201394), Avec (1994\u201397) and [[ASICS|Asics]] (1997\u201300). Nike returned between 2000\u201304. [[Diadora]] produced kits for a solitary season, 2004\u201305, and [[Lonsdale (clothing)|Lonsdale]] made kits between 2005\u201307. Umbro returned for five seasons between 2007\u201312, before [[Adidas]] became the club's kit manufacturer for the first time in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Sunderland/Sunderland.htm |title=Sunderland \u2013 Historical Football Kits |publisher=Historicalkits.co.uk |date=3 March 1956 |accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\" }\n|- align=\"center\"\n!Period\n!Kit manufacturer\n!Shirt sponsor\n|- align=\"center\"\n|1975\u201381\n|| [[Umbro]]\n|rowspan=2|{{small|none}}\n|- align=\"center\"\n|1981\u201383\n|| [[Le Coq Sportif]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|1983\u201385\n|rowspan=2|[[Nike, Inc.|Nike]]\n||Cowie's\n|- align=\"center\"\n|1985\u201386\n|rowspan=5| [[Vaux Breweries]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|1986\u201388\n|| [[Patrick (sportswear company)|Patrick]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|1988\u201394\n|| [[Hummel International|Hummel]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|1994\u201397\n|| Avec\n|- align=\"center\"\n|1997-00\n|| [[ASICS|Asics]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|2000\u201304\n||[[Nike, Inc.|Nike]]\n|rowspan=3| Reg Vardy\n|- align=\"center\"\n|2004\u201305\n|| [[Diadora]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|2005\u201307\n|| [[Lonsdale (clothing)|Lonsdale]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|2007\u201310\n|rowspan=2| [[Umbro]]\n|| [[Boylesports]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|2010\u201312\n|| [[Tombola (bingo company)|Tombola]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|2012\u201313\n|rowspan=5| [[Adidas]]\n|| Invest In Africa\n|- align=\"center\"\n|2013\u201315\n|| [[Bidvest Group|Bidvest]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|2015\u201318\n||[[Dafabet]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|2018\u201319\n||[[Betdaq]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|2019\u201320\n||[[Children with Cancer UK]]\n|}\n\n==Players==\n{{See also|Category:Sunderland A.F.C. players}}\n\n===First team squad===\n{{updated|1 February 2020|<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.safc.com/players/1st-team|title=1st Team|work=Sunderland Association Football Club|access-date=18 September 2019}}</ref>}}\n{{fs start}}\n{{Fs player |no=1 |nat=SCO |pos=GK |name=[[Jon McLaughlin (footballer)|Jon McLaughlin]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=2 |nat=NIR |pos=DF |name=[[Conor McLaughlin]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=3 |nat=WAL |pos=DF |name=[[Joel Lynch]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=4 |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=[[Jordan Willis (footballer)|Jordan Willis]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=5 |nat=TUR |pos=DF |name=[[Alim \u00d6zt\u00fcrk]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=6 |nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[Max Power (footballer)|Max Power]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=7 |nat=SCO |pos=FW |name=[[Chris Maguire]]|other=}}\n{{fs player |no=8 |nat=NIR |pos=FW |name=[[Kyle Lafferty]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=9 |nat=ENG |pos=FW |name=[[Charlie Wyke]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=11|nat=USA |pos=MF |name=[[Lynden Gooch]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=12|nat=NIR |pos=DF |name=[[Tom Flanagan (footballer)|Tom Flanagan]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=13|nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[Luke O'Nien]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=14|nat=ENG |pos=FW |name=[[Duncan Watmore]]|other=}}\n{{fs mid}}\n{{Fs player |no=16|nat=ENG |pos=GK |name=[[Lee Burge]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=17|nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[Elliot Embleton]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=18|nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[George Dobson (footballer, born 1997)|George Dobson]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=20|nat=WAL |pos=DF |name=[[Declan John]]|other=on loan from [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=21|nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[Ethan Robson]]|other=}}\n{{fs player |no=22|nat=NIR |pos=FW |name=[[Will Grigg]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=23|nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[Grant Leadbitter]]|other=[[Captain (association football)|captain]] }}\n{{fs player |no=25|nat=NZL |pos=DF |name=[[Tommy Smith (footballer, born 1990)|Tommy Smith]]|other=}}\n{{fs player |no=26|nat=AUS |pos=DF |name=[[Bailey Wright]]|other=on loan from [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=28|nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[Josh Scowen]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=33|nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=[[Denver Hume]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=42|nat=ENG |pos=FW |name=[[Antoine Semenyo]]|other=on loan from [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]}}\n{{fs end}}\n\n====Out on loan====\n{{fs start}}\n{{Fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=[[Jack Baldwin (footballer)|Jack Baldwin]]|other=at [[Salford City F.C.|Salford City]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=  |nat=IRE |pos=MF |name=[[Aiden McGeady]]|other=at [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]]}}\n{{fs end}}\n\n===Reserves and Academy===\n{{main|Sunderland A.F.C. Reserves and Academy}}\n\n==Club officials==\n\n===Board of Directors===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Position !! Name\n|-\n|Owner/Chairman || [[Stewart Donald]]\n|-\n|Director/Minority Shareholder (20%) || [[Juan Sartori]]\n|-\n|Executive Director || [[Charlie Methven]]\n|-\n|Finance Director ||  Angela Lowes\n|-\n|Director || Neil Fox\n|-\n|}\n\n''Information correct as of 12 June 2019'' <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.safc.com/players/board-and-management|title=Board and Management|work=Sunderland Association Football Club|access-date=12 June 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===Coaching staff===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Position !! Name\n|-\n|Manager\n| {{flagicon|England}} [[Phil Parkinson]]\n|-\n|Assistant Manager\n| {{flagicon|England}} [[Steve Parkin]]\n|-\n|Head of Recruitment\n| {{flagicon|England}} [[Tony Coton]]\n|-\n|Goalkeeping Coach\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Craig Samson]]\n|-\n|Academy Manager\n| {{flagicon|England}} [[Paul Reid (footballer, born 1982)|Paul Reid]]\n|-\n|Under 23 Head Coach\n| {{flagicon|England}} Elliott Dickman\n|-\n|Under 18 Head Coach\n| {{flagicon|England}} Paul Bryson\n|-\n|Senior Physiotherapist\n| {{flagicon|England}} Peter Brand\n|-\n|Kit Manager\n| {{flagicon|England}} [[John Cooke (footballer born 1962)|John Cooke]]\n|}\n\n''Information correct as of 12 November 2019'' <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.safc.com/players/backroom-staff|title=Backroom Staff|work=Sunderland Association Football Club|access-date=12 June 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Managers==\n{{main|List of Sunderland A.F.C. managers}}\n\n==Honours==\nThe following are the honours Sunderland have achieved since their foundation in 1879.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.safc.com/history/trophy-cabinet |title=Roll of Honour |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |access-date=21 December 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engsupcuphist.html|title=England&nbsp;\u2014 List of FA Charity/Community Shield Matches|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=21 December 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spartacus.schoolnet.co.uk/2WWfootball.htm |title=Football and the Second World War |publisher=Spartacus |accessdate=8 September 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225213503/http://www.spartacus.schoolnet.co.uk/2WWfootball.htm |archivedate=25 February 2009 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===League===\n* '''[[List of English football champions|First Division/Premier League]]: 6 (level 1)'''\n:[[1891\u201392 in English football|1891\u201392]], [[1892\u201393 in English football|1892\u201393]], [[1894\u201395 in English football|1894\u201395]], [[1901\u201302 in English football|1901\u201302]], [[1912\u201313 in English football|1912\u201313]], [[1935\u201336 in English football|1935\u201336]]\n\n* '''[[List of winners of English Football League Championship and predecessors|Second Division/First Division/Championship]]: 5 (level 2)'''\n:[[1975\u201376 in English football|1975\u201376]], [[1995\u201396 in English football|1995\u201396]], [[1998\u201399 in English football|1998\u201399]], [[2004\u201305 in English football|2004\u201305]], [[2006\u201307 in English football|2006\u201307]]\n:'''Promoted via Play Offs''': [[1990 Football League Second Division play-off Final|1989\u201390]]\n* '''[[List of winners of English Football League One and predecessors|Third Division/Second Division/League One]]: 1 (level 3)'''\n:[[1987\u201388 in English football|1987\u201388]]\n\n===Cup===\n* '''[[FA Cup]]: '''\n** '''Winners (2):''' [[1937 FA Cup Final|1937]], [[1973 FA Cup Final|1973]]\n* '''[[FA Community Shield|Charity Shield]]'''\n** '''Winners (1): ''' [[1936 FA Charity Shield|1936]]\n* '''[[Sheriff of London Charity Shield]]:'''\n** '''Winners (1):''' [[1902\u201303 in English football|1903]]\n\n===Other===\n*'''[[BBC Sports Personality Team of the Year Award]]: 1'''\n:1973\n\n*'''[[1895 World Championship (football)|Football World Championship]]: 1'''\n:1895\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|author1=Paul Days|author2=John Hudson|author3=Bernard Callaghan |title=Sunderland AFC: The Official History 1879\u20132000|publisher=Business Education Publishers Ltd|date=1 December 1999|page=336|isbn=978-0-9536984-1-7}}\n* {{cite book|author=Garth Dykes|author2=Doug Lamming |title=All The Lads: A Complete Who's Who of Sunderland A.F.C.|publisher=Polar Print Group Ltd|date=November 2000|page=312|isbn=978-1-899538-14-0}}\n* {{cite book|author=Rob Mason|title=Sunderland: The Complete Record|publisher=Breedon Books Publishing Co Ltd|date=October 2005|isbn=978-1-85983-472-5}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.thestatcat.co.uk|title=Sunderland AFC&nbsp;\u2014 Statistics, History and Records|publisher=The Stat Cat|accessdate=19 September 2008}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.safc.com/history/trophy-cabinet|title=Roll of Honour|publisher=Sunderland A.F.C.|accessdate=21 December 2008}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|North East England|Association football|English football}}\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|Sunderland A.F.C.ogg|2010-09-22}}\n{{Commons category-inline|Sunderland AFC}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.safc.com/}}\n{{BBC Football Info|BBClinkname=sunderland}}\n* [http://www.thestatcat.co.uk Sunderland AFC Statistics]\n* [http://www.answers-to-questions.info/England-Football-Play-Offs.aspx?team=Sunderland Sunderland play-off record]\n* [http://safc.blog/ SAFC Stats and Season Reviews from 1890\u20131891 to date]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/resources/idt-sh/the_last_pass The last pass The role of football clubs in WW1 including Jimmy Seed]\n{{Sunderland A.F.C.}}\n{{Football League One}}\n{{City of sunderland}}\n\n{{Featured article}}\n\n[[Category:Sunderland A.F.C.| ]]\n[[Category:1879 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1879]]\n[[Category:FA Cup winners]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in England]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:English Football League clubs]]\n[[Category:Premier League clubs]]\n[[Category:United Soccer Association imported teams]]\n[[Category:Mining association football teams]]\n[[Category:Sunderland]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the Ladies football club|Sunderland A.F.C. Ladies}}\n{{Redirect|SAFC}}\n{{pp-semi-indef|small=yes}}\n{{Short description|Association football club}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| nickname = The Black Cats\n| ground = [[Stadium of Light]]\n| capacity = 49,000\n| season = {{English football updater|Sunderld2}}\n| position = {{English football updater|Sunderld3}}\n| current = 2019\u201320 Sunderland A.F.C. season\n| pattern_la1   = \n| pattern_b1    = _sunderland1920h\n| pattern_ra1   = \n| pattern_sh1   = _adidasred\n| pattern_so1   = _3_stripes_white\n| leftarm1      = FFFFFF\n| body1         = FD1220\n| rightarm1     = FFFFFF\n| shorts1       = 000000\n| socks1        = FF0000\n| pattern_la2   = _sunderland1920a\n| pattern_b2    = _sunderland1920a\n| pattern_ra2   = _sunderland1920a\n| pattern_sh2   = _adidasred\n| pattern_so2   = _color_3_stripes_red\n| leftarm2      = 0000DD\n| body2         = 0000DD\n| rightarm2     = 0000DD\n| shorts2       = 0000DD\n| socks2        = 0000DD\n| clubname = Sunderland A.F.C.\n| image = Logo Sunderland.svg\n| upright = .8\n| fullname = Sunderland Association Football Club\n| short name = SAFC\n| founded = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1879}}<br/>(as ''Sunderland and District Teachers'')\n| owner = [[Stewart Donald]]\n| chairman = \n| manager = [[Phil Parkinson]]\n| league = {{English football updater|Sunderld}}\n| website = http://www.safc.com/\n}}\n'''Sunderland Association Football Club''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=en-uk-Sunderland.ogg|\u02c8|s|\u028c|n|d|\u0259r|l|\u0259|n|d}}, {{IPAc-en|local|\u02c8|s|\u028a|n|d|l|\u0259|n}}) is an English professional [[association football|football]] club based in the city of [[Sunderland]], [[Tyne and Wear]]. Sunderland play in [[EFL League One|League One]], the third tier of English football. Since its formation in 1879,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/teams2.sd?teamid=2493|title=Sunderland|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=19 September 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100510200457/http://www.soccerbase.com/teams2.sd?teamid=2493#|archive-date=10 May 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> the club has won six top-flight ([[Football League First Division|First Division]], now the [[Premier League]]) titles (1892, 1893, 1895, 1902, 1913 and 1936), a total only bettered by five other clubs, and has finished runners-up five times. The club has also won the [[FA Cup]] twice (1937 and 1973) and been runners-up twice (1913 and 1992), as well as winning the [[FA Community Shield|FA Charity Shield]] in 1936 and being finalists the following year. Sunderland have also been [[Football League Cup]] finalists in 1985 and 2014.\n\nSunderland play their home games at the 49,000-capacity [[all-seater stadium|all-seater]] [[Stadium of Light]] having moved from [[Roker Park]] in 1997. The original ground capacity was 42,000 which was increased to 49,000 following expansion in 2000. Sunderland have a long-standing rivalry with their neighbouring club [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], with whom they have contested the [[Tyne\u2013Wear derby]] since 1898.\n\n==History==\n{{main|History of Sunderland A.F.C.}}\n{{For|a statistical breakdown by season|List of Sunderland A.F.C. seasons}}\n\n===Early years and \"the team of all talents\" (1879\u20131908)===\n[[File:Sunderland-1884.jpg|thumb|left|Team photo taken in 1884]]\nThe club was founded as ''<nowiki/>'Sunderland and District Teachers A.F.C''.' by [[schoolmaster]] [[James Allan (footballer, born 1857)|James Allan]] in what has commonly been believed to be October 1879.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.safc.com/history/beginnings|title=Beginnings|work=Sunderland Association Football Club|access-date=6 April 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> However, evidence suggests that the club was not formally created until a year later, on 25 September 1880.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestatcat.co.uk/Article1.aspx|title=Sunderland AFC \u2013 Statistics, History and Records \u2013 from TheStatCat|website=www.thestatcat.co.uk|access-date=2019-01-04}}</ref> It was renamed as ''<nowiki/>'Sunderland A.F.C.''' and became open to more than just school teachers in October 1880.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n[[File:John Middleton Campbell.jpg|thumb|left|[[John Campbell (footballer, born 1870)|John Campbell]], a part of \"the team of all talents\", and league top scorer in Sunderland's first three titles.]]\nSunderland joined [[English Football League|The Football League]] for the [[1890\u201391 Sunderland A.F.C. season|1890\u201391 season]].<ref name=\"History\" /> They replaced [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke]], who had failed to be re-elected, becoming the first new club to join the league since its inauguration in 1888.<ref>Days, p 27.</ref> [[Tom Watson (football manager)|Tom Watson]] became Sunderland's first manager when he was appointed in 1888.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/history/?page_id=2997|title=Past Managers 1889\u20131939|publisher=Sunderland A.F.C.|accessdate=6 January 2009}}</ref> During the late 19th century, they were declared the \"Team of All Talents\" by [[William McGregor (football)|William McGregor]],<ref name=\"Days21\">Days, p 21.</ref> the founder of the league, after a 7\u20132 win against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]].<ref name=\"Days21\" /> Sunderland won the league championship in the [[1891\u201392 Sunderland A.F.C. season|1891\u201392 season]], one season after joining The Football League. The club's 42 points were five clear of nearest rivals [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]], and this performance led ''[[The Times]]'' to describe the players as \"a wonderfully fine team\".<ref name=\"TheTimes\">Days, pp 29\u201330.</ref> Sunderland successfully defended the title the following season, aided by their Scottish [[forward (association football)|centre forward]] [[John Campbell (footballer born 1870)|John Campbell]], who broke the 30-goal mark for the second time in consecutive seasons. In the process, they became the first team to score 100 goals in a season, a feat not matched until [[1919\u201320 in English football|1919\u201320]], when [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] set a new record.<ref>Days, pp 31\u201332.</ref>\n[[File:Thomas Hemy Sunderland v Aston Villa 1895 A Corner Kick.jpg|thumbnail|right|One of the earliest football paintings in the world, Thomas MM Hemy's \"Sunderland v. [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] 1895\" depicts a match between the two most successful English teams of the decade.]]\n\nSunderland came close to winning a third successive league championship in the [[1893\u201394 in English football|1893\u201394 season]], finishing second behind Aston Villa. However, they regained the title in the [[1894\u201395 in English football|1894\u201395 season]], ending the season five points ahead of [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], with Campbell becoming league top scorer for the third time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2016/7/20/12222208/sunderland-s-first-great-centre-forward|title=Sunderland's First Great Centre Forward|date=20 July 2016|website=Roker Report}}</ref> After winning the English League Championship, Sunderland beat [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]], the champions of the Scottish League, 5\u20133 in a game described as the ''[[1894/95 World Championship|Championship of the World]]'' title match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heartsfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/HeartsHistory/0,,10289~985232,00.html|title=Hearts History 1894\u20131904|publisher=Hearts F.C.|accessdate=8 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090101160956/http://www.heartsfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/HeartsHistory/0%2C%2C10289~985232%2C00.html|archivedate=1 January 2009}}</ref><ref>Days, pp 35\u201336.</ref>\n\nImportant to Campbell's success in attack were other \"Team of all Talents\" players from [[Scotland]]: [[Jimmy Hannah]] and [[Jimmy Millar (footballer, born 1870)|Jimmy Millar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ryehillfootball.co.uk/stories/johnny-campbell/|title=Johnny Campbell \u2013 Ryehill Football}}</ref> Their goalkeeper [[Ned Doig]] set a 19th-century world record by not conceding any goals in 87 of his 290 top division appearances (30%).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://iffhs.de/history-curiosities-of-world-football-1891-1900/|title=HISTORY : CURIOSITIES OF WORLD FOOTBALL (1891-1900)|date=25 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter taking Sunderland to three English League championship titles manager Watson resigned at the end of the 1895\u201396 season, in order to join Liverpool.<ref name=\"p39\">Days, p. 39.</ref> [[Robert Campbell (football manager)|Robert Campbell]] replaced him.<ref name=\"p39\"/> From 1886 until 1898, Sunderland's home ground was in Newcastle Road.<ref>Days, p. 44.</ref> In 1898, the club moved to what would become their home for almost a century, [[Roker Park]].<ref name=\"rokerpark\">Days, pp. 45\u201346.</ref> Initially the ground had a capacity of 30,000.<ref name=\"rokerpark\"/> However, over the following decades it was continually expanded, and at its peak would hold an official crowd of over 75,000 in a sixth round FA Cup replay against [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] on 8 March 1933.<ref>Days, p. 134.</ref> Campbell did not achieve the same playing success as former manager Watson, as Sunderland failed to win any titles in his three seasons at the club, which he left in the [[1898\u201399 in English football|1898\u201399 season]] to join [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]].<ref>Days, p. 45.</ref>\n\nScotsman [[Alex Mackie]] replaced Campbell as manager for the 1899 season.<ref>Days, pp. 55\u201356.</ref> Following a second place finish in 1900-01, the club won their fourth league title in the [[1901\u201302 in English football|1901\u201302 season]], beating Everton by a three-point margin.<ref>Days, pp 55\u201356.</ref> They followed this up with victory in the [[Sheriff of London Charity Shield]], a competition featuring the best amateur and professional sides in England and precursor to the [[FA Community Shield|Charity Shield]]. Sunderland beat leading amateurs [[Corinthian F.C.|Corinthians]] 3\u20130.<ref>Days, pp. 59\u201360.</ref>\n\nIn December 1902, [[Arthur Bridgett]] joined Sunderland. He went on to captain the \"Black Cats\" for ten years and gain eleven England caps, making him the club's second most-capped England international behind [[David Watson (footballer, born 1946)|Dave Watson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.englandstats.com/club.php?cid=104|title=England Players from Sunderland|accessdate=19 January 2020|publisher=englandstats.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1904, Sunderland's management was embroiled in a payment scandal involving player [[Andy McCombie|Andrew McCombie]]. The club was said to have given the player \u00a3100 (\u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|100|1904|r=-2}}|0}} today) to help him start his own business, on the understanding that he would repay the money after his benefit game.{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}} However, McCombie refused to repay the money, claiming it had been a gift. An investigation conducted by the [[The Football Association|Football Association]] concluded that the money given to McCombie was part of a \"re-signing/win/draw bonus\", which violated the Association's rules. Sunderland were fined \u00a3250 (\u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|250|1904|r=-2}}|0}} today), and six directors were suspended for two and a half years for not showing a true record of the club's financial dealings. Mackie was also suspended for three months for his involvement in the affair.{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}}<ref name=mackie>Days, p 63.</ref>\n\n===Further league championship titles (1908\u20131950)===\nOn 5 December 1908, Sunderland achieved their highest ever league win, against north-east rivals Newcastle United. They won the game 9\u20131; [[Billy Hogg]] and [[George Holley]] each scored [[hat-trick]]s, while [[Arthur Bridgett]] scored two.<ref>Days, pp 73\u201376.</ref> Under [[Ireland|Irish]] manager [[Bob Kyle]] and with [[Scotland|Scottish]] [[Charles Thomson (footballer, born 1878)|Charles Thomson]] as captain, the club won the league again in 1913,<ref>Days, pp 85\u201386.</ref> but lost their first [[FA Cup final]] 1\u20130 to Aston Villa, in a very tough loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=257177|title=English FA Cup&nbsp;\u2014 Final 1913|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=19 December 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050222213709/http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=257177#|archive-date=22 February 2005|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This was the closest the club has come to winning the league title and the FA Cup in the same season.<ref>Days, pp 87\u201388.</ref>\n\nThis period in their history also saw the goalscoring of [[Charlie Buchan]], who went on to score 221 goals for Sunderland,<ref>Dykes, pp. 58\u201359.</ref> making himthe second highest goalscorer in the club's history, behind [[Bob Gurney]].<ref>Dykes, pp. 170\u2013171.</ref> Holley was the league's top scorer in the season before Sunderland won the title.\n\nTwo seasons later the First World War brought the league to a halt. After the league's resumption, Sunderland came close to winning another championship in the [[1922\u201323 in English football|1922\u201323 season]], when they were runners-up to Liverpool.<ref>Days, pp 107\u2013108.</ref> They also came close the following season, finishing third, four points from the top of the league.<ref>Days, pp 111\u2013112.</ref> The club escaped relegation from the First Division by one point in the [[1927\u201328 in English football|1927\u201328 season]] despite 35 goals from [[Dave Halliday]].[[File:Rokerlads1937.jpg|thumb|right|Sunderland's 1937 FA Cup winning side]] The point was won in a match against [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]], and they finished in fifteenth place.<ref>Days, pp 121\u2013122.</ref> Halliday improved his goal scoring to 43 goals in 42 games the following season,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engtops.html#1920-1|title=Football League Div 1 & 2 Leading Goalscorers 1920\u201339|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=5 December 2008}}</ref> an all-time Sunderland record for goals scored in a single season.<ref name=\"History\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.safc.premiumtv.co.uk.p.preprod.performgroup.com/page/ClubHistoryDetail/0,,10281,00.html |title=Club History |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |access-date=8 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180406232607/http://www.safc.premiumtv.co.uk.p.preprod.performgroup.com/page/ClubHistoryDetail/0,,10281,00.html |archive-date=6 April 2018 |url-status=dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe club's sixth league championship came in the [[1935\u201336 in English football|1935\u201336]] season under [[Scotland|Scottish]] manager [[Johnny Cochrane]].<ref>Days, pp 139\u2013140.</ref> They scored 109&nbsp;goals during the season, with [[Raich Carter]] and [[Bobby Gurney]] each scoring 31.<ref>Days, pp. 139\u2013142.</ref> The League championship led to Sunderland playing in the Charity Shield against FA Cup-winners Arsenal. Sunderland won the shield after goals from [[Eddie Burbanks]] and Raich Carter.<ref name=\"shield\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engsupcuphist.html|title=England&nbsp;\u2014 List of FA Charity/Community Shield Matches|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=30 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nDespite winning the league, the season did not go without tragedy. The young goalkeeper of the team, [[Jimmy Thorpe]], died as a result of a kick in the head and chest after he had picked up the ball following a [[backpass]] in a game against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] at [[Roker Park]]. He continued to take part until the match finished, but collapsed at home afterwards and died in hospital four days later from [[diabetes mellitus]] and heart failure 'accelerated by the rough usage of the opposing team'.<ref name=\"Goalkeeper's Death\">{{cite news|title=Goalkeeper's Death|url=http://archive.timesonline.co.uk/tol/viewArticle.arc?articleId=ARCHIVE-The_Times-1936-02-14-16-001&pageId=ARCHIVE-The_Times-1936-02-14-16 | location=London | work=The Times|date=14 February 1936}}</ref> This tragic incident led to a change in the rules, whereby players were no longer allowed to raise their foot to a goalkeeper when he had control of the ball in his arms.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?xml=/sport/2006/10/04/soinve04.xml |location=London |title=On the run with dogs and a long-dead goalkeeper - Telegraph |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311055415/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?xml=%2Fsport%2F2006%2F10%2F04%2Fsoinve04.xml |archive-date=11 March 2007 |df= }}</ref>\n\nThey won the FA Cup the following season, after a 3\u20131 victory against Preston North End at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.soccerbase.com/teams/team.sd?team_id=2493&season_id=66&teamTabs=results|title=Sunderland Results 1936/37|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe remainder of the decade saw mid-table finishes, until the league and FA Cup were suspended for the duration of the Second World War. Some football was still played as a morale boosting exercise, in the form of the [[Football League War Cup]]. Sunderland were finalists in the tournament in [[1942 Football League War Cup Final|1942]], but were beaten by [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]].<ref>Days, p 154.</ref>\n\nFor Sunderland, the immediate post-war years were characterised by significant spending; the club paid \u00a318,000 (\u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|18000|1949|r=-3}}|0}} today) for [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]]'s [[Ivor Broadis]] in January 1949.{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}} Broadis was also Carlisle's manager at the time, and this is the first instance of a player transferring himself to another club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/1904999.broadis_still_bubbling_along_at_85/|title=Broadis still; bubbling along at 85|last=Amos|first=Mike|date=14 December 2007|work=The Northern Echo|accessdate=19 September 2008}}</ref> This, along with record-breaking transfer fees to secure the services of [[Len Shackleton]] and the Welsh international [[Trevor Ford]], led to a contemporary nickname, the \"[[Bank of England club]]\".<ref>Days, pp 169\u2013170.</ref> The club finished third in the First Division in [[1949\u201350 in English football|1950]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/engpaul/FLA/1949-50.html|title=Season 1949\u201350|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=8 September 2010}}</ref> their highest finish since the 1936 championship.\n\nShackleton, known as the \"Clown Prince of Soccer\", later admitted that the players were more a collection of talented individuals than a true team, and that \"it takes time to harness and control a team of [[thoroughbred]]s. It took time to achieve the blend at Roker Park\".<ref>{{harvnb|Malam|2004|p=84}}</ref>{{full citation needed|date=September 2019}} Shackleton and centre-forward Ford would never build any kind of relationship on or off the pitch however, and Ford once threatened to never play in the same Sunderland team as Shackleton until he was forced to back down by manager [[Bill Murray (footballer, born 1901)|Bill Murray]].<ref name=\"Malam 2004 87\">{{harvnb|Malam|2004|p=87}}</ref>{{full citation needed|date=September 2019}} Ford was sold on to [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] in November 1953.<ref>{{harvnb|Malam|2004|p=88}}</ref>{{full citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n===Financial troubles and three cup finals (1950\u20131995)===\nThe late 1950s saw a sharp downturn in Sunderland's fortunes, and the club was once again implicated in a major financial scandal in 1957.<ref name=mackie/> Found guilty of making payments to players in excess of the [[Salary cap|maximum wage]], they were fined \u00a35,000 (\u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|5000|1957|r=-3}}}} today), and their chairman and three directors were suspended.{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}}<ref>Days, pp 183\u2013184.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.givemefootball.com/pfa/pfa-history/the-jimmy-hill-years-pfa-chairman-1957-1961 |title=The Jimmy Hill Years: PFA Chairman 1957\u20131961 |publisher=Professional Footballers' Association |accessdate=4 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100915053426/http://www.givemefootball.com/pfa/pfa-history/the-jimmy-hill-years-pfa-chairman-1957-1961 |archivedate=15 September 2010 }}</ref> The following year, Sunderland were [[promotion and relegation|relegated]] from the highest division for the first time in their 68-year league history.<ref>Days, p 187.</ref>\n[[File:Ianporterfieldgoal.jpg|thumb|right|Ian Porterfield's winning goal in the 1973 FA Cup Final]]\nSunderland's absence from the top flight lasted six years. The club came within one game of promotion back to the First Division in the [[1962\u201363 in English football|1962\u201363 season]]. Sunderland required only a draw in their final game against promotion rivals Chelsea, who had another game left to play after this match, to secure promotion. However, they were defeated,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.soccerbase.com/teams/team.sd?team_id=2493&season_id=92&teamTabs=results|title=Sunderland Results 1962/63|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref> and Chelsea won their last game 7\u20130 to clinch promotion, finishing ahead of Sunderland on [[goal average]].<ref>Days, pp 199\u2013200.</ref> After the close call in the previous season, the club was promoted to Division One in 1964 after finishing in second place. Sunderland beat [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] in the final stages of the season, where they clinched promotion with a game to spare.<ref>Days, pp 201\u2013202.</ref> At the end of the decade, they were again relegated to the Second Division after finishing 21st.<ref>Days, pp 217\u2013218.</ref>\n\n[[File:1973facuphomecoming.jpg|thumb|left|upright|The homecoming open top bus parade after victory in the 1973 FA Cup final]]\nSunderland won their last major trophy in 1973, in a 1\u20130 victory over [[Don Revie]]'s [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] in the FA Cup Final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/FACompetitions/TheFACup/History/HistoryOfTheFACup/1973SunderlandLeeds|title=1973 Sunderland v Leeds|publisher=TheFA|accessdate=8 September 2010}}</ref> A [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] club at the time, Sunderland won the game thanks mostly to the efforts of their goalkeeper [[Jimmy Montgomery]], who saved two of Leeds shots at goal in quick succession, one being from hot-shot [[Peter Lorimer]].<ref name=\"1973FACupfinal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2003/12/FACup_200304_3R_Montgomery.htm|archive-url=https://archive.is/20041211150904/http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2003/12/FACup_200304_3R_Montgomery.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=11 December 2004|title=Monty wanting more heroics|author=Richard Morgan|date=31 December 2003|publisher=The FA|accessdate=28 November 2008}}</ref> [[Ian Porterfield]] scored a [[volley (football)|volley]] in the 30th minute to beat Leeds and take the trophy.<ref name=\"1973FACupfinal\"/> Since 1973 only two other clubs, [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] in 1976,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/FACompetitions/TheFACup/History/HistoryOfTheFACup/1976SouthamptonManUnited|title=1976 Southampton v Man United|publisher=TheFA|accessdate=8 September 2010}}</ref> and [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in 1980,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/columnists/henrywinter/2296500/Ledley-volley-sends-Cardiff-City-to-FA-Cup-final.html|title=Ledley volley sends Cardiff City to FA Cup final|author=Henry Winter|date=7 April 2008|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=28 November 2008|location=London}}</ref> have equalled Sunderland's achievement of lifting the FA Cup while playing outside the top tier of English football.\n\nBy winning the [[1973 FA Cup Final]], Sunderland qualified for the [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]], the club's only appearance in European competition to date.<ref name=\"Euro\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec197374.html#cwc|title=European Competitions 1973\u201374|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=19 December 2008}}</ref> Sunderland beat [[Vasas SC|Vasas Budapest]] 3\u20130 on [[Two-legged tie|aggregate]], and were drawn against Lisbon club [[Sporting Clube de Portugal|Sporting]] in the [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup 1973\u201374#Second round|second round]].<ref name=\"Euro\"/> They won the first leg at [[Roker Park]] 2\u20131 but were defeated 2\u20130 in the away leg, and were knocked out of the competition 3\u20132 on aggregate.<ref name=\"Euro\"/> After spending six seasons in the Second Division, Sunderland were promoted to Division One in the [[1975\u201376 in English football|1975\u201376 season]]; they topped the table over [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] by three points.<ref>Days, pp 235\u2013236.</ref> However, Sunderland were relegated the following season back into Division Two, without their FA Cup Final winning manager Bob Stokoe, who had resigned because of health problems at the start of the season.<ref>Days, pp 239\u2013240.</ref> The club celebrated its 100-year centenary in the [[1979\u201380 in English football|1979\u201380 season]] with a [[testimonial match|testimonial]] against an England XI side, which they lost 2\u20130.<ref>Days, pp 247\u2013248.</ref>\n\nSunderland appeared in their first [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] [[1985 Football League Cup Final|final]] in 1985, but lost 1\u20130 to [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engleagcuphistfull.html#85|title=England League Cup Full Results 1960\u20131996|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=8 September 2010}}</ref> In 1987, Sunderland saw one of the lowest points in their history, when they were relegated to the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] of the English league for the first time.<ref>Days, pp 265\u2013266.</ref> Under new chairman [[Bob Murray (businessman)|Bob Murray]] and new manager [[Denis Smith (football manager)|Denis Smith]], the club was promoted the following season.<ref>Days, pp 269\u2013270.</ref> In 1990, they were promoted back to the top flight in unusual circumstances. Sunderland lost to [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] in the play-off final, but Swindon's promotion was revoked after the club was found guilty of financial irregularities and Sunderland were promoted instead.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/wiltshire/3976405.stm|title=Football fan's 1,000 game milestone|author=Chris Kelly|date=4 November 2004|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref> They stayed up for one year before being relegated on the final day of the following season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/engpaul/FLA/1990-91.html|title=Season 1990\u201391|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=8 September 2010}}</ref>\n[[File:Peter Reid Sunderland 1998small.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Peter Reid was appointed Sunderland manager in 1997, and served until 2002]]\nSunderland's next outing in a major final came in [[1992 FA Cup Final|1992]] when, as a Second Division club, they returned to the FA Cup final. There was to be no repeat of the heroics of 1973, as Sunderland lost 2\u20130 to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fa-cupfinals.co.uk/1992.htm |title=Liverpool 2 Sunderland 0 |publisher=FA Cup Finals |accessdate=8 September 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071023204315/http://www.fa-cupfinals.co.uk/1992.htm |archivedate=23 October 2007 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===New stadium, promotions and relegations (1995\u20132006)===\nIn 1995, they faced the prospect of a return to the third-tier of English football.<ref>Days, pp 291\u2013292.</ref> [[Peter Reid]] was brought in as manager, and quickly turned things around. Reid's time in charge had a stabilising effect; he remained manager for seven years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/managers2.sd?managerid=1031|title=Peter Reid's managerial career|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=20 September 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071124052357/http://www.soccerbase.com/managers2.sd?managerid=1031#|archive-date=24 November 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> After promotion from Division One in the [[1995\u201396 in English football|1995\u201396 season]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/engpaul/FLA/1995-96.html|title=England 1995/96|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=8 September 2010}}</ref> Sunderland began their first season in the [[Premier League]], but finished third from the bottom and were relegated back to the First Division,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/engpaul/FLA/1996-97.html|title=Season 1996\u201397|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=8 September 2010}}</ref> despite beating Manchester United,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=241571|title=Sunderland 2&nbsp;\u2013 1 Man Utd|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=6 January 2009}}</ref> Arsenal<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=241525|title=Sunderland 1&nbsp;\u2013 0 Arsenal|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=6 January 2009}}</ref> and Chelsea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=242206|title=Sunderland 3&nbsp;\u2013 0 Chelsea|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=6 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, Sunderland left [[Roker Park]], their home for 99 years. Bearing fond memories of the stadium, former Sunderland player [[Len Shackleton]] said, \"There will never be another place like Roker\".<ref>Days, p 298.</ref> The club moved to the [[Stadium of Light]], a 42,000-seat arena that, at the time, was the largest stadium built in England after the Second World War.<ref name=\"SOL\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.safc.com/club/stadium-of-light |title=Stadium of Light |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |access-date=8 September 2010}}</ref> The capacity was later increased to 49,000.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/clubs/profile.stadium.html/sunderland |title=Club Profile &#124; Sunderland |publisher=Premierleague.com |accessdate=17 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208114958/http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/clubs/profile.stadium.html/sunderland |archivedate= 8 February 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\nSunderland returned to the Premier League as First Division champions in 1999 with a then-record 105 points.<ref>Days, p 312.</ref> Sunderland's [[1999\u20132000 in English football|1999\u20132000]] season started at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]], where Chelsea beat them 4\u20130.<ref name=\"soccerbase\">{{cite web|url=https://www.soccerbase.com/teams/team.sd?team_id=2493&season_id=129&teamTabs=results|title=Sunderland Results 1999/00|publisher=[[Soccerbase]]|accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref> However, in the return match later in the season Sunderland turned the tables on Chelsea, avenging their 4\u20130 defeat with a 4\u20131 win at the Stadium of Light.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/fa_carling_premiership/550014.stm|title=Chelsea shot down in flames|date=5 December 1999|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=2 November 2008}}</ref>  Sunderland also achieved a 2\u20131 victory over rivals Newcastle United at St. James' Park,<ref name=\"soccerbase\"/> a result which helped bring about the resignation of Newcastle's manager, [[Ruud Gullit]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nufc.com/html/gullit-resigns.html|title=Gullit Resignation Statement|date=28 August 1999|publisher=Newcastle United F.C.|accessdate=2 November 2008}}</ref> At the end of the season Sunderland finished seventh, with [[Kevin Phillips (footballer)|Kevin Phillips]] winning the [[European Golden Shoe]] in his first top-flight season, scoring 30 goals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sunderland/856691.stm|title=Phillips nets Golden prize|date=29 July 2000|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=2 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nAnother seventh-place finish in the 2000\u201301 season was followed by two less successful seasons, and they were relegated to the second-tier with a then-record low 19 points in 2003.<ref name=\"History\" /><ref name=\"recent\">{{cite web|url=http://www.premierleague.com/page/sunderland|title=Club Profile|publisher=Premier League|accessdate=20 September 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509075844/http://www.premierleague.com/page/sunderland|archivedate=9 May 2008}}</ref> Former [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Ireland]] manager [[Mick McCarthy]] took over at the club, and, in 2005, he took Sunderland up as champions for the third time in less than 10 years.<ref name=\"History\" /> However, the club's stay in the top flight was short-lived as Sunderland were once again relegated, this time with a new record-low total of 15 points. McCarthy left the club in mid-season, and he was replaced temporarily by former Sunderland player [[Kevin Ball]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sunderland/4778496.stm|title=Sunderland sack manager McCarthy|date=6 March 2006|publisher=BCB Sport|accessdate=8 September 2010}}</ref> The record-low 15-point performance was surpassed in the [[Premier League 2007\u201308|2007\u201308 season]] by [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]], who finished on 11 points.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sunderland/4856682.stm#Derby|title=Where do woeful Derby rank?|last=Stevenson|first=Jonathon|date=29 March 2008|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=20 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Drumaville Consortium takeover and Ellis Short era (2006\u20132016)===\n[[File:Quinn, Niall.jpg|thumb|Former player Niall Quinn led the takeover of the club in 2006, and spent six more years at the club in the roles of manager, chairman and Director of International Development]]\nFollowing Sunderland's relegation from the Premier League, the club was taken over by the Irish [[Drumaville Consortium]],<ref name=\"History\" /> headed by ex-player [[Niall Quinn]], who appointed former [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] captain [[Roy Keane]] as the new manager.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sunderland/5290778.stm|title=Keane becomes new Sunderland boss|date=28 August 2006|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 September 2008}}</ref> Under Keane, the club rose steadily up the table with an unbeaten run of 17 games<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/apr/23/match.sunderland|title=Keane's march to the top falters on tiny Colchester's own ambitions|last=Alexander|first=Jeremy|date=23 April 2007|work=The Guardian|accessdate=21 September 2008 | location=London}}</ref> to win promotion to the Premier League,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/6578817.stm|title=Crystal Palace 2\u20130 Derby|last=Mercer|first=Nathan|date=29 April 2007|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 September 2008}}</ref> and were named winners of the [[Football League Championship|Championship]] after beating [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] 5\u20130 at [[Kenilworth Road]] on 6 May 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/may/07/match.sunderland|title=Sunderland's title has Keane almost smiling|last=Walker|first=Michael|date=7 May 2007|work=The Guardian|accessdate=21 September 2008 | location=London}}</ref> Following an inconsistent start to the [[2008\u201309 in English football|2008\u201309 season]], Keane resigned.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sunderland/8066360.stm|title=Sbragia resigns from Sunderland|date=25 May 2009|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=26 September 2009}}</ref> Before the start of the following campaign, Irish-American businessman [[Ellis Short]] completed a full takeover of the club,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/sunderland/5392742/Steve-Bruce-set-for-Sunderland-talks-while-Ellis-Short-completes-takeover.html|title=Steve Bruce set for Sunderland talks while Ellis Short completes takeover|author=Rob Stewart|date=27 May 2009|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=27 May 2011|location=London}}</ref> and [[Steve Bruce]] was announced as the next manager on 3 June.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sunderland/8080762.stm|title=Bruce named as Sunderland manager|date=3 June 2009|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=26 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nOne of Bruce's first signings, [[Darren Bent]], cost a club record fee of \u00a310 million, broken a year later when they bought Ghana international [[Asamoah Gyan]] for around \u00a313&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"gyan\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/8958346.stm|title=Asamoah Gyan joins Sunderland for record \u00a313m fee|date=31 August 2010|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=8 September 2010}}</ref> Sunderland started the 2010\u201311 season strongly, but after Bent left for [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in January 2011 in a deal potentially worth \u00a324 million, a record transfer fee received for the club,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/jan/17/darren-bent-sunderland-aston-villa|title=Darren Bent heads for Aston Villa in record \u00a324m deal|author=Louise Taylor|date=17 January 2011|work=The Guardian|accessdate=30 November 2011|location=London}}</ref> they eventually finished 10th&nbsp;\u2014 which was still their highest top-flight finish for 10 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/sport/sunderland-afc/chris-young-column/west_ham_0_sunderland_3_win_means_sunderland_finish_above_newcastle_1_3407202?commentssort=1&commentspage=10|title=West Ham 0 Sunderland 3: Win means Sunderland finish above Newcastle|date=22 May 2011|publisher=Sunderland Echo|accessdate=30 November 2011}}</ref> After being named Sunderland's Young Player of the Year for two seasons in a row,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/sunderland-afcs-academy-graduates-now-15359267|title=Sunderland AFC's academy graduates - where are they now?|first=Sean|last=McCormick|date=2 November 2018|website=nechronicle}}</ref> at the end of the [[2010\u201311 Premier League|2010-11]] season, [[Jordan Henderson]] was transferred to [[Liverpool FC]], where he went on to become captain and win the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://talksport.com/football/550057/liverpool-damien-comolli-jordan-henderson-super-cup-champions-league/|title=Former Liverpool chief explain Jordan Henderson transfer cost him his job|date=15 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/jurgen-klopp-turned-down-jordan-16635323|title=Inside story of what happened on night of Liverpool's CL final win|first=Ian|last=Doyle|date=24 July 2019|website=liverpoolecho}}</ref>\n\nShort replaced Quinn as chairman in October 2011, with Quinn becoming Director of International Development.<ref>{{cite news|author=|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15159659.stm |title=Niall Quinn steps down as Sunderland chairman |publisher=BBC Sport |date=3 October 2011 |accessdate=17 February 2012}}</ref> Bruce was sacked in November 2011,<ref>{{cite news|author=|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15975008.stm |title=Sunderland sack Steve Bruce as manager |publisher=BBC Sport |date=30 November 2011 |accessdate=17 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Press Association |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/nov/30/steve-bruce-leaves-sunderland |title=Steve Bruce sacked by Sunderland |work=The Guardian |date= 30 November 2011|accessdate=17 February 2012 |location=London}}</ref> and replaced by [[Martin O'Neill]].<ref>{{cite news|author=|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15997197.stm |title=Martin O'Neill named Sunderland manager |publisher=BBC Sport |date=3 December 2011 |accessdate=17 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Press Association |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/dec/03/martin-oneill-sunderland |title=Martin O'Neill named as Sunderland manager after signing three-year deal |work=The Guardian |date=3 December 2011 |accessdate=17 February 2012 |location=London}}</ref> In February 2012, Quinn left the club with immediate effect.<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/sunderland/9092819/Niall-Quinn-leaves-Sunderland-with-immediate-effect-to-concentrate-on-business-interests-outside-football.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Niall Quinn leaves Sunderland with immediate effect to concentrate on business interests outside football | date=20 February 2012}}</ref> O'Neill was sacked in March 2013<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11695/8608743/Martin-O-Neill-sacked-as-Sunderland-manager-after-Manchester-United-defeat|title=Martin O'Neill sacked as Sunderland manager after Manchester United defeat|work=SkySports|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref> and Italian [[Paolo Di Canio]] was announced as his  replacement the following day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21990117 |title=Paolo Di Canio appointed Sunderland head coach |publisher=BBC Sport |date=31 March 2013 |accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref> The appointment prompted the immediate resignation of club Vice Chairman [[David Miliband]] due to Di Canio's \"past political statements\".<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-21991812 | work=BBC News | title=Di Canio: David Miliband quits Sunderland role | date=1 April 2013}}</ref> It also met opposition from the [[Durham Miners' Association]],<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tyne-22049080 | work=BBC News | title=Miners' Di Canio protest 'will only end with Sunderland campaign support' | date=6 April 2013}}</ref> which threatened to remove one of its mining banners from Sunderland's [[Stadium of Light]], which is built on the former site of the [[Wearmouth Colliery]], as a symbol of its anger over the appointment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tyneandwear.sky.com/news/article/62109/durham-miners-association-our-issues-with-di-canio-now-resolved |title=Durham Miners' Association: Our Issues With Di Canio At Sunderland Now Resolved |accessdate=2013-04-24 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130625103549/http://tyneandwear.sky.com/news/article/62109/durham-miners-association-our-issues-with-di-canio-now-resolved |archivedate=25 June 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/apr/02/paolo-di-canio-sunderland-miners-banner | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Matthew | last=Taylor | title=Sunderland miners demand return of banner after Paolo Di Canio's arrival | date=2 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nSunderland went on to avoid relegation with one game to go. Di Canio was sacked after a poor start to the 2013\u201314 season, and reports of a complete breakdown in relations with his players.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/paolo-di-canio-was-fired-by-sunderland-for-systematic-destruction-of-his-players-8835606.html|title=Paolo Di Canio was fired by Sunderland for 'systematic destruction' of|date=24 September 2013|work=The Independent}}</ref> [[Gus Poyet]] was announced as his replacement,<ref>{{cite web|author=Dennis, Ian |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24441758 |title=Gus Poyet: Sunderland name Uruguayan as head coach |publisher=BBC Sport |date=8 October 2013 |accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref> and led Sunderland to the [[2014 Football League Cup Final]], where they were defeated 3\u20131 by [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]].<ref>{{cite news|last=McNulty |first=Phil |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26311649 |title=Manchester City 3\u20131 Sunderland |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2 March 2014 |accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref> In March 2015 Poyet was sacked,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31902933|title=Gus Poyet: Sunderland sack manager after crisis talks|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref> and veteran Dutchman [[Dick Advocaat]] was appointed as the club's new head coach,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31919801|title=Sunderland: Dick Advocaat appointed Black Cats boss|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref> saving the club from relegation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32716700|title=Arsenal 0\u20130 Sunderland|author=Phil McNulty|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref> Eight games into the 2015\u201316 season he resigned from the position.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34437620|title=Dick Advocaat: Sunderland boss quits Premier League strugglers|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref> [[Sam Allardyce]] was appointed the next manager in October 2015, and the club was again saved from relegation at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35733486 | title=Sunderland 3\u20130 Everton | publisher=BBC Sport | date=11 May 2016 | accessdate=12 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Back-to-back relegations and sale (2016\u2013present)===\nIn July 2016, Allardyce left the club to be announced as manager for the [[England national football team|English national team]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/12016/10508367/sam-allardyce-appointed-new-england-manager-football-association-confirms|title=Sam Allardyce appointed new England manager on two-year deal|publisher=}}</ref> and former Everton and Manchester United manager [[David Moyes]] was appointed as his replacement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36874200 |title=Sunderland: David Moyes replaces Sam Allardyce as manager |date=23 July 2016 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref> Under Moyes, Sunderland made the worst ever start to a Premier League season, taking just two points from their opening 10 matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/10636619/sunderland-make-worst-ever-start-to-a-premier-league-season|title=Sunderland make worst ever start to a Premier League season|publisher=}}</ref> The club was relegated to the second tier for the first time in 10 years at the end of the 2016\u201317 season, finishing bottom of the table with 24 points,<ref>{{cite news|title=Sunderland 0\u20131 AFC Bournemouth|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39676422|accessdate=29 April 2017|publisher=BBC Sport|date=29 April 2017}}</ref> and Moyes resigned as manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40003697|title=David Moyes resigns as Sunderland boss after relegation from Premier League|date=22 May 2017|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> In June 2017, goalkeeper [[Jordan Pickford]], a product of  Sunderland's academy who joined the club aged eight, was transferred to Everton for a fee of \u00a325 million, rising to a possible \u00a330 million, a record for a British goalkeeper.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40258852|title=Jordan Pickford: Everton confirm \u00a325m, rising to \u00a330m, deal with Sunderland|date=15 June 2017|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nFollowing relegation, [[Simon Grayson]] was announced as the new manager of the club.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/jun/29/sunderland-shelve-takeover-talks-close-preston-simon-grayson |title= Sunderland appoint Simon Grayson as manager after shelving takeover talks |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=29 June 2017 |accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref> Under Grayson, the club made a very poor start to the [[2017\u201318 EFL Championship]] season (which was documented in the [[Netflix]] series ''[[Sunderland 'Til I Die]]''), taking only 2 wins in 14 games. Following a 3\u20133 draw against Bolton, Grayson was sacked,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/oct/31/simon-grayson-sacked-sunderland-manager|title=Simon Grayson sacked as Sunderland manager after draw with Bolton|last=Association|first=Press|date=31 October 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=19 November 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and [[Wales national football team|Wales]] head coach [[Chris Coleman (footballer)|Chris Coleman]] replaced him in November 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.safc.com/news/team-news/2017/november/coleman-named-new-manager|title=Coleman named new manager|date=19 November 2017|publisher=Sunderland A.F.C.|access-date=19 November 2017}}</ref> In April 2018, after a second consecutive relegation, this time to [[EFL League One|League One]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43762308|title=Sunderland 1\u20132 Burton Albion|publisher=BBC Sport|date=21 April 2018}}</ref> the club was sold to a group led by [[Stewart Donald]], the chairman of [[Eastleigh F.C.|Eastleigh]], and Coleman was released from his contract.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/apr/29/chris-coleman-sackedd-manager-sunderland |title=Sunderland sold by Ellis Short as Chris Coleman is sacked |date=29 April 2018 |work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n[[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] manager [[Jack Ross (footballer, born 1976)|Jack Ross]] was appointed as the new manager in May 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44238168|title=Jack Ross: Sunderland name St Mirren boss as new manager|date=25 May 2018 |work=BBC sport}}</ref> In the club's first season in League One they finished 5th and reached the play-off final, but lost to [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] at Wembley. After a disappointing start to the 2019\u201320 season, Ross was sacked in October 2019.<ref>https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11695/11830823/sunderland-sack-jack-ross-as-manager</ref> He was replaced by former Bolton manager [[Phil Parkinson]] on 17 October.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50081814</ref>\n\n==Colours and crest==\n[[File:Sunderland_AFC_cat_badge.jpg|thumb|left|Sunderland's club badge until 1972]]\n[[File:SAFC1972-97crest.svg|thumb|right|upright|Sunderland's club badge, used from 1972\u201397]]\nSunderland played in an all blue [[Kit (association football)|strip]] from their formation until 1884,<ref name=\"History\" /> when they adopted a red and white halved strip.<ref name=\"rokerpark2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.roker-roar.com/pauldays/navbar/redandwhite.html |title=Red and white stripes |publisher=Roker Park |accessdate=19 September 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080603122644/http://www.roker-roar.com/pauldays/navbar/redandwhite.html |archivedate=3 June 2008 }}</ref> They assumed the current strip of red and white stripes in the [[1887\u201388 in English football|1887\u201388 season]].<ref>Days, p 15.</ref> Their badge included a ship, the upper part of the [[Coat of arms of Sunderland|Sunderland coat of arms]], a black cat, and a football in front of Sunderland's red and white stripes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uefaclubs.com/showlogos.php?club=Sunderland%20AFC&logo=5|title=European Football Club Logos|publisher=UEFA Clubs|accessdate=20 December 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002105118/http://uefaclubs.com/showlogos.php?club=Sunderland%20AFC&logo=5|archivedate=2 October 2011}}</ref> In 1972 the badge was changed,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sunderlandecho.com/sport/football/sunderland-afc/sunderland-afc-news/views-divided-on-sunderland-afc-s-new-badge-1-5634662|title=Views divided on Sunderland AFC's new badge|website=www.sunderlandecho.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-17}}</ref> removing the black cat but still including a ship, a football and the background of red and white stripes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uefaclubs.com/showlogos.php?club=Sunderland%20AFC&logo=2|title=European Football Club Logos|publisher=UEFA Clubs|accessdate=20 December 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002105127/http://uefaclubs.com/showlogos.php?club=Sunderland%20AFC&logo=2|archivedate=2 October 2011}}</ref> This badge was first used on the match day shirt in 1977, replacing the simple black 'SAFC' initials which had been used since 1973.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Sunderland/Sunderland.htm|title=Sunderland - Historical Football Kits|website=www.historicalkits.co.uk|access-date=2019-05-17}}</ref> The top section and border of the badge was coloured in blue until 1991, when it changed to black.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nTo coincide with the move from Roker Park to the Stadium of Light in 1997, Sunderland released a new crest divided into four quarters; the upper right and lower left featured their traditional red and white colours, but the ship was omitted. The upper left section features the [[Penshaw Monument]] and the lower right section shows the [[Wearmouth Bridge]].<ref name=\"Presentcrest\">{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/page/ClubCrest|title=SAFC Crest|publisher=Sunderland A.F.C.|accessdate=8 September 2010}}</ref> A colliery wheel at the top of the crest commemorates County Durham's mining history, and the land the Stadium of Light was built on, formerly the [[Monkwearmouth Colliery]]. The crest also contains two lions, the black cats of Sunderland, and a banner displaying the club's motto, ''Consectatio Excellentiae'', which means \"In pursuit of excellence\".<ref name=\"Presentcrest\"/>\n\n==Stadium==\n{{See also|List of Sunderland A.F.C. Grounds}}\n[[File:Roker Park August 1976.jpg|left|thumb|Sunderland's stadium for 99 years, Roker Park]]\n[[File:Safcattendances.JPG|thumb|250px|right|Average match attendances since 1891]]\nSunderland have had eight grounds throughout their history; the first was at [[Blue House Field]] in [[Hendon, Sunderland|Hendon]] in 1879. The ground was close to the place where Sunderland formed, at Hendon Board School; at that time the rent for use of the ground was \u00a310 (\u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|10|1879|r=-2}}|0}} today).{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.safc.com/history/stadiums/blue-house-field |title=Blue House Field, Hendon |date=22 June 2009 |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |access-date=8 September 2010}}</ref> The club then used a number of fields, one of which was near The Cedars road,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.safc.com/history/stadiums/the-cedars|title=The Cedars|work=Sunderland Association Football Club|access-date=6 April 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> before relocating to [[Groves Field]] in [[Ashbrooke]] in 1882 for one season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.safc.com/history/stadiums/groves-field |title=The Grove, Ashbrooke |date=22 June 2009 |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |access-date=8 September 2010}}</ref> The club's third stadium was [[Horatio Street]] in [[Roker]], the first Sunderland stadium north of the [[River Wear]]; the club played a single season there before another move,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.safc.com/history/stadiums/horatio-street |title=Horatio Street, Roker |date=22 June 2009 |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |access-date=8 September 2010}}</ref> this time to [[Abbs Field]] in [[Fulwell, Tyne and Wear|Fulwell]] for two seasons. Abbs Field was notable for being the first Sunderland ground to which they charged admission.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.safc.com/history/stadiums/abbs-field |title=Abbs Field, Fulwell |date=22 June 2009 |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |access-date=8 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nSunderland moved to [[Newcastle Road (stadium)|Newcastle Road]] in 1886. By 1898, the ground reached a capacity of 15,000 after renovations, and its rent had risen to \u00a3100 (\u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|100|1898|r=-2}}|0}} today) a year.{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.safc.com/history/stadiums/newcastle-road |title=Newcastle Road |date=22 June 2009 |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |access-date=8 September 2010}}</ref> Near the turn of the 20th century, Sunderland needed a bigger stadium. They returned to Roker and set up home in [[Roker Park]]. It was opened on 10 September 1898, and the home team played a match the same day against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]],<ref name=\"rokerparksafc\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.safc.com/history/stadiums/roker-park |title=Roker Park |date=22 June 2009 |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |access-date=8 September 2010}}</ref> which they won. The stadium's capacity increased to 50,000 after redevelopment with architect [[Archibald Leitch]] in 1913. Sunderland were nearly bankrupted by the cost of renovating the Main Stand, and Roker Park was put up for sale but no further action was taken. On&nbsp;8 March 1933, an overcrowded Roker Park recorded the highest ever attendance at a Sunderland match, 75,118 against [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] in a [[FA Cup]] sixth round replay.<ref name=\"History\" /> Roker Park suffered a bombing in 1943, in which one corner of the stadium was destroyed. A [[special constable]] was killed while patrolling the stadium. By the 1990s, the stadium was no longer large enough, and had no room for possible expansion.<ref>Days, pp 153\u2013154.</ref> In January 1990, the [[Taylor Report]] was released after overcrowding at the [[Hillsborough Stadium]] resulted in 96 deaths, an incident known as the [[Hillsborough Disaster]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/merseyside/3627261.stm|title=Service marks Hillsborough deaths|date=15 April 2004|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 January 2009}}</ref> The report recommended that all major stadiums must be converted to an all-seater design.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southyorks.police.uk/sites/default/files/foi/significantpublicinterest/hillsborough%20stadium%20disaster%20final%20report.zip|title=Lord Taylor's final report on the Hillsborough stadium disaster (zipped pdf)|author=Lord Justice Taylor|date=January 1990|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=5 January 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330053408/http://southyorks.police.uk/sites/default/files/hillsborough%20stadium%20disaster%20final%20report.pdf|archivedate=30 March 2014}}</ref> As a result, Roker Park's capacity was reduced. It was demolished in 1997 and a housing estate built in its place.<ref name=\"rokerparksafc\" /> [[File:Stadium of Light, Sunderland afc.jpg|thumb|left|250px|The [[Stadium of Light]] has been Sunderland's home ground since 1997.]]\nIn 1997, Sunderland moved to their present ground, [[Stadium of Light]] in [[Monkwearmouth]], which was opened by [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York]]. Built with an original capacity of 42,000, it hosted its first game against Dutch team [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]].<ref name=\"SOL\" /> The stadium bears a similar name to the Portuguese club [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]]'s ground [[Est\u00e1dio da Luz]], albeit in a different language.\n\nStadium expansion in 2000 saw the capacity increase to 49,000. A [[Davy lamp]] monument stands outside the stadium, and a miners banner was presented to the club by the [[Durham Miners' Association]],<ref>{{cite news|first1=Matthew|last1=Taylor|accessdate=2019-08-28|title=Sunderland miners demand return of banner after Paolo Di Canio's arrival|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/apr/02/paolo-di-canio-sunderland-miners-banner|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=2 April 2013|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> as a reminder of the [[Monkwearmouth Colliery]] pit the stadium was built on.\n\n==Supporters and rivalries==\n{{See also|Sunderland A.F.C. league record by opponent}}\nSunderland held the seventh highest average home attendance out of the 20 clubs in the Premier League at the end of the [[2013\u201314 Premier League|2013\u201314]] season with an average of 41,089,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/stats/attendance/_/league/eng.1/year/2011/barclays-premier-league?cc=5739 |title=Barclays Premier League Team Attendance Statistics \u2013 2011\u201312 \u2013 ESPN Soccernet |publisher=Soccernet.espn.go.com |date=13 May 2012 |accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref> and held the sixth highest average attendance in the [[2014\u201315 Premier League|2014\u201315]] season with an average of over 43,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caughtoffside.com/2014/09/12/ten-highest-premier-league-attendances-for-201415-with-arsenal-2nd-liverpool-5th/5/|title=Ten Highest Premier League Attendances For 2014/15, With Arsenal 2nd & Liverpool 5th|work=CaughtOffside|accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref> Sunderland fans often sell out allocations for away games: in the 2013\u201314 season, 9,000<ref name=\"BBC News Online 22 January 2014\">{{cite news |last= McNulty |first= Phil |title= League Cup: Results| url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25740123| date= 22 January 2014| website= [[BBC News Online]] | accessdate= 16 October 2015 }}</ref> Sunderland fans attended [[Old Trafford]] for the second leg of the Football League Cup semi-final, which they won to go through to the final. At Wembley, London was taken over by thousands of [[Mackem]]s, the sights of Covent Garden and Leicester Square were awash with red and white, local shops completely sold out of alcohol but only one arrest was reported by the police.<ref name=\"101 Great Goals 2 March 2014\">{{cite news |last= Newman |first= Benjamin |title= 1000s of Sunderland fans mobbed Covent Garden on Saturday before the Capital One Cup final v Man City| url= http://www.101greatgoals.com/blog/1000s-of-sunderland-fans-mobbed-covent-garden-on-saturday-night-before-the-capital-one-cup-final-v-man-city/| date= 2 March 2014| work= 101 Great Goals | accessdate= 16 October 2015 }}</ref> Support is drawn from across the [[North East England|North East]], in particular [[County Durham]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/newcastle-united/11306241/Newcastle-vs-Sunderland-Why-is-the-Tyne-Wear-derby-such-a-big-deal.html|title=Newcastle vs Sunderland: Why is the Tyne-Wear derby such a big deal?|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=7 October 2015}}</ref> and beyond. The club has many supporter branches across the world, including the United States, Australia, Canada, Cambodia, and Greece.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/news/20050302/supporter-branches_2256213_1710147|title=Supporter Branches|publisher=Sunderland A.F.C.|accessdate=8 September 2010}}</ref> According to [[YouGov]] statistics, supporters of Sunderland predominantly lean to the political [[left-wing|left]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2014/nov/18/you-gov-premier-league-profiles-20-clubs|title=Are you an average fan? Find out with YouGov's Premier League profiles|work=The Guardian|accessdate=7 October 2015}}</ref> and often sing \"[[The Red Flag]]\" during games.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/everton-vs-sunderland-match-report-danny-graham-and-jermain-defoe-fire-black-cats-closer-to-premier-10238451.html|title=Everton vs Sunderland match report: Danny Graham and Jermain Defoe fire Black Cats closer to Premier League safety|author=Tim Rich|date=9 May 2015|work=The Independent|accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nTraditionally, Sunderland's main rivals are Newcastle United, with whom they contest the [[Tyne\u2013Wear derby]]. The club shared a rivalry with the now defunct [[Sunderland Albion]] in the 1880s and 1890s, a breakaway club formed by Sunderland's founder James Allan.<ref name=\"page19\">Days, p 19.</ref> In recent seasons the club has also developed a minor rivalry with [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]], mainly stemming from the clubs meeting each other 5 times in the 18/19 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/sunderland-portsmouth-story-so-far-16284128|title=Sunderland vs Portsmouth: A story of red cards, penalties and a simmering rivalry|first=Sean|last=Tighe|date=16 May 2019|website=nechronicle}}</ref> Conversely, sections of fans share a mutual friendship with Dutch club [[Feyenoord]]; this was developed after Wearside shipbuilders found jobs in Rotterdam during the 1970s and 80s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1724981-7-friendships-between-football-clubs/page/3|title=7 Friendships Between Football Clubs|publisher=Bleacher Report|accessdate=7 October 2015}}</ref> The club also has good relations with [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]], matches between the two clubs being known as the ''[[Friendship Trophy]],'' following good rapport in the [[1985 Football League Cup Final|1985 Milk Cup final]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/what-heck-friendship-trophy-footballs-oddest-closed-cup-competitions|title=What the heck is the Friendship Trophy? Football's oddest closed cup competitions|last=House|first=Future Publishing Limited Quay|last2=Ambury|first2=The|date=2016-04-15|website=FourFourTwo|language=en|access-date=2019-07-16|last3=Engl|first3=Bath BA1 1UA All rights reserved|last4=number 2008885|first4=Wales company registration}}</ref>\n\nThe club had an official quarterly magazine, called the ''Legion of Light'', which season ticket holders received at no cost.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/shop/?page_id=15449|title=Magazine&nbsp;\u2014 Legion of Light|publisher=Sunderland A.F.C.|accessdate=21 September 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080823120217/http://www.safc.com/shop/?page_id=15449|archivedate=23 August 2008}}</ref> It was discontinued in January 2017. One of the club's current [[fanzine]]s is ''[[A Love Supreme (Sunderland)|A Love Supreme]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.a-love-supreme.com/|title=A Love Supreme&nbsp;\u2014 The Independent Sunderland Football Club Fanzine|publisher=ALS Publications|accessdate=19 September 2008}}</ref> Others in the past have been ''It's The Hope I Can't Stand'',  ''It's An Easy One For Norman/It's An Easy One For Given'', ''Sex and Chocolate'', ''Wise Men Say'' and ''The Roker Roar'' (later ''The Wearside Roar'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.a-love-supreme.com/S%20and%20C%20archive/S&Carchive001.htm|title=History of Fanzines|publisher=ALS Publications|accessdate=19 September 2008}}</ref> In recent years, blogging sites such as ''[[Roker Report]]'' have been popular.\n\nThere are over 70 branches of official Supporters' Clubs in [[England]] and around the world, including [[North America]], which started in 2013;<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/charlie-methven-how-sunderland-plan-15683807 | title=How Sunderland plan to chase the American dream| date=16 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2018/11/18/18094711/meet-the-branches-chatting-with-the-sunderland-north-american-supporters-association-nasa |title = Meet the Branches: Chatting with the Sunderland North American Supporters Association (NASA)!|date = 18 November 2018}}</ref> [[Scotland]];<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2019/2/21/18226257/meet-the-branches-och-aye-its-the-newly-formed-scottish-sunderland-supporters-branch |title = Meet the Branches: \"Och Aye!\" - It's the newly formed Scottish Sunderland Supporters Branch!|date = 21 February 2019}}</ref> [[South Africa]];<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2019/5/21/18263424/meet-the-branches-say-sawubona-to-the-south-african-sunderland-supporters-branch | title=Meet the Branches: Say 'Sawubona' to the South African Sunderland supporters branch!| date=21 May 2019}}</ref> [[Germany]];<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2019/3/21/18270693/meet-the-branches-how-fifa12-netflix-convinced-this-fan-to-start-a-german-sunderland-branch |title = Meet the Branches: How FIFA12 & Netflix convinced this fan to start a German Sunderland branch!|date = 21 March 2019}}</ref> a united [[Denmark|Danish]] and [[Ireland|Irish]] Supporters Branch;<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2019/2/26/18237253/meet-the-branches-finding-out-about-the-intriguing-danish-irish-sunderland-supporters-branch | title=Meet the Branches: Finding out about the intriguing Danish & Irish Sunderland supporters branch!| date=26 February 2019}}</ref> a separate [[Dublin]] supporters club;<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2019/2/28/18244360/meet-the-branches-sunderlands-dublin-supporters-branch-flying-the-flag-on-the-emerald-isle |title = Meet the Branches: Sunderland's Dublin Supporters Branch - Flying the flag on the Emerald Isle!|date = 28 February 2019}}</ref> [[Sydney]], [[Australia]];<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2018/9/2/17803722/meet-the-branches-introducing-the-brand-new-sydney-sunderland-supporters-group | title=MEET THE BRANCHES: Introducing the BRAND NEW Sydney Sunderland supporters group!| date=2 September 2018}}</ref> [[United Arab Emirates]];<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2018/11/20/18087306/meet-the-branches-uae-sunderland-supporters-branch-following-the-lads-from-4500-miles-away |title = Meet the Branches: UAE Sunderland Supporters Branch - following the lads from 4500 miles away!|date = 20 November 2018}}</ref> [[Switzerland]];<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2016/3/10/11118984/mackems-abroad-meet-the-swiss-branch |title = Mackems Abroad: Meet the Swiss Branch|date = 10 March 2016}}</ref> and even [[North Korea]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11695/11654819/sunderland-open-new-supporters-club-branch-in-north-korea |title = Sunderland open new Supporters Club branch in North Korea}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/47442923 |title = Sunderland's North Korea fan club: Supporter aims to build fan base|work = BBC Sport|date = 4 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Charitable associations===\n{{See also|Foundation of Light}}\nA charity, the [[Foundation of Light]], is affiliated with the club and helps encourage educational development through football, and offers learning centres in addition to scholarships.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sunderlandecho.com/sport/football/sunderland-afc/sunderland-s-foundation-of-light-launches-north-durham-football-scholarship-1-9071904|title=Sunderland's Foundation of Light launches North Durham Football Scholarship|newspaper=Sunderland Echo|date=19 March 2018|accessdate=20 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Affiliated clubs===\nSunderland have recently created affiliations with several African clubs including Ghana's [[Asante Kotoko SC|Asante Kotoko]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2896/premier-league/2011/07/18/2580268/sunderland-seal-partnership-with-ghana-giants-asante-kotoko |title=Sunderland seal partnership with Ghana giants Asante Kotoko |publisher=Goal.com |date=18 July 2011 |accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref> Egypt's [[El-Ittihad El-Iskandary]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/5745851/bruce-away-form-must-improve|title=Bruce \u2013 Away form must improve|work=SkySports|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref> and South Africa's [[Bidvest Wits F.C.|Bidvest Wits]]. Sunderland also have an affiliation with Belgian side [[Lierse S.K.]], allowing the possibility for young African players who would not qualify for a UK work permit to spend three years with Lierse to gain a Belgian passport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espnfc.com/news/story/_/id/1184672/sunderland-announce-link-with-belgian-side-lierse-sk?cc=5739 |title=Sunderland announce link with Belgian side Lierse SK |publisher=Espn Fc |date=8 October 2012 |accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref> In August 2014, Sunderland announced a commercial partnership with [[Washington, D.C.|Washington D.C.]] based [[MLS]] club [[D.C. United]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/aug/08/dc-united-sunderland-mls-premier-league-partnership |title=DC United and Sunderland announce MLS-Premier League partnership |work=The Guardian |location=London |accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nSunderland were the subject, together with [[Aston Villa FC|Aston Villa]], of one of the earliest football paintings in the world - possibly the earliest - when in 1895 the artist Thomas M. M. Hemy painted a picture of a game between the teams at Sunderland's then ground [[Newcastle Road]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2017/11/21/16681978/the-famous-sunderland-v-aston-villa-painting-that-hangs-in-the-lobby-of-the-sol-a-history-of |title = The famous Sunderland v Aston Villa painting that hangs in the lobby of the SoL - a history of|date = 21 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Thomas Hemy Sunderland v Aston Villa 1895 A Corner Kick.jpg|thumbnail|right|One of the earliest football paintings in the world, Thomas MM Hemy's \"Sunderland v. [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] 1895\" depicts a match between the two most successful English teams of the decade.]]\n\nIn 1973, [[Bobby Knoxall]] recorded \"Sunderland All The Way\" for the [[1973 FA Cup Final]] record.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2009/07/21/9324/end_of_a_north-east_legend|title=End of a North-East legend : News 2009 : Chortle : The UK Comedy Guide|first=Steve|last=Bennett|website=www.chortle.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nSunderland AFC were mentioned in the show [[Auf Wiedersehen, Pet]], in the episode \"[[List of Auf Wiedersehen, Pet episodes|The Girls They Left Behind]]\". In the episode, characters Dennis & Oz go to support Sunderland in [[Li\u00e9ge]] despite being [[Newcastle United|Newcastle]] fans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0516479/|title=The Girls They Left Behind|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998 and following the demolition of Roker Park, playwright Tom Kelly and actor Paul Dunn created a one-man play called \"I Left My Heart at Roker Park\" about a fan struggling with the move and what Roker Park meant for him - the play originally ran in 1997, and had a few revivals since.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2014/8/11/5990401/i-left-my-heart-at-roker-park-roker-report-meets-paul-dunn|title=I Left My Heart In Roker Park|date=11 August 2014|website=Roker Report}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thepauldunn.co.uk/projects/past-projects/2014-2/i-left-my-heart-in-roker-park-by-tom-kelly/|title=I Left My Heart In Roker Park by Tom Kelly|date=13 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishtheatreguide.info/reviews/rokerpark-rev|title=Theatre review: I Left My Heart in Roker Park... (And Extra Time at the Stadium of Light) at Customs House, South Shields|website=British Theatre Guide}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/share-your-stadium-of-light-tales-357411|title=Share your Stadium of Light tales|website=www.sunderlandecho.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, BBC broadcast a six-part documentary named [[Premier Passions]]. It chronicled Sunderland A.F.C. during the [[1996\u201397 in English football|1996\u201397 season]], in which the club was [[Promotion and relegation|relegated]] from the [[Premier League]], the year after winning [[promotion and relegation|promotion]] from the [[Football League First Division]], and the move to [[Stadium of Light]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0364860/plotsummary|title=Premier Passions (TV Series 1998\u2013 ) - IMDb|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/sunderlands-premier-passions-remembered-20-13166765|title=Sunderland's Premier Passions remembered 20 years after fly-on-the-wall TV came to Roker Park|first=James|last=Hunter|date=11 June 2017|website=nechronicle}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Netflix released an eight-part documentary called [[Sunderland 'Til I Die]]. It documented the events around Sunderland A.F.C. during their [[2017-18 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2017\u201318 season]] which saw them relegated from the [[EFL Championship]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/sunderland-afc-netflix-documentary-gets-15064738 |title=Sunderland AFC Netflix documentary gets a release date and a title too |last=Johns |first=Craig |date=26 November 2018 |work=Evening Chronicle |access-date=29 January 2019}}</ref> As a result of the success of the first series, a second season was confirmed, despite opposition from many club members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.businesstimes.cn/articles/117639/20190825/sunderland-til-i-die-season-2-will-happen-despite-club-members-disapproval-to-documentary-series.htm|title='Sunderland 'Til I Die' Season 2 Will Happen Despite Club Members' Disapproval To Documentary Series|first=Business|last=Times|date=25 August 2019|website=Business Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sunderlandecho.com/sport/football/sunderland-afc/latest-sunderland-afc-news/sunderland-til-i-die-everything-we-know-so-far-about-season-two-popular-netflix-series-634112|title=This is when season two of Sunderland 'Til I Die is set to be released|website=www.sunderlandecho.com}}</ref> The opposition was mostly to do with players fearing the series would cause their failures being associated with them for the rest of their careers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/49254051|title=Sunderland: Jack Ross on Netflix, promotion & his legacy|date=9 August 2019|via=www.bbc.com|work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n==Nicknames==\n[[File:BLACK CATS.jpg|thumbnail|left|A Black Cat logo on the exterior of the Stadium of Light]]\nSunderland's official nickname is 'The Black Cats'. The previous nickname, 'The Rokerites', was made redundant after the club left Roker Park for the Stadium of Light in 1997.<ref name=\"nickname\">{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/page/BlackCatsNickname|title=Black Cats Nickname|publisher=Sunderland A.F.C.|accessdate=19 September 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090725202042/https://www.safc.com/page/BlackCatsNickname|archivedate=25 July 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> The new name was decided upon in a public vote that year.<ref name=\"safc.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/the-club/history/black-cats|title=Black Cats Nickname|date=17 July 2012|publisher=SAFC|accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/football/2000/feb/22/newsstory.sport4 Sunderland find new identity as The Black Cats], The Guardian, 22 February 2000</ref>\n\nDespite the nickname being made official only relatively recently, the black cat has been used as an emblem of the club throughout most of its history. Photographs exist of players holding a black cat which made Roker Park its home in the 1900s and 1910s, and which was fed and watered by the football club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ryehillfootball.co.uk/stories/the-original-sunderland-black-cat/|title=The Original Sunderland Black Cat \u2013 Ryehill Football|website=ryehillfootball.co.uk|language=en-US|access-date=19 May 2017}}</ref> The club's first official badge featured a black cat sitting prominently in its centre.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thebeautifulhistory.wordpress.com/clubs/sunderland/|title=Sunderland|date=28 May 2011|work=The Beautiful History|access-date=6 August 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> Since the 1960s the emblem of the Sunderland A.F.C. Supporters Association has been a black cat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.safcsahoe.co.uk/|title=Heart of England Branch|publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. Supporters Association|accessdate=19 September 2008}}</ref> A Sunderland supporter, Billy Morris, took a black cat in his chest pocket as a good luck charm to the 1937 FA Cup final in which Sunderland brought home the trophy for the first time.<ref name=\"nickname\"/> Reference has also been made to a \"Black Cat Battery\", an [[Artillery battery]] based on the [[River Wear]] during the [[Napoleonic Wars]].<ref name=\"nickname\" />\n\nAs well as club nicknames, names have been used to define memorable periods in the club's history. The \"Team of All Talents\" moniker was used during Sunderland's successful period in the 1890s,<ref name=\"History\" /> and Sunderland were known as the \"[[Bank of England]] club\" during the 1950s. This was in reference to the club's spending in the [[transfer market]] at the time, which saw the transfer-record broken twice.<ref name=\"History\" />\n\n==Statistics and records==\n{{main|List of Sunderland A.F.C. statistics and records}}\n[[File:Sunderland AFC League Performance.svg|right|thumb|300px|League positions since 1890\u201391 season.]]\nThe holder of the record for the most league appearances is [[Jimmy Montgomery]], having made 527&nbsp;first team appearances between 1961 and 1976.<ref>Dykes, pp 280\u2013282.</ref> The club's top league goal scorer is [[Charlie Buchan]], who scored 209&nbsp;goals from 1911\u20131925;<ref name=\"soccerbaserecords\">{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/team_records.sd?teamid=2493|title=Sunderland all time records|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=19 September 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080926194651/http://www.soccerbase.com/team_records.sd?teamid=2493#|archive-date=26 September 2008|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Bobby Gurney]] is the record goalscorer over all competitions with 228&nbsp;goals between 1926&nbsp;and&nbsp;1939.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.safc.premiumtv.co.uk.p.preprod.performgroup.com/page/PlayersArticleDetail/0,,10281~1929361,00.html |title=11. Bobby Gurney |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |access-date=8 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407043306/http://www.safc.premiumtv.co.uk.p.preprod.performgroup.com/page/PlayersArticleDetail/0,,10281~1929361,00.html |archive-date=7 April 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Dave Halliday]] holds the record for the most goals scored in a season: 43&nbsp;in the [[1928\u201329 in English football|1928\u201329 season]] in the Football League First Division.<ref name=\"soccerbaserecords\"/> As of October 2014 [[John O'Shea]] is the most capped player for the club, making 100&nbsp;appearances for the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]].<ref name=\"soccerbaserecords\"/>\n\nThe club's widest victory margin in the league was in the 9\u20131 win against Newcastle United in the First Division in 1908. Sunderland's biggest ever win in the FA cup was against Fair field (a non-league team) and the final score was 11\u20131.<ref name=\"page443\"/> Their heaviest defeats in the league were 8\u20130 against [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] in 1911, [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in 1968, [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] in 1982 and [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] in 2014<ref name=\"page443\">Mason, p 443.</ref> Sunderland joined the top division in England, [[The Football League]], in the [[1890\u201391 in English football|1890\u201391 season]] and were not relegated until [[1957\u201358 in English football|1957\u201358]] (a span of 67&nbsp;seasons). In October 2015, Sunderland defeated rivals Newcastle United for the sixth consecutive time, a new record.\n\nSunderland's record home attendance is 75,200 for a sixth round replay FA Cup match against Derby County on 8 March 1933.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stadiumguide.com/rokerpark.htm|title=Roker Park|publisher=The Stadium Guide|accessdate=21 December 2008}}</ref>\n\n=== Record goalscorers ===\n11 Sunderland players have scored 100 goals or more in all competitions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestatcat.co.uk/|title=Sunderland AFC - Statistics, History and Records - from TheStatCat|website=www.thestatcat.co.uk|access-date=2019-01-23}}</ref> They are as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!\n!Name\n!Goals\n|-\n|'''1'''\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Bobby Gurney]]\n|228\n|-\n|'''2'''\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Charlie Buchan]]\n|222\n|-\n|'''3'''\n|{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Dave Halliday]]\n|165\n|-\n|'''4'''\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[George Holley]]\n|159\n|-\n|'''5'''\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Kevin Phillips (footballer)|Kevin Phillips]]\n|130\n|-\n|'''6'''\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Raich Carter]]\n|128\n|-\n|'''7'''\n|{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Jimmy Millar (footballer, born 1870)|Jimmy Millar]]\n|127\n|-\n|'''8'''\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Arthur Bridgett]]\n|116\n|-\n|'''9'''\n|{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Patrick Gallacher|Patsy Gallacher]]\n|107\n|-\n|'''10'''\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Gary Rowell]]\n|103\n|-\n|'''11'''\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Len Shackleton]]\n|100\n|}\n\n===Transfers===\nThe biggest transfer fee Sunderland have ever received for one of their players is \u00a330 million for [[Jordan Pickford]], who moved to [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] on 1 July 2017. This was also the biggest fee Sunderland have received for a player produced by the Sunderland academy. The biggest transfer fee paid by Sunderland is the eventual \u00a317.1 million for [[Didier Ibrahim Ndong|Didier Ndong]], who was bought from [[FC Lorient]] in August 2016.\n\n===Overall===\n*Seasons spent at Level 1 of the [[English football league system|football league system]]: 86\n*Seasons spent at Level 2 of the football league system: 30\n*Seasons spent at Level 3 of the football league system: 3\n*Seasons spent at Level 4 of the football league system: 0\nAs of the [[2019\u201320 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2019\u201320 season]]\n\n==Kit sponsorship==\n\nThe first sponsor to appear on Sunderland kits was Cowie's, the business group of then chairman [[Tom Cowie]], between 1983\u201385.<ref name=\"kit\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/Sir-Tom-gets-own-campus.598289.jp|title=Sir Tom gets own campus!|date=27 August 2002|work=Sunderland Echo|accessdate=8 January 2009}}</ref> The club was sponsored by the [[Vaux Breweries]] between 1985 and 1999, with drink brands such as Lambtons sometimes appearing on kits. Subsequently, the club were sponsored by Sunderland car dealership company Reg Vardy from 1999 to 2007.<ref name=\"kit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/page/Kit|title=Kit History|publisher=Sunderland A.F.C.|accessdate=8 January 2009}}</ref> Sunderland were sponsored by the Irish bookmaker [[Boylesports]], who signed a four-year contract with the club in 2007 estimated to be worth \u00a38&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/sport/arena/a-safe-bet-38737.html|title=A safe bet|work=Irish Examiner|date=1 August 2007|access-date=1 December 2018}}</ref> In April 2010, Sunderland signed a two-year shirt sponsorship deal with [[Tombola (bingo company)|tombola]], a local online bingo company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/news/20100413/tombola-to-become-club-sponsor_2256213_2022672|title=Tombola to become club sponsor|publisher=Sunderland A.F.C.|date=13 April 2010|accessdate=13 April 2010}}</ref> On 25 June 2012, Sunderland announced the strengthening of their partnership with the Invest in Africa initiative, with the initiative becoming the club's shirt sponsor for two years. The project is closely linked with [[Tullow Oil]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/news/20120625/sunderland-steps-up-african-partnership_2256213_2821265|title=- SAFC|work=safc.com|accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref> However, after a year the club announced a new sponsorship deal with South African company [[Bidvest Group|Bidvest]]. On 1 June 2015 Sunderland announced a new sponsorship with [[Dafabet]] to appear on the kits for the following season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/sunderland-afc-announce-new-shirt-9365782|title=Sunderland AFC announce new shirt sponsor will be eGaming operator Dafabet|first=Craig|last=Johns|date=1 June 2015|website=nechronicle}}</ref>\n\nThe first kit manufacturer to appear on Sunderland kits was [[Umbro]], between 1975\u201381. French brand [[Le Coq Sportif]] produced kits between 1981\u201383. [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]]'s first stint as kit manufacturer came between 1983\u201386, before kits from [[Patrick (sportswear)|Patrick]] (1986\u201388), [[Hummel International|Hummel]] (1988\u201394), Avec (1994\u201397) and [[ASICS|Asics]] (1997\u201300). Nike returned between 2000\u201304. [[Diadora]] produced kits for a solitary season, 2004\u201305, and [[Lonsdale (clothing)|Lonsdale]] made kits between 2005\u201307. Umbro returned for five seasons between 2007\u201312, before [[Adidas]] became the club's kit manufacturer for the first time in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Sunderland/Sunderland.htm |title=Sunderland \u2013 Historical Football Kits |publisher=Historicalkits.co.uk |date=3 March 1956 |accessdate=19 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\" }\n|- align=\"center\"\n!Period\n!Kit manufacturer\n!Shirt sponsor\n|- align=\"center\"\n|1975\u201381\n|| [[Umbro]]\n|rowspan=2|{{small|none}}\n|- align=\"center\"\n|1981\u201383\n|| [[Le Coq Sportif]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|1983\u201385\n|rowspan=2|[[Nike, Inc.|Nike]]\n||Cowie\u2019s\n|- align=\"center\"\n|1985\u201386\n|rowspan=5| [[Vaux Breweries]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|1986\u201388\n|| [[Patrick (sportswear company)|Patrick]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|1988\u201394\n|| [[Hummel International|Hummel]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|1994\u201397\n|| Avec\n|- align=\"center\"\n|1997-00\n|| [[ASICS|Asics]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|2000\u201304\n||[[Nike, Inc.|Nike]]\n|rowspan=3| Reg Vardy\n|- align=\"center\"\n|2004\u201305\n|| [[Diadora]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|2005\u201307\n|| [[Lonsdale (clothing)|Lonsdale]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|2007\u201310\n|rowspan=2| [[Umbro]]\n|| [[Boylesports]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|2010\u201312\n|| [[Tombola (bingo company)|Tombola]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|2012\u201313\n|rowspan=5| [[Adidas]]\n|| Invest In Africa\n|- align=\"center\"\n|2013\u201315\n|| [[Bidvest Group|Bidvest]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|2015\u201318\n||[[Dafabet]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|2018\u201319\n||[[Betdaq]]\n|- align=\"center\"\n|2019\u201320\n||[[Children with Cancer UK]]\n|}\n\n==Players==\n{{See also|Category:Sunderland A.F.C. players}}\n\n===First team squad===\n{{updated|1 February 2020|<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.safc.com/players/1st-team|title=1st Team|work=Sunderland Association Football Club|access-date=18 September 2019}}</ref>}}\n{{fs start}}\n{{Fs player |no=1 |nat=SCO |pos=GK |name=[[Jon McLaughlin (footballer)|Jon McLaughlin]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=2 |nat=NIR |pos=DF |name=[[Conor McLaughlin]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=3 |nat=WAL |pos=DF |name=[[Joel Lynch]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=4 |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=[[Jordan Willis (footballer)|Jordan Willis]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=5 |nat=TUR |pos=DF |name=[[Alim \u00d6zt\u00fcrk]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=6 |nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[Max Power (footballer)|Max Power]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=7 |nat=SCO |pos=FW |name=[[Chris Maguire]]|other=}}\n{{fs player |no=8 |nat=NIR |pos=FW |name=[[Kyle Lafferty]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=9 |nat=ENG |pos=FW |name=[[Charlie Wyke]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=11|nat=USA |pos=MF |name=[[Lynden Gooch]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=12|nat=NIR |pos=DF |name=[[Tom Flanagan (footballer)|Tom Flanagan]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=13|nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[Luke O'Nien]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=14|nat=ENG |pos=FW |name=[[Duncan Watmore]]|other=}}\n{{fs mid}}\n{{Fs player |no=16|nat=ENG |pos=GK |name=[[Lee Burge]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=17|nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[Elliot Embleton]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=18|nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[George Dobson (footballer, born 1997)|George Dobson]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=20|nat=WAL |pos=DF |name=[[Declan John]]|other=on loan from [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=21|nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[Ethan Robson]]|other=}}\n{{fs player |no=22|nat=NIR |pos=FW |name=[[Will Grigg]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=23|nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[Grant Leadbitter]]|other=[[Captain (association football)|captain]] }}\n{{fs player |no=25|nat=NZL |pos=DF |name=[[Tommy Smith (footballer, born 1990)|Tommy Smith]]|other=}}\n{{fs player |no=26|nat=AUS |pos=DF |name=[[Bailey Wright]]|other=on loan from [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=28|nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[Josh Scowen]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=33|nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=[[Denver Hume]]|other=}}\n{{Fs player |no=42|nat=ENG |pos=FW |name=[[Antoine Semenyo]]|other=on loan from [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]}}\n{{fs end}}\n\n====Out on loan====\n{{fs start}}\n{{Fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=[[Jack Baldwin (footballer)|Jack Baldwin]]|other=at [[Salford City F.C.|Salford City]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=  |nat=IRE |pos=MF |name=[[Aiden McGeady]]|other=at [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]]}}\n{{fs end}}\n\n===Reserves and Academy===\n{{main|Sunderland A.F.C. Reserves and Academy}}\n\n==Club officials==\n\n===Board of Directors===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Position !! Name\n|-\n|Owner/Chairman || [[Stewart Donald]]\n|-\n|Director/Minority Shareholder (20%) || [[Juan Sartori]]\n|-\n|Executive Director || [[Charlie Methven]]\n|-\n|Finance Director ||  Angela Lowes\n|-\n|Director || Neil Fox\n|-\n|}\n\n''Information correct as of 12 June 2019'' <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.safc.com/players/board-and-management|title=Board and Management|work=Sunderland Association Football Club|access-date=12 June 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===Coaching staff===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Position !! Name\n|-\n|Manager\n| {{flagicon|England}} [[Phil Parkinson]]\n|-\n|Assistant Manager\n| {{flagicon|England}} [[Steve Parkin]]\n|-\n|Head of Recruitment\n| {{flagicon|England}} [[Tony Coton]]\n|-\n|Goalkeeping Coach\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Craig Samson]]\n|-\n|Academy Manager\n| {{flagicon|England}} [[Paul Reid (footballer, born 1982)|Paul Reid]]\n|-\n|Under 23 Head Coach\n| {{flagicon|England}} Elliott Dickman\n|-\n|Under 18 Head Coach\n| {{flagicon|England}} Paul Bryson\n|-\n|Senior Physiotherapist\n| {{flagicon|England}} Peter Brand\n|-\n|Kit Manager\n| {{flagicon|England}} [[John Cooke (footballer born 1962)|John Cooke]]\n|}\n\n''Information correct as of 12 November 2019'' <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.safc.com/players/backroom-staff|title=Backroom Staff|work=Sunderland Association Football Club|access-date=12 June 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Managers==\n{{main|List of Sunderland A.F.C. managers}}\n\n==Honours==\nThe following are the honours Sunderland have achieved since their foundation in 1879.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.safc.com/history/trophy-cabinet |title=Roll of Honour |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |access-date=21 December 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engsupcuphist.html|title=England&nbsp;\u2014 List of FA Charity/Community Shield Matches|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=21 December 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spartacus.schoolnet.co.uk/2WWfootball.htm |title=Football and the Second World War |publisher=Spartacus |accessdate=8 September 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225213503/http://www.spartacus.schoolnet.co.uk/2WWfootball.htm |archivedate=25 February 2009 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===League===\n* '''[[List of English football champions|First Division/Premier League]]: 6 (level 1)'''\n:[[1891\u201392 in English football|1891\u201392]], [[1892\u201393 in English football|1892\u201393]], [[1894\u201395 in English football|1894\u201395]], [[1901\u201302 in English football|1901\u201302]], [[1912\u201313 in English football|1912\u201313]], [[1935\u201336 in English football|1935\u201336]]\n\n* '''[[List of winners of English Football League Championship and predecessors|Second Division/First Division/Championship]]: 5 (level 2)'''\n:[[1975\u201376 in English football|1975\u201376]], [[1995\u201396 in English football|1995\u201396]], [[1998\u201399 in English football|1998\u201399]], [[2004\u201305 in English football|2004\u201305]], [[2006\u201307 in English football|2006\u201307]]\n:'''Promoted via Play Offs''': [[1990 Football League Second Division play-off Final|1989\u201390]]\n* '''[[List of winners of English Football League One and predecessors|Third Division/Second Division/League One]]: 1 (level 3)'''\n:[[1987\u201388 in English football|1987\u201388]]\n\n===Cup===\n* '''[[FA Cup]]: '''\n** '''Winners (2):''' [[1937 FA Cup Final|1937]], [[1973 FA Cup Final|1973]]\n* '''[[FA Community Shield|Charity Shield]]'''\n** '''Winners (1): ''' [[1936 FA Charity Shield|1936]]\n* '''[[Sheriff of London Charity Shield]]:'''\n** '''Winners (1):''' [[1902\u201303 in English football|1903]]\n\n===Other===\n*'''[[BBC Sports Personality Team of the Year Award]]: 1'''\n:1973\n\n*'''[[1895 World Championship (football)|Football World Championship]]: 1'''\n:1895\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|author1=Paul Days|author2=John Hudson|author3=Bernard Callaghan |title=Sunderland AFC: The Official History 1879\u20132000|publisher=Business Education Publishers Ltd|date=1 December 1999|page=336|isbn=978-0-9536984-1-7}}\n* {{cite book|author=Garth Dykes|author2=Doug Lamming |title=All The Lads: A Complete Who's Who of Sunderland A.F.C.|publisher=Polar Print Group Ltd|date=November 2000|page=312|isbn=978-1-899538-14-0}}\n* {{cite book|author=Rob Mason|title=Sunderland: The Complete Record|publisher=Breedon Books Publishing Co Ltd|date=October 2005|isbn=978-1-85983-472-5}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.thestatcat.co.uk|title=Sunderland AFC&nbsp;\u2014 Statistics, History and Records|publisher=The Stat Cat|accessdate=19 September 2008}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.safc.com/history/trophy-cabinet|title=Roll of Honour|publisher=Sunderland A.F.C.|accessdate=21 December 2008}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|North East England|Association football|English football}}\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|Sunderland A.F.C.ogg|2010-09-22}}\n{{Commons category-inline|Sunderland AFC}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.safc.com/}}\n{{BBC Football Info|BBClinkname=sunderland}}\n* [http://www.thestatcat.co.uk Sunderland AFC Statistics]\n* [http://www.answers-to-questions.info/England-Football-Play-Offs.aspx?team=Sunderland Sunderland play-off record]\n* [http://safc.blog/ SAFC Stats and Season Reviews from 1890\u20131891 to date]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/resources/idt-sh/the_last_pass The last pass The role of football clubs in WW1 including Jimmy Seed]\n{{Sunderland A.F.C.}}\n{{Football League One}}\n{{City of sunderland}}\n\n{{Featured article}}\n\n[[Category:Sunderland A.F.C.| ]]\n[[Category:1879 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1879]]\n[[Category:FA Cup winners]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in England]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:English Football League clubs]]\n[[Category:Premier League clubs]]\n[[Category:United Soccer Association imported teams]]\n[[Category:Mining association football teams]]\n[[Category:Sunderland]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: second place \u2192 second-place, \u2019s \u2192 's, 1900-01 \u2192 1900\u201301", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sunderland_A.F.C."}
